INSERT INTO `entry` VALUES (6,'5124718f8aa5a07c7364277c51c58107','2022','talk','Community Assembly of Vertic Clay Endemic Annual Plants of the San Joaquin Desert','The San Joaquin Desert (SJD) supports a high diversity of rare, endemic annual plants notable for their massive floral displays following high rainfall winters, which form a distinctive color patchwork that reflects the heterogeneous pattern of soil texture and salinity across the landscape. These vertic clay soils are physically extreme due to high smectite clay content which causes extensive cracking upon drying, reducing soil moisture access, and creating physical stress for roots. Vertic clay soils in the SJD are also often chemically extreme due to high sodium content, and the species within this community appear highly adapted to vertic clay soils. The combination of a diverse suite of vertic clay endemic species (species pool), extreme physical and chemical soil abiotic factors (habitat filter), and widespread invasion by [[Bromus madritensis]] (competition filter) make this system ideal for studying the factors contributing to plant community assembly. This study aimed to quantify edaphic factors, determining fundamental niche for these species through a reciprocal transplant study of twelve SJD native annuals across three vertic clay soils spanning three orders of magnitude of sodium content. A duplicate set of each species sample was also seeded with [[B. madritensis]] to determine the realized niche of these species. These combined results have informed a preliminary model of the community assembly of the vertic clay endemic flora of the SJD, which includes the different combined and separate effects of both soil chemistry and competition from invasive annual grasses on the species that make up this community.','[{\"name\":\"Fryer, Emma\",\"email\":\"erfryer@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Biological Sciences\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"no\",\"presenter\":\"yes\"},{\"name\":\"Rajakaruna, Nishanta\",\"email\":\"nrajakar@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Biological Sciences\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Faculty\",\"frost\":\"no\"},{\"name\":\"Shon, Alyssa\",\"email\":\"alshon@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Biological Sciences\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"yes\"},{\"name\":\"McKinnon, Skyler\",\"email\":\"snmckinn@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Other...\",\"other_affiliation\":\"Natural Resources Mgt and Environmental Sciences\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"yes\"}]','9:00am-10:30am',NULL,'2022-04-04 17:35:42',1,'9:00-10:45','9-9:15','180-261'),(7,'4fd5654677d998d1fb426dce1535b70c','2022','poster','Online Physical Activity Advice for Older Adults during COVID-19: Results of a Pilot Study','With the ebb and flow of surges in COVID-19 cases, over the course of the pandemic, it is likely older adults have become more reliant on the internet for health advice. Like their younger counterparts, the internet may be one of the first places older adults check for health advice (Berry et al., 2011, Health Communication). This poster presentation will report the results of one pilot to determine the credibility of online physical advice presented to older adults during the COVID-19 pandemic, which was led by Cal Poly students. A rationale for this focus is two-fold: (a) even before COVID many producers of online health information advised to exercise or be active (Thomas et al., 2020, TJACSM) and (b) news outlets, including YouTube dot com, have popularized research showing physical activity is buffers against COVID-19 onset and severity. Pilot data suggests older adults seeking credible advice for maintaining their health during COVID-19 likely receive little advice matching physical activity guidelines through online articles. Students will discuss what their findings suggest be done to ensure the dissemination of credible online health information during a global pandemic.','[{\"name\":\"Russo, Mirabella\",\"email\":\"mirusso@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Kinesiology and Public Health\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"yes\"},{\"name\":\"Thomas, Jafr\\u0101\",\"email\":\"jthoma84@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Kinesiology and Public Health\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Faculty\",\"frost\":\"yes\"},{\"name\":\"Wu, Calvin\",\"email\":\"cwu66@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Kinesiology and Public Health\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"yes\"},{\"name\":\"McIntyre, Abigail\",\"email\":\"ammcinty@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Kinesiology and Public Health\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"yes\"}]',NULL,'We have one already','2022-04-04 22:54:33',1,NULL,NULL,NULL),(8,'dce1aad19049cfddfed2d430d83c874f','2022','poster','Direct Measure of How Well End-users Understand Physical Activity Promotion Material: A Road Less Traveled in Kinesiology: Preliminary Findings of a Rapid Systematic Review','Physical activity promotion material (PAPM) often lack good readability, multiple studies suggest (Thomas et al., 2018, Quest). It appears, however, only one study has directly measured end-user PAPM comprehension (Thomas et al., 2021, Quest). The purpose of this presentation is to report the preliminary findings of a rapid systematic literature review (February-March, 2021), which was done to guide a replication study designed to directly measure end-user PAPM comprehension (2021 Cal Poly BEACoN funded project; Hockert et al., 2021, WSKW Conference Program). To be included, articles must have been peer-reviewed research, written in English, and studied/examined the Cloze methodology vis-a-vis a sample of lay adults and health promotion material. The Cloze methodology is a way to directly measure material comprehension. Of the 954 records identified, six met the criteria for inclusion (M publication date = 2003, SD = 14.1). The present study confirmed it is likely only one study has directly measured PAPM comprehension in a 26-year period (1995-2021). No other study in the articles obtained in this review focused on PAPM. Most articles involved nutrition education. This investigation\'s initial findings suggest little knowledge exists about how well lay adults truly understand PA promotion material routinely given to the public.','[{\"name\":\"Hockert, Regina\",\"email\":\"rhockert@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Kinesiology and Public Health\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"yes\"},\r\n{\"name\":\"Thomas, Jafra\",\"email\":\"jthoma84@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Kinesiology and Public Health\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Faculty\",\"frost\":\"yes\"},\r\n{\"name\":\"Cutner, Emma\",\"email\":\"ecutner@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Kinesiology and Public Health\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"yes\"},\r\n{\"name\":\"Montoya, Ruben\",\"email\":\"rumontoy@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Animal Sciences\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"yes\"}\r\n\r\n]',NULL,'We know how to make one','2022-04-06 01:41:48',2,NULL,NULL,NULL),(11,'5bc8539522311b110e2dbaed5d2258a1','2022','talk','Seasonal controls on nearshore dissolved oxygen variability and hypoxia in a coastal embayment','Declining dissolved oxygen (DO) is emerging as an increasingly important stressor in nearshore ecosystems, and there is a growing need to better understand DO dynamics and hypoxia risk in this highly variable environment. In this study, we collected data from monthly cruises on the inner shelf, continuous nearshore moorings inside and outside a small coastal upwelling embayment (San Luis Obispo Bay in Central California), and weekly phytoplankton measurements inside the bay during the upwelling season. Nearshore DO was generally dominated by low-frequency synoptic variability, with increased DO variance near the surface relative to the bottom and inside the bay compared to outside. Two nearshore hypoxic regimes were identified. In the first regime, which occurred during periods of strong upwelling in the spring across all nearshore sites, the nearshore bottom water temperature-DO (T-DO) relationship was aligned with that found offshore, suggesting hypoxia was driven by the direct advection and cross-shelf exchange of low DO subthermocline waters from the shelf. This period also coincided with minimal water-column stratification, small vertical DO differences, and a diatom-dominated phytoplankton assemblage. In the second regime, which occurred during summer months and was characterized by weaker upwelling, strong stratification, and dinoflagellate-dominated phytoplankton assemblage, the near-bottom T-DO relationship inside the bay deviated significantly from that on the shelf offshore. These hypoxic events inside the bay were likely driven by localized respiration and lack of ventilation of bottom waters due to strong stratification. Collectively, these observations reveal a shift in the strength and magnitude of physical versus biological processes driving nearshore DO dynamics. The high spatiotemporal variability of DO dynamics in upwelling bays means that they are likely to be at the forefront of ecosystem impacts of and adaptions to climate change, and may act as sentinel systems or \'canaries on the coast.\'  ','[{\"name\":\"Abraham, Jon\",\"email\":\"jpabraha@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Physics\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"yes\"},{\"name\":\"Walter, Ryan\",\"email\":\"rkwalter@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Physics\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Faculty\",\"frost\":\"yes\"},{\"name\":\"Huie, Stephen\",\"email\":\"\",\"affiliation\":\"Physics\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"yes\"},{\"name\":\"Pasulka, Alexis\",\"email\":\"apasulka@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Biological Sciences\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Faculty\",\"frost\":\"no\"},{\"name\":\"Davis, Kristen\",\"email\":\"davis@uci.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Other...\",\"other_affiliation\":\"University of California, Irvine\",\"role\":\"Faculty\",\"frost\":\"no\"},{\"name\":\"Connolly, Thomas\",\"email\":\"tconnolly@mlml.calstate.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Other...\",\"other_affiliation\":\"Moss Landing Marine Laboratories\",\"role\":\"Faculty\",\"frost\":\"no\"},{\"name\":\"Mazzini, Piero\",\"email\":\"pmazzini@vims.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Other...\",\"other_affiliation\":\"Virginia Institute of Marine Science\",\"role\":\"Faculty\",\"frost\":\"no\"},{\"name\":\"Robbins, Ian \",\"email\":\"irobbins@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Physics\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Faculty\",\"frost\":\"no\"}]','9:00am-10:30am',NULL,'2022-04-08 14:08:47',8,'9:00-10:45','9-9:15','180-266'),(12,'6868a157b1fc0afb289a2181d2391cc1','2022','talk','Quality Improvement Strategies to Promote Community Health','Health in All Policy recognizes institutional policy as a major cause of health disparity. One area often overlooked concerns inclusive resource material. Numerous studies each year report that health related organizations circulate material with low odds of promoting health literacy (Thomas et al., 2021, Quest). Additionally, healthcare facilities may have policy that requires overly technical language in material, erroneously believing it reduces the risk of malpractice litigation (Watson, 2019, HEC Forum). This presentation\'s purpose is to pitch one idea to curb low quality resource material. We will showcase one such experience that policy could encourage, a short video project by one undergraduate public health student (Jun.-Sep., 2020). The project\'s aims were to (a) present a plain language summary of original research on material quality, (b) engage professionals/students in activities to help them understand common design pitfalls, and (c) prompt them to practice correcting pitfalls. The student performed a reflexive thematic analysis of her experience, and found she developed: (a) multi-media skills, (b) plain language communication skills, (c) anticipation of pitfalls in designing resource material, and (d) use of end-user feedback. This overlaps with Erwin and Brownson\'s essential skills for future public health practitioners (AJPH, 2017).\n','[{\"name\":\"Smith, Caroline\",\"email\":\"csmit247@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Kinesiology and Public Health\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"yes\"},{\"name\":\"Thomas, Jafra D\",\"email\":\"jthoma84@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Kinesiology and Public Health\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Faculty\",\"frost\":\"no\"}]','1:00pm-3:00pm','','2022-04-08 22:21:36',22,'1:00-2:45','1:15-1:30','180-261'),(13,'642c98d1e19ac14e1e7ad112bb78c7a6','2022','talk','Colloidal Covalent Organic Framework Synthesis with Carboxylic Acid Catalysts','Covalent Organic Frameworks (COFs) are traditionally synthesized via solvothermal methods that produce bulk COF powders with limited control over crystallite morphology. This talk examines carboxylic acid catalysts in the synthesis of colloidal covalent organic frameworks (COFs) as an effective means to control particle size. In this study, imine-linked COFs are synthesized via the acid-catalyzed condensation of multifunctional amine and aldehyde monomers. The resulting structures are characterized via techniques including scanning electron microscopy (SEM). Trends in particle morphologies have been discovered from these changes in catalyst acidity. These materials will be further investigated for their efficacy in molecular separations and water purification.','[{\"name\":\"Tran, Donna\",\"email\":\"dtran111@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Chemistry and Biochemistry\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"no\",\"presenter\":\"yes\"},{\"name\":\"Chew, Alyssa\",\"email\":\"achew05@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Chemistry and Biochemistry\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"yes\"},{\"name\":\"Chew, Alison\",\"email\":\"acchew@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Other...\",\"other_affiliation\":\"Department of Materials Engineering\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"no\"},{\"name\":\"Posson, Brendan\",\"email\":\"bposson@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Chemistry and Biochemistry\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"no\"},{\"name\":\"Hamachi, Leslie\",\"email\":\"hamachi@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Chemistry and Biochemistry\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Faculty\",\"frost\":\"no\"}]','10:30am-12:00pm',NULL,'2022-04-09 00:19:47',18,'9:00-10:45','10-10:15','180-270'),(14,'ecaf346d6d397c14793a2a987308a5dd','2022','poster','Life History Traits Drive Island Colonization Success in Angiosperms','Previous studies have found an overrepresentation of plant species with a self-compatible breeding system on islands. This supports the idea that species that do not require another mate to reproduce are more likely to colonize new habitats. Using a global dataset with over 2500 plant species, we tested for interactions and relationships between additional life history traits such as fruit type, life span, floral symmetry, and growth form with breeding system and island colonization. We found that breeding system is the strongest predictor for successful island colonization. Further, interactions between breeding system and the other life history traits can be used to explain the success of certain species on islands that could not be explained exclusively by breeding system data. The findings of this study may provide insight into the evolutionary factors and constraints that impact colonization success in angiosperms.','[{\"name\":\"Forster, Elena\",\"email\":\"elforste@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Biological Sciences\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"no\"},{\"name\":\"Grossenbacher, Dena\",\"email\":\"dgrossen@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Biological Sciences\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Faculty\",\"frost\":\"no\"},{\"name\":\"Zell, Annie\",\"email\":\"azell@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Biological Sciences\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Other\",\"frost\":\"no\"},{\"name\":\"Grady, Erin\",\"email\":\"elgrady@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Biological Sciences\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"no\"},{\"name\":\"Francisco, Erin\",\"email\":\"ekfranci@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Biological Sciences\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"no\"},{\"name\":\"Brooks, Ford\",\"email\":\"fbrooks@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Biological Sciences\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"no\"},{\"name\":\"Melillo, Tommy\",\"email\":\"tmelillo@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Biological Sciences\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"no\"},{\"name\":\"Diorio, Kira\",\"email\":\"kdiorio@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Biological Sciences\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"no\"},{\"name\":\"Gonor, Weston\",\"email\":\"wgonor@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Biological Sciences\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"no\"}]','','We know how to make one','2022-04-09 01:11:59',3,NULL,NULL,NULL),(15,'bbf514b6ee7989d5233b399f6169b6da','2022','poster','MD-SAPT: Python Based Toolkit for Running Symmetry Adapted Perturbation Theory Calculations on Molecular Dynamics Trajectories','Molecular dynamics (MD) can be used to identify important molecular interactions in biomolecular systems and examine how these interactions change over the course of the simulation. To accurately quantify the strength of these interactions, interaction energies between residues can be calculated using correlated electronic structure methods. In this work, we use MDAnalysis for reading the MD data; RDKit and PDBrepair for preparing coordinates, and Psi4 for calculating the interaction energies. Combining several software packages into a single workflow can be challenging. To simplify the workflow, we have created MDSAPT, a python package to manage the entire workflow, including rebuilding residues with the correct charge state to set up the electronic structure calculations.','[{\"name\":\"Lescoulie, Alia\",\"email\":\"alescoul@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Chemistry and Biochemistry\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"yes\"},{\"name\":\"Ringer-McDonald, Ashley\",\"email\":\"armcdona@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Chemistry and Biochemistry\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Faculty\",\"frost\":\"yes\"},{\"name\":\"Yu, Astrid\",\"email\":\"myu27@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Other...\",\"other_affiliation\":\"Compter Science\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"yes\"}]','','We have one already','2022-04-09 01:38:39',4,NULL,NULL,NULL),(16,'e604748bf257d1fc710ec5f2c34ddec9','2022','talk','Are sea otter pups more vulnerable to the effects of oiling?','Given the small geographic range of southern sea otters [[Enhydra lutris nereis]], oil spills currently pose a significant threat to their population. It is already understood that oil contamination worsens the fur insulation in adult sea otters, but no one has investigated how oil affects the lanugo (newborn pelage) found in neonates. To better understand differences in thermal function of sea otter pelts across ontogeny, we measured thermal conductivity and thermal resistance of sea otter pelts in air, in water, and when oiled with crude oil. We tested a total of 39 sea otter pelts across six age classes: neonate, small pup, large pup, juvenile, subadult, and adult. For the pelt thermal conductivity model analysis, age class (p=0.024) and treatment (p<0.001) were significant. The neonatal pelage had a higher thermal conductivity in air (p<0.001) compared to juvenile, subadult, and adult pelage, suggesting lanugo pelts are poorer insulators when dry. Pelt thermal conductivity values in water (p<0.001) and oiled (p=0.009) were higher than the in air condition. The thermal resistance model revealed that resistance differed significantly across treatments (p<0.001), but it did not differ significantly across ontogeny (p=0.48). Overall, dry sea otter fur proved to be the best insulator, followed by wet fur, and oiled fur had significantly reduced thermal function, across all age classes. This study is the first to investigate the effects of oil on sea otter pelage across ontogeny, with a direct comparison to the thermal properties of pelts under normal conditions. Defining age-specific properties of sea otter pelage improves our understanding of the effects of oiling on the thermoregulatory abilities of sea otters.','[{\"name\":\"Riordan, Kate\",\"email\":\"kriord01@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Biological Sciences\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"yes\",\"presenter\":\"yes\"},{\"name\":\"Levin, Emily\",\"email\":\"elevin02@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Biological Sciences\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Other\",\"frost\":\"yes\"},{\"name\":\"Adema, Payton\",\"email\":\"Padema@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Biological Sciences\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Other\",\"frost\":\"no\"},{\"name\":\"Dean, Annika\",\"email\":\"aedean@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Biological Sciences\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Other\",\"frost\":\"yes\"},{\"name\":\"Thompson, Alex\",\"email\":\"athomp52@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Biological Sciences\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Other\",\"frost\":\"no\"},{\"name\":\"Thometz, Nicole\",\"email\":\"nthometz@usfca.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Biological Sciences\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Other\",\"frost\":\"no\"},{\"name\":\"Batac, Francesca\",\"email\":\"francesca.batac@wildlife.ca.gov\",\"affiliation\":\"Biological Sciences\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Other\",\"frost\":\"no\"},{\"name\":\"Liwanag, Heather\",\"email\":\"hliwanag@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Biological Sciences\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Faculty\",\"frost\":\"no\"}]','9:00am-10:30am,10:30am-12:00pm',NULL,'2022-04-09 21:00:32',2,'9:00-10:45','9:15-9:30','180-261'),(17,'8ea556c23e6de90ea45e3d087197a076','2022','poster','Teaching One-Way ANOVA with Engaging NBA Data and R Shiny within a Flexdashboard ','This paper provides introductory statistics instructors the capacity to use engaging NBA data within a web application to either strengthen students\' understanding or introduce the concept of variance and One-Way ANOVA. Using engaging data within the classroom provides context to data that students deem applicable to their lives. This paper not only provides a lesson plan for teaching these concepts but also provides a web application and the engaging NBA dataset if the instructor decides to use the app or the data in another context. The NBA data selected focuses on the debate \"Who is the greatest NBA player of all time?\" By using context students are familiar with and interested in, we are able to get them interested in and further engaged in statistics. ','[{\"name\":\"Sisso, Danielle\",\"email\":\"dsisso@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Statistics\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"yes\"},{\"name\":\"Williams, Dr. Immanuel \",\"email\":\"imwillia@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Statistics\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Faculty\",\"frost\":\"yes\"}]','','We know how to make one','2022-04-10 19:38:31',5,NULL,NULL,NULL),(18,'89cfb1421350e7a8327b0c5fd7b2c3d1','2022','poster','Synthesis of Cathepsin B Inhibitors as a Treatment Targeting Anthrax and Ebola','Historically, infectious diseases have been fought by designing inhibitors targeting the proteins of pathogenic invaders. These inhibitors inevitably lose their effectiveness as the pathogenic organism evolves, leading to drug resistance and calls for new treatment options. Some infectious agents, however, exploit human protein, opening the door to host-orientated treatment strategies. Our project focuses on the inhibition of the human protease Cathepsin B, which is found in the lysosome and is exploited by both Anthrax and Ebola. By repurposing a currently approved drug with weak inhibitory activity, we hope to design an improved inhibitor of Cathepsin B that could serve as a new treatment option against these deadly diseases.','[{\"name\":\"Viswanathan, Neil K.\",\"email\":\"nkviswan@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Kinesiology and Public Health\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"yes\"},{\"name\":\"Gibbs, Julia M.\",\"email\":\"jugibbs@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Chemistry and Biochemistry\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"yes\"},{\"name\":\"Deguara, Salvatore\",\"email\":\"sdeguara@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Chemistry and Biochemistry\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"yes\"},{\"name\":\"Eagon, Scott\",\"email\":\"seagon@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Chemistry and Biochemistry\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Faculty\",\"frost\":\"yes\"}]','','We know how to make one','2022-04-10 22:04:46',6,NULL,NULL,NULL),(19,'c427fabd0e093a928c7e228a0e948c2d','2022','poster','Synthesis of 2-Aminooxazole Inhibitors Targeting Kinase STK16','Protein kinases are a class of enzymes that transfer phosphate groups from ATP to specified substrates, resulting in structural and functional modifications to substrate activity. Cell division, signaling, and metabolism are all affected by the phosphorylation of proteins via post-translational modification by protein kinases. Within the past few decades, protein kinase research has emerged at the forefront of chemical biology as one of the primary areas of interest in drug development. An estimated total of 500 protein kinases exist in the human kinome. However, only a small fraction of these have been subjected to studies regarding biological function and therapeutic targeting. A common practice in determining the function and mechanism of a protein kinase is the synthesis and utilization of small-molecule chemical probes. These inhibitors are targeted towards a specified protein and subsequently elucidate pathways in both healthy and diseased cells. From this verification, the probe can serve as a precursor to a therapeutic drug in combating the disease in question. Our project focuses on the inhibition of kinase STK16, an understudied serine-threonine kinase. STK16 is also known to phosphorylate DRG1 (developmentally regulated GTP-binding protein 1), but the biological consequences of these interactions remain unknown. A recent paper reported the discovery of a STK16 inhibitor that caused binucleation and arrested cell growth in some cancer lines. However, this reported inhibitor was not screened for activity against other families of enzymes and was also found to be a strong inhibitor of mTOR, a kinase known to regulate cell growth. In contrast, another paper reported that kinase-dead STK16 mutants of the HT1080 cell line did not display binucleation, but rather decreased expression of VEGF leading to lower angiogenesis activity. These conflicting results make it clear that a high-quality chemical probe is needed to unravel the biological function of this ubiquitously expressed kinase. ','[{\"name\":\"Klug, Trevan\",\"email\":\"tkklug@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Biological Sciences\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"yes\"},{\"name\":\"Johnson, Kieran\",\"email\":\"hjohns35@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Biological Sciences\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"yes\"},{\"name\":\"Gleason, Cameron\",\"email\":\"cegleaso@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Chemistry and Biochemistry\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"yes\"},{\"name\":\"Schmid, Connor\",\"email\":\"cschmi14@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Chemistry and Biochemistry\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"yes\"},{\"name\":\"Eagon, Scott\",\"email\":\"seagon@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Chemistry and Biochemistry\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Faculty\",\"frost\":\"yes\"}]','','We know how to make one','2022-04-10 22:10:42',7,NULL,NULL,NULL),(20,'c7826da6571a28c57efd38a40b3e903e','2022','poster','Synthesis of Benzoxazole Inhibitors of Kinase CK2','Kinases are enzyme catalysts that allow the transfer of phosphate from ATP to serine, threonine, and tyrosine amino acids of their respective substrate proteins. Although a large number of kinases have been discovered, the biological roles of the majority of these kinases remain unknown. This along with the fact that kinase inactivity has been strongly correlated to a number of human diseases has propelled research into better understanding kinase activity and developing small molecules that target these proteins. Success in targeting kinases is underscored by the fact that there are more than sixty FDA-approved kinase inhibitor drugs, and many studies have demonstrated that protein kinases are one of the most effective protein targets for drug therapeutics.\nDespite the breakthroughs in recent years, kinase potential still remains largely untapped, and a number of calls for contribution have been made. To answer this call, a composition of a public library of kinase activity, called the kinase chemogenomic set (KCGS), was recently disclosed to accelerate the synthesis and screening of drugs targeting kinase activity. With public access to the KCGS, many researchers are leveraging this resource to study biological function and therapeutic potential of many understudied kinases. As a part of this public effort, our group has focused on the synthesis of a benzoxazole compound that targets CK2, a human kinase whose upregulation is associated with several forms of cancer. In developing a procedure for the synthesis of drugs targeting this kinase, we hope to develop a library of potent and selective compounds that can later be screened as potential treatments for human diseases and added to the comprehensive public library of kinase inhibitors.\n','[{\"name\":\"Ganjooi, Kimiya\",\"email\":\"kganjooi@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Biological Sciences\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"yes\"},{\"name\":\"Wong, Chloe\",\"email\":\"cwong141@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Chemistry and Biochemistry\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"yes\"},{\"name\":\"Troftgruben, Mark\",\"email\":\"mtroftgr@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Biological Sciences\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"yes\"},{\"name\":\"Mora, Hannah\",\"email\":\"hamora@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Biological Sciences\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"yes\"},{\"name\":\"Young, Brenden\",\"email\":\"byoung30@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Chemistry and Biochemistry\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"yes\"},{\"name\":\"Eagon, Scott\",\"email\":\"seagon@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Chemistry and Biochemistry\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Faculty\",\"frost\":\"yes\"}]','','We know how to make one','2022-04-10 22:14:07',8,NULL,NULL,NULL),(21,'2ade7c42803cf50aef5268a46904d814','2022','poster','Therapeutics Targeting the Iron Acquisition Systems of Escherichia coli for the Treatment of Urinary Tract Infections','We report the design of novel compounds which are thought to inhibit the iron uptake protein TonB, a protein that is not targeted by any current medication in clinical practice. Iron is essential for bacterial growth and virulence, but the urinary tract is an iron depleted environment. As a consequence, uropathogenic E. coli express multiple redundant iron acquisition systems which are highly upregulated during infection. A number of siderophores (iron chelating molecules) are produced by these systems which are able to extract iron bound to host proteins. The large number and variety of these iron acquisition systems and their upregulation underlines their importance for bacterial survival. While these iron acquisition systems use a variety of siderophores and outer membrane receptors, all of these systems require the TonB inner-membrane protein to transport the iron across the cytoplasmic membrane to the cell interior. Deletion of TonB from uropathogenic E. coli strains has been shown to greatly reduce virulence in a mouse model, demonstrating that TonB is an excellent target for a small molecule inhibitor. Targeting TonB also has the additional benefit of likely being active only in the urinary tract, preserving beneficial strains of E. coli in the gut where iron is more readily available. Additionally, there is no TonB homolog in human cells, thus limiting potential toxicity.','[{\"name\":\"Kaplan, Abigail\",\"email\":\"akapla05@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Biological Sciences\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"yes\"},{\"name\":\"Oldenburg, Bella\",\"email\":\"ioldenbu@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Biological Sciences\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"yes\"},{\"name\":\"Eagon, Scott\",\"email\":\"seagon@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Chemistry and Biochemistry\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Faculty\",\"frost\":\"yes\"}]','','We know how to make one','2022-04-10 22:20:43',9,NULL,NULL,NULL),(22,'fbc2f7fc9d3a17f8bb5b0520672a72ef','2022','poster','Development of Apneustic Breathing in Weddell Seal Pups (Leptonychotes weddellii)','The ability to perform prolonged apnea (breath hold) is a key adaptation in diving mammals. Pinnipeds (seals, sea lions, walruses) are known to practice apnea on land as well as during diving, and the ability to extend breath hold duration tends to increase with ontogeny. These apnea practice moments on land and in the water increase a pup\'s control over its cardiorespiratory system. We examined the development of apneustic breathing in the Weddell seal (Leptonychotes weddellii), a deep-diving species, throughout the dependence period. We hypothesized that both age and early experience in the water would influence the development of apneustic breathing. To test this hypothesis, we characterized the respiratory patterns of known-age Weddell seal pups (n=19) using video footage of pups resting on ice, every 1-2 weeks from 1 week through 7 weeks of age. Eupneic (i.e., normal) respiration rate (breaths/min), presence/absence of apneustic breathing, and apneustic interval (length of breath hold) were quantified for each recording. We found that most animals did not perform apnea until after their first entry into the water, and that apneustic interval was significantly positively correlated with age (r2=0.429, P<0.0001). These results are consistent with early developmental patterns in other pinnipeds, but this is the first study to correlate physiological development with early behavioral experience in the water. Future work will compare similar variables in northern elephant seals, another phocid (true seal) species.','[{\"name\":\"Fiskum, Elise\",\"email\":\"efiskum@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Biological Sciences\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"yes\"},{\"name\":\"Pearson, Linnea\",\"email\":\"lepearson@alaska.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Biological Sciences\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"no\"},{\"name\":\"Weitzner, Emma\",\"email\":\"emmaweitzner82@gmail.com\",\"affiliation\":\"Biological Sciences\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"no\"},{\"name\":\"Petch, Shane\",\"email\":\"petch.shane@gmail.com\",\"affiliation\":\"Other...\",\"other_affiliation\":\"Department of Ecology, Montana State University\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"no\"},{\"name\":\"Rotella, Jay\",\"email\":\"rotella@montana.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Other...\",\"other_affiliation\":\"Department of Ecology, Montana State University\",\"role\":\"Faculty\",\"frost\":\"no\"},{\"name\":\"Schroth-Glanz, Madeline\",\"email\":\"mschroth@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Statistics\",\"other_affiliation\":\"Department of Ecology, Montana State University\",\"role\":\"Faculty\",\"frost\":\"no\"},{\"name\":\"Glanz, Hunter\",\"email\":\"hglanz@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Statistics\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Faculty\",\"frost\":\"no\"},{\"name\":\"Liwanag, Heather\",\"email\":\"hliwanag@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Biological Sciences\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Faculty\",\"frost\":\"no\"}]','','We can attend April 19, 5-6pm','2022-04-10 22:31:19',10,NULL,NULL,NULL),(23,'f8e007c31c19dd0da42882473b0ac3e2','2022','poster','Birds of a Feather: Morphological Adaptations of Birds to Aquatic Environments','Birds are endothermic (\"warm-blooded\") organisms and maintain a constant body temperature independent of their environment. The evolution of feathers gives birds a specialized form of insulation for maintaining internal temperature while also serving as a means of protection and allowing for flight. The environment in which a bird lives impacts the amount of insulation necessary, with aquatic species requiring more protection than terrestrial species due to the higher thermal conductivity of water.  The purpose of this study is to determine the morphological feather characteristics important for maintaining insulation in aquatic birds. We will image feathers using a scanning electron microscope (SEM) to measure the density of barbules (minute barbs projecting from the barb section of a feather) and hooklets (minute hooks connecting feather barbules) in aquatic versus terrestrial birds to determine whether feather structure correlates with a species\' habitat. We hypothesize that increased barbule and hooklet density will allow the feather to trap more air, serving as a more efficient insulator. Therefore, we predict aquatic birds will have higher barbule and hooklet density compared to their respective terrestrial outgroups. This is the first study to systematically investigate the microstructure of bird feathers at a comparative level.  \n','[{\"name\":\"Moylan, Eva\",\"email\":\"emoylan@calpoly.edu \",\"affiliation\":\"Biological Sciences\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"yes\"},{\"name\":\"Repella, Kai\",\"email\":\"krepella@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Biological Sciences\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"yes\"},{\"name\":\"Riordan, Kate\",\"email\":\"kriord01@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Biological Sciences\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"yes\"},{\"name\":\"Adema, Payton\",\"email\":\"padema@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Biological Sciences\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"yes\"},{\"name\":\"Liwanag, Heather\",\"email\":\"hliwanag@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Biological Sciences\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Faculty\",\"frost\":\"yes\"}]','','We would like to attend a workshop but CANNOT attend on Tuesday April 19, 5:10-6pm','2022-04-10 23:18:30',11,NULL,NULL,NULL),(24,'6884c51a93e3aad6eab708828c1d4168','2022','poster','Particle Size Control of Colloidally Synthesized COF-300 Pigments','Covalent organic frameworks (COFs) are an emerging class of porous, crystalline polymers with applications in gas separation and water purification. As novel materials, synthetic optimization is required for improving crystallinity, controlling particle size, and understanding their surface chemistry. These optimizations are essential for producing COFs that can be used in industrial applications such as in carbon capture or as functional pigments. While typically synthesized as a bulk powder, colloidal synthesis improves COF materials\' properties. In this study, we synthesize colloidal COF-300, a 3D imine-linked COF, with five different acid catalysts to determine their effect on the particle size of the resulting material. The samples are confirmed as crystalline with X-ray Diffraction (XRD) and imaged with Scanning Electron Microscopy (SEM) to measure particles. The change in acid catalyst has a visible effect on particle morphology and size, which will be further investigated in subsequent rheology and water purification studies. ','[{\"name\":\"Chew, Alison\",\"email\":\"acchew@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Other...\",\"other_affiliation\":\"Department of Materials Engineering\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"no\"},{\"name\":\"Posson, Brendan\",\"email\":\"bposson@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Chemistry and Biochemistry\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"no\"},{\"name\":\"Ottoes, Sachi\",\"email\":\"sottoes@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Chemistry and Biochemistry\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"yes\"},{\"name\":\"Hamachi, Leslie\",\"email\":\"hamachi@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Chemistry and Biochemistry\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Faculty\",\"frost\":\"no\"}]','','We have one already','2022-04-11 19:00:38',12,NULL,NULL,NULL),(25,'9d2fb5bfe022366367ea3ccd12bfb834','2022','poster','Synthesis of Isoflavones as New Treatments for Leishmaniasis','Leishmaniasis is a disease caused by several species of Leishmania parasites and presents a number of infection types, including the disfiguring cutaneous and mucocutaneous forms, as well as the visceral form, which is fatal if untreated. Leishmaniasis is recognized as a neglected global infectious disease and has been prioritized by the World Health Organization (WHO) and the Drugs for Neglected Diseases Initiative (DNDi). Leishmaniasis is spread by infected sandflies, and it is estimated that there are 600,000 to 1 million infections each year with more than 600 million people at risk across the globe. Despite the prevalence of leishmaniasis, the only available treatments are very toxic (such as antimony-based drugs) and have poor clinical profiles (severe side effects, require I.V. administration, declining effectiveness due to resistance, etc.). We report a new project to develop and advance a new class of orally available drugs to treat leishmaniasis (antileishmanials) through the pre-clinical pipeline as an interdisciplinary collaboration between Cal Poly, Oregon Health & Science University, and the University of Kentucky School of Pharmacy. ','[{\"name\":\"Weckerle, Julia\",\"email\":\"jubaptis@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Biological Sciences\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"no\"},{\"name\":\"Benavides, Kennedy\",\"email\":\"kebenavi@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Biological Sciences\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"no\"},{\"name\":\"Fardanesh, Blake\",\"email\":\"bfardane@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Biological Sciences\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"no\"},{\"name\":\"Shields, Maya\",\"email\":\"mshiel03@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Chemistry and Biochemistry\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"no\"},{\"name\":\"Eagon, Scott\",\"email\":\"seagon@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Chemistry and Biochemistry\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Faculty\",\"frost\":\"no\"}]','','We know how to make one','2022-04-12 17:37:08',13,NULL,NULL,NULL),(26,'bca685abd93907ed329e49828527bccf','2022','poster','Characterizing the Numerical Range of Block Toeplitz Operators','The numerical range of an operator $A$ on a complex Hilbert space $\\mathcal{H}$ is the subset of the complex plane defined by $W(A)=\\{\\langle Av,v \\rangle: v \\in \\mathcal{H}, ||v|| = 1\\}.$ Let $\\phi$ be a bounded analytic matrix-valued function on the unit disc $\\mathbb{D}$. The block Toeplitz operator of symbol $\\phi,$ denoted $T_{\\phi},$ is defined by $T_{\\phi}f(z)=\\phi(z)f(z)$ for a function $f$ on the vector-valued Hardy Hilbert space. A theorem of Bebiano and Spitkovsky states that the closure of the numerical range of a general analytic block Toeplitz operator is the convex hull of the set of numerical ranges $\\{W(\\phi(z)): |z|=1\\}$. We have restricted our research to $W(T_{\\phi})$ where $\\phi(z) = A_0 + zA_1$. Even in this case, a wide variety of shapes is possible. We have several results describing the numerical range of block Toeplitz operators when the blocks are $2\\times2$ matrices. These include separate results about $W(T_{\\phi})$ when $A_0$ is the zero matrix, when the $W(\\phi(z))$ sets are nested, and when the boundary of $W(T_{\\phi})$ has flat portions.','[{\"name\":\"Randell, Brooke\",\"email\":\"brandell@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Mathematics\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"yes\"},{\"name\":\"Lara, Mav\",\"email\":\"mzlara@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Mathematics\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"yes\"},{\"name\":\"Patton, Linda\",\"email\":\"lpatton@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Mathematics\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Faculty\",\"frost\":\"yes\"}]','','We have one already,We know how to make one','2022-04-12 21:47:55',14,NULL,NULL,NULL),(28,'ea5aba7a8a2c179f58c18c5bed441207','2022','talk','Designing a Replication Study on Comprehension of Physical Activity Promotional Material in Kinesiology: Lessons from the Field  ','Physical activity promotion material (PAPM) often lacks good readability, multiple studies have suggested (Thomas et al., 2021, Quest). Our 2021 rapid systematic literature review confirmed that only one study has directly measured how well end-users understand PAPM, which was published over 25 years ago (Hockert et al., 2021, WSKW Conference). This 2021 Cal Poly BEACoN and FROST-supported project aims to replicate that study done 25 years ago, using methodology for systematic replication research. The purpose of the presentation is to discuss the current milestones of this replication project. This presentation will provide pertinent background knowledge, literature review design and results, methods for designing the replication study, and student insight on learning opportunities through hands-on research. Milestones we will illustrate and discuss include the following benchmarks: (a) selection of mock web material which tests PAPM comprehension at different reading grade levels (i.e., at lay adult comfort level [8th grade] versus above comfort level [11th grade]), (b) adaptation of the comprehension question to an online, asynchronous platform (enhancing study access), (c) experience with developing IRB protocol to the study (conditional approval obtained), (d) and planned next step with piloting our materials.','[{\"name\":\"Hockert, Regina\",\"email\":\"rhockert@calpoly.edy\",\"affiliation\":\"Kinesiology and Public Health\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"yes\",\"presenter\":\"yes\"},{\"name\":\"Emma, Cutner\",\"email\":\"ecutner@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Kinesiology and Public Health\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"no\"},{\"name\":\"Montoya, Ruben\",\"email\":\"rumontoy@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Biological Sciences\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"yes\"},{\"name\":\"Jafra, Thomas\",\"email\":\"jthoma84@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Kinesiology and Public Health\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Faculty\",\"frost\":\"yes\"}]','9:00am-10:30am,1:00pm-3:00pm',NULL,'2022-04-13 01:01:44',20,'9:00-10:45','10:30-10:45','180-270'),(29,'09c73e7efce92e49229557ce3443e490','2022','poster','Characterization of plankton communities via epifluorescence microscopy','Planktonic communities (i.e., phytoplankton and microzooplankton) make up the base of marine food webs. In coastal ecosystems, these communities exhibit variations in composition and abundance over seasonal timescales in response to upwelling and relaxation events, and over interannual timescales in response to large-scale climate variability and climate change. However, the ability to detect variations in plankton composition is method dependent. Our current understanding of planktonic communities along the central coast comes from samples analyzed by light microscopy. Epifluorescence microscopy offers several advantages over traditional light microscopy including the ability to detect smaller size classes of plankton and the ability to distinguish between autotrophic and heterotrophic plankton. In order to capture these key elements of the community, we collected weekly plankton samples for epifluorescence microscopy in conjunction with our light microscopy samples from September through December of 2021 at the Cal Poly Pier in San Luis Bay, California. These samples were imaged using an Axio Observer Z1 inverted epifluorescence microscope. Our work has focused on learning image analysis using an open-source MATLAB-based program and developing a data-analysis pipeline (in RStudio) to effectively characterize the planktonic community from these images. The results from our analysis will direct future sampling efforts to more effectively characterize the entire planktonic community and provide insight into which components of the community may have been overlooked in previous studies. ','[{\"name\":\"Hupe, Emily\",\"email\":\"ehupe@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Biological Sciences\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"no\"},{\"name\":\"Gammal, Nick\",\"email\":\"ngammal@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Biological Sciences\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"no\"},{\"name\":\"Lord, Sarah\",\"email\":\"smlord@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Biological Sciences\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"no\"},{\"name\":\"Pasulka, Alexis\",\"email\":\"apasulka@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Biological Sciences\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Faculty\",\"frost\":\"no\"}]','','We know how to make one','2022-04-13 01:15:38',15,NULL,NULL,NULL),(30,'1a9aa754e426ad41bc7ac23f1800ea7b','2022','poster','Topological Data Analysis of Emergent Patterning within Embryonic Pluripotent Stem Cells','Stem cells\' potential has prompted remarkable advances in regenerative medicine and in vitro diagnostics. Transitions in early development from pluripotent stem cell systems to differentiated, structurally-ordered tissue provide an ideal testbed to study generalizable properties of cellular coordination. While methods for quantifying self-organization are limited to manual inspection or global measures in many applications, our novel approach utilizes tools from topological data analysis to provide summary statistics describing patterns on both microscopic and macroscopic scales.','[{\"name\":\"Bialozynski, Laura\",\"email\":\"lbialozy@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Mathematics\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"yes\"},{\"name\":\"Green, Jaxon\",\"email\":\"jsgreen@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Mathematics\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"yes\"},{\"name\":\"Newsome-Slade, Vanessa\",\"email\":\"vnewsome@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Mathematics\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"yes\"},{\"name\":\"Wessel, Stephen\",\"email\":\"swessel@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Mathematics\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"yes\"},{\"name\":\"Dimitrova, Elena\",\"email\":\"edimitro@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Mathematics\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Faculty\",\"frost\":\"no\"},{\"name\":\"Anderson, Paul\",\"email\":\"pander14@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Other...\",\"other_affiliation\":\"Computer Science\",\"role\":\"Faculty\",\"frost\":\"no\"}]','','We have one already,We know how to make one','2022-04-13 04:35:24',16,NULL,NULL,NULL),(31,'1c0396bab7492465298636c4a9684170','2022','talk','Analysis of Post-Eradication Transitions and Dynamics of Santa Cruz Island Vegetation Communities ','My long-term project is to analyze vegetation dynamics on Santa Cruz Island (SCI), California over a 32 year period (1991 - 2023). The island has experienced two major animal grazing events (sheep and pigs) that had a large effect on vegetation dynamics. Subsequent removal of these herbivores resulted in a recovery period for native species, and an expansion of the invasive plants. Along with historical disturbances, the island is also expected to be subjected to longer term changes in climate. There are going to be pronounced as well as subtle changes in the vegetation. In the 1990s one hundred plots were established to monitor changes in vegetation cover over time. My research will resample these 100 plots in 2022-2023. With these data, I will look at changes in diversity, composition and structure of the plant communities. Beyond SCI, I anticipate that my approach can be used as a model for assessing vegetation dynamics and management strategies in island systems in many parts of the world as well as mainland areas where vegetation has undergone alteration from overgrazing. ','[{\"name\":\"Meeder, Annie\",\"email\":\"aemeeder@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Biological Sciences\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"no\"},{\"name\":\"Yost, Jenn\",\"email\":\"jyost@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Biological Sciences\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Faculty\",\"frost\":\"no\"},{\"name\":\"Klinger, Rob\",\"email\":\"rcklinger@usgs.gov\",\"affiliation\":\"Biological Sciences\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Faculty\",\"frost\":\"no\"}]','9:00am-10:30am','','2022-04-13 16:49:59',3,'9:00-10:45','9:30-9:45','180-261'),(32,'b04834ee692a340247af7dfff9cf04ae','2022','poster','Using Fourier Analysis to Separate Musical Instruments from a Mixed Recording','The technique of \"audio extraction\" is on the cutting edge of mixing and recording technology, but there is still a lot of room for improvement and innovation in this area. The purpose of this project is to produce a single example of this process, and to calculate how accurate an extraction of two individual instruments from a mixed recording can be. The Fourier transforms of several flute and guitar recordings are analyzed, and the mathematical properties of the distinct timbres are defined. A system of equations is devised, and a mixed recording of both guitar and flute is shown as a linear combination of these two distinct sounds.','[{\"name\":\"Brode, John\",\"email\":\"jpbrode@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Mathematics\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"no\"},{\"name\":\"Choboter, Paul\",\"email\":\"pchobote@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Mathematics\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Faculty\",\"frost\":\"no\"}]','','We know how to make one','2022-04-13 17:32:24',17,NULL,NULL,NULL),(33,'6042f7e24c22d123e0451418c0cf2bbb','2022','poster','Quantitation of Phthalates in Microplastics Found in Morro Bay National Estuary','Consumer plastic products are manufactured with plasticizer compounds such as phthalates to increase their flexibility and pliability. Phthalates are endocrine disruptors that mimic estrogen and negatively affect the reproductive systems of aquatic wildlife when they enter the marine ecosystem through microplastics. Here we developed an analytical method for the extraction and quantification of phthalates in microplastics collected from San Luis Obispo county beaches. Specifically, microplastics were dissolved in organic solvents, sonicated, purified, and analyzed by gas chromatography-mass spectrometry (GC-MS). Our results indicated that wildlife in San Luis Obispo are being exposed to phthalates at detectable levels, which may be playing a role in recent ecosystem changes. It was also found that analysis by GC-MS is an effective method for detecting and quantifying phthalates from beach sediment microplastic samples.','[{\"name\":\"Carrick, Sean\",\"email\":\"skcarric@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Chemistry and Biochemistry\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"no\"},{\"name\":\"Thibault, Kelsey\",\"email\":\"kthibaul@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Chemistry and Biochemistry\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"no\"},{\"name\":\"Lehr, Corinne\",\"email\":\"clehr@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Chemistry and Biochemistry\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Faculty\",\"frost\":\"no\"}]','','We would like to attend a workshop but CANNOT attend on Tuesday April 19, 5:10-6pm','2022-04-13 18:32:18',18,NULL,NULL,NULL),(34,'f4e270f516a79d1ccd5a69752178b93d','2022','talk','Synthesis of Novel Polymer for Vesicle-Hydrogel Drug Delivery Systems','In order for drugs to be effective, they must efficiently be transported from the site it was introduced to the site of infection. Drug delivery systems are constantly being innovated to improve targeting and release. Particularly at focus are hydrogels, which give off an uncontrollable burst release of a drug, and vesicles which are not locationally stable. The research presented combines these two methods of delivery to mitigate their disadvantages. Supramolecular amphiphiles were synthesized and self-assembled into vesicles when put in an aqueous solution. These vesicles are capable of a sustained payload release, and will be  cross-linked by a synthesized silyl-ether acid sensitive polymer into a hydrogel. This vesicle-hydrogel drug delivery system allows for a stable, sustained release of two payloads at particular environments. Here we present our work toward synthesizing the acid-labile 4-arm PEG. ','[{\"name\":\"Cordova, Raul\",\"email\":\"recordov@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Chemistry and Biochemistry\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"yes\"},{\"name\":\"Ward, Sandra\",\"email\":\"sward07@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Chemistry and Biochemistry\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Faculty\",\"frost\":\"yes\"}]','9:00am-10:30am','','2022-04-13 18:54:14',13,'9:00-10:45','10:15-10:30','180-266'),(35,'df02a2ebda296715f47454b52767951d','2022','poster','A Socio-Ecological Perspective: Supports and Barriers Facing Female Officials ','Today, social forces continue to marginalize women, as well as some men, with the hopes of recreating a male-dominated society. In this study, researchers are evaluating the supports and barriers facing female officials in sports using the socio-ecological model. Due to the lack of published research concentrating on female officials, articles focusing on female coaches will be utilized. Many similarities lie between female coaches and officials as they are both women of power in sports. A study conducted by LaVoi and Dutove (2012) used the socio-ecological model to identify the supports and barriers assisting woman in entering, maintaining, or exiting the coaching industry. As LaVoi and Dutove progressed through the levels of the socio-ecological model, the number of supports decreased while the barriers increased. Until finally, the societal level identified zero supports for female coaches. The researchers conducted a qualitative study by interviewing multiple female and male high school officials asking questions about their overall experience. This study hopes to fill gaps in the literature by solidifying previous findings and discovering more evidence on the supports and barriers facing female officials. In a world where women continued to be underrepresented, this study will allow organizations to recognize how they can improve their environments to support women in officiating. ','[{\"name\":\"Cranston, Catherine\",\"email\":\"cgcranst@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Kinesiology and Public Health\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"yes\"},{\"name\":\"Maurice, Stefanee\",\"email\":\"somauric@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Kinesiology and Public Health\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Faculty\",\"frost\":\"yes\"},{\"name\":\"Halbrook, Meghan\",\"email\":\"mhalbrooke@randolphcollege.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Kinesiology and Public Health\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Other\",\"frost\":\"no\"}]','','We know how to make one','2022-04-13 20:26:26',19,NULL,NULL,NULL),(36,'2421dccef216d9586a728958ec2b868d','2022','talk','Detecting and Sorting Alpha Accompanied Ternary Fission in the NIFFTE TPC','The Neutron Induced Fission Fragment Tracking Experiment (NIFFTE) is a MICROMEGAS Time Projection Chamber (TPC) used to detect nuclear fission events induced by a pulsed beam from the Los Alamos Neutron Science Center (LANSCE). While most fission events are binary, involving a nucleus breaking into two charged fragments, there is a chance of ternary fission when three charged fragments are produced, typically including an alpha particle. To sort these rare alpha ternary events from NIFFTE experimental data on a U238/U235 target, a Hough Transform is applied for track reconstruction and a series of cuts are made on the tracks, such as a distance of closest approach (DCA) test. The candidate tracks are then sorted into populations based on their length and energy deposited within the TPC gas, and visually sorted. Current status on the effectiveness of the sorting algorithm and ternary to binary fission counts will be presented.','[{\"name\":\"Androski, Nick\",\"email\":\"nandrosk@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Physics\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"no\"},{\"name\":\"Klay, Jennifer\",\"email\":\"jklay@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Physics\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Faculty\",\"frost\":\"no\"}]','9:00am-10:30am,10:30am-12:00pm','','2022-04-13 20:37:39',9,'9:00-10:45','9:15-9:30','180-266'),(37,'511f8ee6eaa7b0d6606281046d345d33','2022','poster','Fostering resiliency in California\'s urban forests: Suitability of California\'s urban tree species to current and future climates','Climate change has the potential to negatively affect the productivity and health of California\'s urban forests. To maintain the overall health of California\'s urban forests as the climate changes, foresters must plant species that will be well suited for both current and future climatic conditions. While some studies have outlined methods for selecting climate-ready trees or begun initial field trials to assess a small number of species, there are currently no easy-to-use resources to help guide foresters in selecting species that may be suitable for California\'s future climate. Our project aims to meet this need by (1) identifying the 200 most planted trees in California, (2) using species distribution modeling to assess both the current and future suitability of these target species in all 24 Sunset climate zones in California, and (3) providing straight-forward and zone-specific climate change resiliency grades for each of these species on SelecTree, an online and interactive tree selection tool. I am working to identify the native ranges of the 200 target species and find/create shape files for each, which will allow us to gather climate data on the native habitat of each species. We can then compare the native climates to the climate in each of California\'s 24 Sunset zones and use models to predict future suitability. These efforts will help guide foresters in making selections that will foster resiliency in California\'s urban forests in the future, and, ultimately, will maximize ecosystem services and minimize maintenance and removal costs as the climate continues to change.','[{\"name\":\"Grady, Erin \",\"email\":\"elgrady@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Biological Sciences\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"yes\"},{\"name\":\"Love, Natalie\",\"email\":\"nllove@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Biological Sciences\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Faculty\",\"frost\":\"yes\"},{\"name\":\"Ritter, Matt\",\"email\":\"mritter@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Biological Sciences\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Faculty\",\"frost\":\"no\"},{\"name\":\"Yost, Jenn\",\"email\":\"jyost@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Biological Sciences\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Faculty\",\"frost\":\"no\"}]','','We know how to make one','2022-04-13 22:08:22',20,NULL,NULL,NULL),(38,'bc27865dcd656922d4433e19003a661f','2022','poster','Development of an Orally Delivered Vaccine Against Coronaviruses','Porcine Epidemic Diarrhea Virus (PEDV) is a coronavirus that causes gastroenteritis and transmits quickly between pigs via fomites, feces, and windborne exposure. PEDV is most harmful to newborn piglets since their immune system is not fully established. Mortality rates of PEDV-infected piglets are between 50% and 100%, and this has a significant economic impact for the pig industry with an estimate anywhere between 900 million and 1.9 billion dollars in annual revenue loss. There is a need to develop highly effective vaccine against PEDV. Our study investigates the efficacy of an orally administered, spike protein-expressing corn vaccine against PEDV. We have successfully transformed spike protein into corn, evaluated the expression level using Western blotting technique, and grown the corn in the greenhouse. The corn was collected, grounded into corn meal, and fed to pregnant dams. Newborn piglets were challenged with PED virus at the age of 3-5 days and the level of serum neutralizing antibodies as well as the level of IgA antibodies in fecal samples was evaluated. We concluded that our novel corn-based oral vaccine provides protection to piglets when challenged with PED virus and elicits an immune response.  In addition, production costs and heat stability components of a maize-based vaccine make it favorable compared to current vaccines on the market. \n\n\n\n\n\n\n','[{\"name\":\"Maj, Magdalena\",\"email\":\"mmaj@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Biological Sciences\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Faculty\",\"frost\":\"yes\"},{\"name\":\"Williams, Jenna\",\"email\":\"jwill160@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Biological Sciences\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"no\"},{\"name\":\"Blanchard, Nate\",\"email\":\"nblancha@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Biological Sciences\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"no\"},{\"name\":\"Iturribarria, Luis\",\"email\":\"luisiturriuniv@gmail.com\",\"affiliation\":\"Biological Sciences\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"no\"},{\"name\":\"Pogue, Jacob\",\"email\":\"jrpogue@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Biological Sciences\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"no\"}]','','We have one already','2022-04-13 23:06:56',21,NULL,NULL,NULL),(39,'6f271070de0f300c388ede4895416877','2022','talk','Developmental abnormalities in [[Strongylocentrotus purpuratus]] with gametic exposure to microplastics','Growing awareness of microplastics have catalyzed increased scientific interest in the effects of microplastics on marine organisms. Using <i>Strongylocentrotus purpuratus</i> as a model organism, we examine the effects of pre-fertilization exposure to microplastics on fertilization and development. Sea urchin gametes were exposed to low (0.1 mg/L) or high (1.0 mg/L) concentrations of either polymethyl methacrylate or polyethylene before fertilization. The effects of pre-fertilization exposure were isolated based on gamete, concentration, and plastic type. No significant differences in percent normal fertilization were found. Furthermore, no significant differences were found in development 24 hours after fertilization. Embryos whose eggs were exposed to high concentrations of polyethylene saw significantly more developmental abnormalities than the control 48 hours after fertilization (p = 0.003). Furthermore, after 48 hours, eggs exposed to higher levels of polyethylene had significantly higher rates of developmental abnormality than eggs exposed to lower levels of polyethylene (p = 0.031). Polyethylene in high concentrations was significantly more harmful than polymethyl methacrylate in low concentrations across gametes (p values range from 0.02 to 0.04 based on gamete breakdown). At the time of presentation, I will also have data on the effects of polyethylene fibers compared to spheres.','[{\"name\":\"Sarin, Audrey\",\"email\":\"ausarin@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Biological Sciences\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"yes\"},{\"name\":\"Adams, Nikki\",\"email\":\"nadams@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Biological Sciences\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Faculty\",\"frost\":\"yes\"}]','9:00am-10:30am,10:30am-12:00pm,1:00pm-3:00pm',NULL,'2022-04-14 00:09:56',4,'9:00-10:45','9:45-10','180-261'),(40,'f4d6e9c0d24164e562395d884c4fc2ec','2022','poster','Insignificant effects of feeding on IGF-1 levels in ball pythons (Python regius)','Pythons are infrequent eaters with a wide variability in meal size and timing between meals. This can result in variability in processes that depend on increases in nutrients such as growth. Insulin-like growth factor 1 (IGF-1) is a hormone found in all vertebrates that plays a role in the regulation of both cellular growth and metabolism. In reptiles, IGF-1 is sensitive to environmental conditions as well as resource availability. In ball pythons (Python regius) there is an increase in neural cell proliferation six days after feeding, but the signaling molecules involved with stimulating this increase in proliferation are unknown. The goal of this study is to investigate plasma IGF-1 levels in response to feeding and to determine whether IGF-1 is related to the proliferation of neural tissue. We collected plasma samples from ball pythons that were fasted or fed two or six days before sampling. Plasma IGF-1 levels were measured using a sandwich ELISA assay. There was not a significant difference between the plasma IGF-1 levels among pythons that were fasted, two days after feeding, and six days after feeding. There must be involvement of binding proteins or signaling molecules other than IGF-1 that facilitate the observed growth in pythons as a result of their variable feeding patterns.','[{\"name\":\"Langmead, Aveline\",\"email\":\"alangmea@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Biological Sciences\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"yes\"},{\"name\":\"Stayner, Katherine\",\"email\":\"kstayner@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Biological Sciences\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"yes\"},{\"name\":\"Habroun, Stacy\",\"email\":\"sshabroun@gmail.com\",\"affiliation\":\"Biological Sciences\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Other\",\"frost\":\"no\"},{\"name\":\"Strand, Christy\",\"email\":\"cstrand@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Biological Sciences\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Faculty\",\"frost\":\"no\"}]',NULL,'We would like to attend a workshop but CANNOT attend on Tuesday April 19, 5:10-6pm','2022-04-14 00:11:48',22,NULL,NULL,NULL),(41,'176c9a7717e6096b12fd81d82ee383b3','2022','talk','Designing Messages to Promote E-cigarette Prevention Policies','E-cigarettes have become more popular among youth over the last decade. E-cigarette control policies may be beneficial in reducing use of e-cigarettes, particularly among highly impacted groups. The aim of this study was to test theory-based messages designed to increase support for e-cigarette control policies. Participants completed a survey where they were exposed to one of three groups: 1) attitudes-based messages, 2) subjective norms-based messages, and 3) control messages. Findings showed that the attitudes-based message group was significantly related to a higher perceived effectiveness score compared to the control group. The attitudes-based message group was positively related to higher support for taxing e-cigarettes compared to the control group. The results of this study will inform future research into the types of communication strategies that best resonate with the public and are more likely to promote increased support for e-cigarette prevention policy.','[{\"name\":\"Jessup, Owen\",\"email\":\"ojessup@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Kinesiology and Public Health\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"yes\"},{\"name\":\"Viela, Ruta\",\"email\":\"rviela@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Kinesiology and Public Health\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"yes\"},{\"name\":\"Alber, Julia\",\"email\":\"jmalber@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Kinesiology and Public Health\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Faculty\",\"frost\":\"yes\"},{\"name\":\"Jackson, Lorraine\",\"email\":\"ljacksonn@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Other...\",\"other_affiliation\":\"Communication Studies\",\"role\":\"Faculty\",\"frost\":\"no\"}]','10:30am-12:00pm,1:00pm-3:00pm','','2022-04-14 00:35:40',24,'1:00-2:45','1:45-2','180-261'),(42,'654674b955cc5df994100130ec5df320','2022','poster','Evaluating Minor League Pay Based on Modern Philosophies: A Follow-Up Analysis','Many minor league baseball players in the United States are paid below the federal minimum wage (McDaniel, 2022, SpoortsIllustrated.com). However, inequities faced by minor league baseball players may oftentimes be overlooked or under-discussed. Given the obscurity surrounding this topic, the first author performed a follow-up study to one end-of-term Cal Poly course project (KINE 278: Intro to Perspectives in Physical Activity, Winter 2021). The previous project used historical and philosophical perspectives to analyze opposing discourse on the issue captured in a piece of investigative journalism (Garofalo, 2019, TalkPoverty.org). A limitation of the previous project was only ancient philosophies (e.g., Bhagavad Gita, Confucianism) were used to describe and deconstruct opposing views regarding minor league pay. The present follow-up study addressed this limitation by examining opposing views on the issue using two modern philosophical paradigms: utilitarianism and deontology. Both emerged in parallel to the rise of modern sport. As the tenets of \"modern\" sport have remained largely unchanged since the mid-1800s, modern philosophies reactive to the \"fallout\" of modernizing society could uniquely aid students in critically appraising ways leadership in modern sport leagues intertwine with present-day social issues, such as pay equity. This presentation will highlight key findings of our follow-up study.','[{\"name\":\"Napolitano, Mia\",\"email\":\"mia@napolitanofamily.com\",\"affiliation\":\"Kinesiology and Public Health\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"no\"},{\"name\":\"Thomas, Jafr\\u0101\",\"email\":\"jthoma84@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Kinesiology and Public Health\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Faculty\",\"frost\":\"no\"}]','','We would like to attend a workshop but CANNOT attend on Tuesday April 19, 5:10-6pm','2022-04-14 01:00:09',23,NULL,NULL,NULL),(43,'ae60e7df43dc91a6ef5100799b55cf36','2022','poster','Detrital zircon geochronology and geochemistry of southern California Cretaceous forearc strata, western Transverse Ranges','Provenance studies of forearc strata provide insight into the timing of uplift and exposure of adjacent lithotectonic belts, and growth and deformation of convergent margin structures. In particular, detrital zircon geochronology and geochemistry has become widely used because it can determine the maximum depositional age of the strata, as well as characterize ages of the source rock. Furthermore, recent compilations of zircon geochemical data allow differentiation of discrete zircon geochemical populations correlated with continental versus oceanic source rocks through comparison of trace element ratios (e.g., U/Yb). Previous provenance studies from Nacimiento forearc strata exposed along the central California coast suggest a period of uplift and erosion of ophiolitic crust within the forearc and isolated from the arc during the Albian-early Cenomanian. This study presents detrital zircon age and geochemical data from the western Transverse Ranges south of the Santa Ynez River fault. Although these samples are now adjacent to the Nacimiento block, they represent an area of the forearc that formed over 100 km south of the southernmost samples from the Nacimiento block because the western Transverse Ranges along the Santa Barbara coast rotated clockwise ~90 degrees during Neogene deformation. Our preliminary results data from the western Transverse Ranges yield maximum depositional ages of 103 Ma for the Lower Cretaceous Espada Formation and 69 Ma for the Upper Cretaceous Jalama Formation. Importantly, the Espada Formation includes a 176-159 Ma low U/Yb zircon that is not present in the younger Jalama Formation, and indicates the presence of a primitive, erosional source to the southern California forearc basin during the Aptian. This supports results from the Nacimiento forearc and suggests that uplift and erosion of Jurassic Coast Range ophiolite in the forearc may have been widespread throughout the southern California Mesozoic forearc. ','[{\"name\":\"Alamillo, Lauren\",\"email\":\"lalami01@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Physics\",\"other_affiliation\":\"Geology\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"yes\"},{\"name\":\"Johnston, Scott\",\"email\":\"scjohnst@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Physics\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Faculty\",\"frost\":\"yes\"},{\"name\":\"Kylander-Clark, Andrew\",\"email\":\"akylander@geol.ucsb.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Other...\",\"other_affiliation\":\"Earth Science\",\"role\":\"Other\",\"frost\":\"yes\"}]','','We know how to make one','2022-04-14 02:29:40',24,NULL,NULL,NULL),(44,'7b5056e7c4c4160f67a3a7c25bab03c1','2022','talk','Stability and Behavior of a Novel Vesicle-Hydrogel for Drug Delivery','Drug loaded nanomaterials can improve therapy for localized illnesses, such as biofilm infections. Stimuli responsive nanomaterials further improve efficacy and reduce side effects by selectively releasing the payload drug at the targeted condition. Liposomes and hydrogels are commonly seen in nanomaterial development. However, neither nanomaterial provides a sustained localized drug release, and both are limited by the material\'s stability and behavior. Composite nanomaterials address these challenges by combining multiple structures for tunable material characteristics. \n\nThis research presents a novel vesicle-embedded hydrogel for sequential drug delivery. It retains the stability characteristic of hydrogels as well as the drug encapsulation and sustained release of vesicles. A hydrogel lattice is formed by crosslinking a 4-armed polyethylene-glycol (PEG) to a previously designed vesicle via disulfide exchange. This work investigated conditions for formation, stability, and stimuli responsive degradation. In addition, the vesicle-hydrogel was investigated for the vesicle specific characteristics of payload encapsulation and stimuli response.','[{\"name\":\"Need, Esther\",\"email\":\"eneed@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Chemistry and Biochemistry\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"yes\"},{\"name\":\"Ward, Sandra\",\"email\":\"sward07@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Chemistry and Biochemistry\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Faculty\",\"frost\":\"yes\"}]','10:30am-12:00pm','','2022-04-14 02:32:51',19,'9:00-10:45','10:15-10:30','180-270'),(45,'d088723a3b80915d541a8ce2de96b7fe','2022','poster','PROTRACTED INTRUSION AND LATE HIGH TEMPERTAURE DEFORMATION DURING CRETACEOUS HIGH FLUX MAGMATISM, SALINIAN ARC MIDDLE CRUST, CENTRAL COAST RANGES, CALIFORNIA','Voluminous magma that forms in arcs above subduction zones at convergent margins is a first-order tectonic process that has implications for the formation of continental crust. Magma bodies evolve during ascent, cooling, and interaction with crust in the overriding plate. However, the timing of deformation and metamorphism in the overriding plate with respect to intrusion are poorly constrained, and degree to which rising arc magmas are contaminated by lower and middle crustal rocks remains uncertain. In this study, we investigate Salinian block arc exposures from the Santa Lucia Mountains where granitic arc rocks and their high-grade metamorphic framework present a unique opportunity to investigate lower- and middle-crustal arc processes and magma evolution. To place constraints on the timing of deformation, metamorphism, and igneous intrusion within the Salinian block, we collected garnet-bearing samples of orthogneiss and paragneiss from the central portion of the Salinian block where prior studies have indicated metamorphism and crystallization at middle-crustal depths. Here, we present the field and petrographic observations as well as coupled zircon geochronology and geochemistry from these rocks. Our results indicate a protracted intrusive history from ~120 to 95 Ma followed by high-temperature metamorphism at 90 to 80 Ma. Outcrop and microstructural relations suggest that deformation of the Sur Series occurred as early 105 Ma, but the main phase must have continued after 98 Ma. Following deformation lithostatic conditions were dominant during metamorphic zircon crystallization in pelitic migmatites and during intrusion of late dikes from 90 to 80 Ma. We interpret these results as a protracted intrusive history followed by high temperature metamorphism that occurred during a period of burial. Further studies will include thermobarometry and petrogenetic modeling to determine the PT conditions of potentially igneous and metamorphic garnet growth in orthogneisses and pelitic schists.','[{\"name\":\"Pitsillides, Iason\",\"email\":\"ipitsill@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Other...\",\"other_affiliation\":\"NRES\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"yes\"},{\"name\":\"Johnston, Scott\",\"email\":\"scjohnst@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Physics\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Faculty\",\"frost\":\"yes\"},{\"name\":\"Kylander-Clark, Andrew\",\"email\":\"kylander@geol.ucsb.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Other...\",\"other_affiliation\":\"UCSB Geology\",\"role\":\"Faculty\",\"frost\":\"no\"}]','','We know how to make one','2022-04-14 02:36:25',25,NULL,NULL,NULL),(46,'6fab2d662861f025591fee4810be839c','2022','poster','Phytoplankton community response to changing environmental conditions across two central California sites','Understanding the role that changing environmental conditions play in altering phytoplankton abundance and community composition, and in turn ecosystem structure and function, will be increasingly important for the sustainable use and management of ocean resources in a changing climate. Characterizing change in nearshore ecosystems requires long-term studies with a broad spatial extent, with most studies sacrificing spatial extent for temporal duration. However, phytoplankton and ecosystem response can vary substantially over small spatial scales due to local oceanographic forcing and anthropogenic influence, making the application of long-term data from one site to another in the same geographic vicinity potentially challenging. In this study, we compare weekly phytoplankton abundance and community composition samples between two sites on the Central California Coast. One site, located in San Luis Obispo (SLO) Bay upwelling shadow, is a long-term harmful algal blooms (HABs) sampling site with more than a decade of data with a well characterized seasonal and interannual variability. The other site (~30 km away) is located at the mouth of Morro Bay, a seasonally low-inflow estuary with multiple aquaculture farms and long-term data from higher trophic levels, where samples were collected at high tide to capture incoming oceanic waters. Comparison of nearly a year of data shows significant similarities in community response, and in particular the relative proportion of diatoms and dinoflagellates, to changing temperature at both sites. Moreover, during large bloom events, while phytoplankton abundance differed by up to an order of magnitude between sites, the composition reached high levels of similarity. This study serves as a precursor to future research focused on predicting higher trophic level community response to change, potentially linking the long-term SLO Bay plankton dataset and higher trophic-level datasets collected closer to the Morro Bay site.  ','[{\"name\":\"Pasulka, Alexis\",\"email\":\"apasulka@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Biological Sciences\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Faculty\",\"frost\":\"no\"},{\"name\":\"Walter, Ryan\",\"email\":\"rkwalter@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Physics\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Faculty\",\"frost\":\"no\"},{\"name\":\"Soares, Nicholas\",\"email\":\"nicholasoares29@gmail.com\",\"affiliation\":\"Biological Sciences\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"yes\"},{\"name\":\"Romanini, Elysa \",\"email\":\"eromanin@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Biological Sciences\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"no\"}]','','We know how to make one,We can attend April 19, 5-6pm','2022-04-14 04:28:53',26,NULL,NULL,NULL),(47,'adbde8fea4bb03446188fb738d24bb78','2022','poster','Metadata Repository','This poster details Sucheen Sundaram and Dr. Hunter Glanz\'s work to build a repository of metadata over the course of Summer 2021. The purpose of this project was to increase the accessibility of datasets and tailor searches to more complex and/or specific objectives. Some examples include machine-learning tasks, education, cleaning, and much more.','[{\"name\":\"Sundaram, Sucheen\",\"email\":\"sssundar@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Statistics\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"yes\"},{\"name\":\"Glanz, Hunter\",\"email\":\"hglanz@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Statistics\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Faculty\",\"frost\":\"yes\"}]','','We know how to make one','2022-04-14 05:23:50',27,NULL,NULL,NULL),(48,'6e19b7d35aa10b7c6027efa22d3af049','2022','poster','Population trends of a federally endangered plant in San Luis Obispo County','Goals of this 3 year long study are to determine current and future population growth of the Chorro Creek Bog Thistle, a federally endangered species known from fewer than 20 populations all located in San Luis Obispo County.  This species, Cirsium fontinale var. obispoensis, is found only in perennial serpentine seeps, a habitat that is likely to be negatively impacted by climatic warming and drought. In 2022 we began a demographic study tagging 200 individuals at multiple populations that will be monitored for survival and growth for 3 full growing seasons. These data will then be used to develop matrix models to predict population growth rates now and into the future, and to determine which life stages (seedling, juvenile, or reproductive adult) are most limiting for this species.  \n','[{\"name\":\"Grossenbacher, Dena\",\"email\":\"dgrossen@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Biological Sciences\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Faculty\",\"frost\":\"no\"},{\"name\":\"Yost, Jenn\",\"email\":\"jyost@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Biological Sciences\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Faculty\",\"frost\":\"yes\"},{\"name\":\"Calloway, Stephanie\",\"email\":\"smcallow@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Biological Sciences\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Other\",\"frost\":\"yes\"},{\"name\":\"Barton, Anneliese\",\"email\":\"abarto01@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Biological Sciences\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"no\"},{\"name\":\"Suchy, Kyle\",\"email\":\"ksuchy@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Biological Sciences\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"yes\"}]','','We know how to make one','2022-04-14 06:08:44',28,NULL,NULL,NULL),(49,'4fabaec213abb5748fc5f59a4bed343c','2022','talk','Large Galaxies in the Local Universe','Our group studies the formation and evolution of large galaxies in the local universe. By using both observational data the WIYN telescope, the Sloan Digital Sky Survey as well as simulation data for use with the Legacy Survey of Space and Time, we show that the largest galaxies are the oldest, reddest and most metal rich objects in the local universe. We also investigate properties such as number of companions and their properties. By investigating these issues, our data can shed light on how the universe - on the largest scales - evolves over time.','[{\"name\":\"Higgins, Denvir\",\"email\":\"dehiggin@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Physics\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"no\"},{\"name\":\"Gavidia, Adriana\",\"email\":\"aygavidi@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Physics\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"no\"},{\"name\":\"Looper, Adam\",\"email\":\"adam.looper15@gmail.com\",\"affiliation\":\"Physics\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"no\"},{\"name\":\"Chawla, Angela\",\"email\":\"amchawla@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Other...\",\"other_affiliation\":\"Graphic Design\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"no\"},{\"name\":\"Ruano, Melina\",\"email\":\"mruano@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Other...\",\"other_affiliation\":\"Aerospace Engineering\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"no\"},{\"name\":\"Bardwell, Josh\",\"email\":\"jbardwel@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Other...\",\"other_affiliation\":\"General Engineering\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"no\"},{\"name\":\"Edwards, Louise\",\"email\":\"ledwar04@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Physics\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Faculty\",\"frost\":\"no\"}]','1:00pm-3:00pm','','2022-04-14 16:43:04',34,'1:00-2:45','1:15-1:30','180-270'),(50,'272b5120c1d331b1c99659c0bcf6102c','2022','poster','How often does sexual misconduct occur in K-12 schools?','How often does the abuse and misconduct of students by school personnel occur? This answer to this question cannot be answered by the Department of Education or the Department of Justice and minimal data is available. The last generalizable study was conducted in the year 2000 and other studies ask about rape or assault, but not misconduct or grooming behaviors. Some states and newspaper reporters collect information, but these studies have various definitions and timepoints. School districts, states and the Department of Education may be fearful to document these occurrences because it may reflect poorly on the state, Y, Z. In an effort to document the prevalence of this issue, this study examined two sets of data 1) Freedom of Information (FOIA) requests of state revocations, and 2) google alerts for teachers arrested. FOIA requests were cataloged for the year 2019, and google alerts have been cataloged from January 2014 - August 2021. Of the 35 states who provided their data, 406 teachers licenses were revoked and 177 teachers licenses were suspended for sexual misconduct. (add another take away). 3,877 google alerts were cataloged, with 726 in 2019. This data only represents the cases that are egregious enough to warrant a license action or law enforcement/media report and does not include cases that are handled at the district level with informal actions or resignations. ','[{\"name\":\"Huynh, Lana\",\"email\":\"lmhuynh@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Statistics\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"yes\"},{\"name\":\"Dhaliwal, Sahib \",\"email\":\"sdhali01@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Statistics\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"yes\"},{\"name\":\"Grant, Billie-Jo\",\"email\":\"bgrant02@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Statistics\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Faculty\",\"frost\":\"yes\"}]','','We know how to make one','2022-04-14 17:14:58',29,NULL,NULL,NULL),(51,'7696f73b4708a7cc99275fed55cbd10f','2022','poster','Virtual Reality Scientific Diving in the Classroom','I and Dr. White lead a group of Cal Poly student scientific SCUBA divers in generating underwater virtual reality (VR) videography of scientific methods in marine ecology research, including benthic transect surveys for quantifying the population densities of marine invertebrates. We accomplished this using a 360-degree spherical underwater video camera (from Dr. White\'s lab). We filmed at the Cal Poly Pier and in Montana de Oro using the Cal Poly boat, the Richards. Using this video footage, I created a VR scientific diving experience for 7th-grade students. We partnered with a local teacher at Laguna Middle School for testing the VR experience using Chromebooks and/or wearing re-usable, affordable VR browsers (recycled phones inserted into Google Cardboard headsets). As they watch our video, the students will not only experience SCUBA diving but also conduct scientific methods themselves. For example, they will \"swim\" a transect and quantify the abundance of benthic invertebrates they see, such as sea urchins. Furthermore, I developed a lesson plan that guides the students in analyzing their data after the VR experience, comparing their results with other students and classes that also conducted transect surveys. Collectively, this educational experience will support 7th-grade students achieve the NGSS Performance Expectation MS-LS2-1, \"Analyze and interpret data to provide evidence for the effects of resource availability on organisms and populations of organisms in an ecosystem\" (NGSS 2013). By increasing understanding and appreciation for life in the ocean, we can inspire students to think about climate change and how their actions affect the animals that they \"studied\" through our videos.','[{\"name\":\"Beymer, Meg\",\"email\":\"mbeymer@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Biological Sciences\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"no\"},{\"name\":\"White, Crow\",\"email\":\"cwhite31@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Other...\",\"other_affiliation\":\"Marine Sciences\",\"role\":\"Faculty\",\"frost\":\"no\"}]','','We have one already','2022-04-14 17:19:41',30,NULL,NULL,NULL),(52,'e84d5819d1b37544764b40bcecde36aa','2022','poster','Action Potential Propagation in the Myocardium: An Agent-Based Approach','The successful propagation of action potentials (APs) through the myocardium is critical to cardiac function, yet the relevant physiological mechanisms are still being investigated. In this project, we present a novel agent-based model of AP propagation between cardiomyocytes which attempts to incorporate the functionality of gap junction proteins as well as other biophysical phenomena that enable intercellular communication (referred to as ephaptic effects). In contrast to existing differential equation-based modeling efforts, our model prioritizes cell geometry and visualization, making it a promising tool for further interdisciplinary study of ephaptic effects in the myocardium. We cover the conceptual development and implementation of this model in NetLogo and demonstrate its ability to both represent resting, polarized cells as well as to conduct a depolarization signal between two adjacent cardiomyocytes. Lastly, we examine the limitations of the model and point to future directions which may improve the model\'s accuracy and utility.','[{\"name\":\"Dimitrova, Elena\",\"email\":\"edimitro@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Mathematics\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Faculty\",\"frost\":\"yes\"},{\"name\":\"Lin, Joyce\",\"email\":\"jlin46@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Mathematics\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Faculty\",\"frost\":\"yes\"},{\"name\":\"Berg, Brady\",\"email\":\"bcberg@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Mathematics\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"yes\"},{\"name\":\"McGuire, Joseph\",\"email\":\"jmcgui05@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Mathematics\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"no\"}]','','We have one already','2022-04-14 18:10:51',31,NULL,NULL,NULL),(53,'895555934bd2d15c0f344005d5fafe90','2022','poster','Effects of age on neural cell proliferation in Children\'s pythons (Antaresia childrenii)','In mammals, neurogenesis in the brain decreases with age. However, little research has been done on this topic in reptiles, even though reptiles exhibit greater postnatal neurogenesis than mammals in general. Studying how such factors affect postnatal neurogenesis among all vertebrates will help increase our understanding of the evolution of this trait and the functional consequences for decreasing neurogenesis from development into adulthood. In this study, we used Childrens pythons (Antaresia childreni) to test the hypothesis that neural cell proliferation in the telencephalon decreases with age. We injected 5-bromo-12-deoxyuridine, a cell birth marker, the day before sacrifice, to quantify and compare neural cell proliferation in the brains of three-year old, two-year old, and one-year old snakes. Overall, there was no significant effect of age on new neural cell density. However, there was a significantly higher new neural cell density in the retrobulbar region compared to other parts of the telencephalon, regardless of age. The higher cell density in the retrobulbar region is consistent with results from previous studies. Snakes continue to grow into adulthood, well beyond sexual maturation, while mammals stop growing before they are sexually mature. Therefore, the lack of differences across age groups may be due to a more gradual decline in growth, including cell proliferation in the brain, than in mammals. ','[{\"name\":\"Gonzalez, Priscilla\",\"email\":\"pgonza22@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Biological Sciences\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"yes\"},{\"name\":\"Jacobs, Emma Katharina\",\"email\":\"ejacob10@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Other...\",\"other_affiliation\":\"Department of Biomedical Engineering\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"yes\"},{\"name\":\"Pradhan, Amrit Das\",\"email\":\"adpradha@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Liberal Studies\",\"other_affiliation\":\"Psychology and Child Development\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"yes\"},{\"name\":\"Bow, Hannah\",\"email\":\"hbow@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Biological Sciences\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"yes\"},{\"name\":\"Strand, Christy\",\"email\":\"cstrand@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Biological Sciences\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Faculty\",\"frost\":\"no\"}]','','We know how to make one','2022-04-14 18:44:38',32,NULL,NULL,NULL),(54,'e2598b1e849d43089d2760716abb3e7e','2022','poster','Which factors predict bystander intervention to prevent sexual harassment among college students?','Background: Sexual harassment is especially prevalent on college campuses, with 47% of students reporting sexual harassment victimization while in college (Cantor et al., 2015). A common approach to reduce sexual harassment on college campuses is to train students about Bystander Intervention (BI), a method used to instruct students how to stop sexual harassment whenever it arises. Little research has been conducted to investigate student perceptions regarding BI to prevent sexual harassment, with almost none of this research having a theoretical framework.\nPurpose: To test a Reasoned Action Approach (RAA) based scale to predict BI to stop sexual harassment. \nMethods: Two RAA-based surveys were sent out to students in nine general education courses between January and April 2022 at two US universities, with the time period between survey dissemination being approximately ten weeks. Students who completed both surveys received a small amount of extra credit.  \nResults: About 300 respondents between the ages of 18 and 25 years old completed the Time 1 survey, and approximately 220 completed the Time 2 survey. We are cleaning the data, then we plan to run psychometric analyses and multiple linear regressions to determine the predictive utility of the instrument.\nDiscussion: To meaningfully decrease the rate of sexual harassment on college campuses, it is important to understand commonly endorsed BI perceptions and actions. Results from this study will be used to enhance and tailor BI programming for college students.\n','[{\"name\":\"Barrow, Rebecca\",\"email\":\"rmbarrow@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Kinesiology and Public Health\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"no\"},{\"name\":\"Hyland, Catherine\",\"email\":\"cshyland@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Kinesiology and Public Health\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"no\"},{\"name\":\"Staten, Sarah\",\"email\":\"sstaten@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Kinesiology and Public Health\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"yes\"},{\"name\":\"Hackman, Christine\",\"email\":\"chackman@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Kinesiology and Public Health\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Faculty\",\"frost\":\"yes\"}]','','We know how to make one','2022-04-14 18:53:52',33,NULL,NULL,NULL),(55,'3571aef01c46221b22417e9818147570','2022','poster','Horses and Apples: Applications of DNA technology','Direct analysis of DNA using molecular techniques allows researchers to answer interesting biological questions. Both projects presented here use the same approach of extracting, amplifying, and visualizing DNA. In one project, DNA analysis is used to determine the origin of animal hair used as stuffing for an antique chair. In another project, DNA from apples is analyzed to identify sequences that distinguish red-skinned and green-skinned fruit. Preliminary results from each project are presented.','[{\"name\":\"Elizarraraz, Luz\",\"email\":\"lelizarr@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Biological Sciences\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"no\"},{\"name\":\"Wick, Lars\",\"email\":\"lwick@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Biological Sciences\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"no\"},{\"name\":\"Benedict, Kaeley\",\"email\":\"knbenedi@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Biological Sciences\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"no\"},{\"name\":\"Himelblau, Ed\",\"email\":\"ehimelbl@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Biological Sciences\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Faculty\",\"frost\":\"no\"}]','','We know how to make one','2022-04-14 19:58:59',34,NULL,NULL,NULL),(56,'933cc35a20ff67383718410e9ee70dea','2022','poster','Polyurethane Coating Reinforced by Functionalized Graphene Oxide','Corrosion costs both in monetary and health & safety terms. Corrosion costed $2.5 trillion equaling 3.4% worlds GDP in 2016 which did not only include the damage to metal surface but also the indirect loss resulted from leakages, fires etc. While many anticorrosion methods have been attempted in the coating industry, protection by polymer coating is the one of the most cost-effect methods. In this work, we report functionalized graphene oxide based polyurethane coating with the anticorrosion property. Polyurethane is one of the most common binders having high barrier and mechanical strength. Graphene oxide nanosheets act as a 2D barrier having low permeation towards molecules and ions preventing corrosion. Graphene oxide is surface-functionalized to increase its compatibilization with polyurethane resulting in great miscibility. The effect of different surface functionality and graphene oxide loading on the physical properties is investigated.','[{\"name\":\"Gupta, Shubham\",\"email\":\"sgupta36@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Chemistry and Biochemistry\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"yes\"},{\"name\":\"Zhang, Shanju\",\"email\":\"szhang05@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Chemistry and Biochemistry\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Faculty\",\"frost\":\"yes\"}]','','We have one already,We know how to make one','2022-04-14 20:18:07',35,NULL,NULL,NULL),(57,'6011869431fe6136d2d1c7dc48756618','2022','talk','Expression of gonadotropin-inhibitory hormone in juvenile Children\'s pythons ([[Antaresia childreni]])','Prior to the discovery of gonadotropin-inhibitory hormone (GnIH) in Japanese Quail, gonadotropin-releasing hormone (GnRH) was understood to be the primary regulating factor of gonadotropin synthesis and secretion. The discovery of GnIH in the past two decades has disturbed this understanding of gonadotropin regulation, as GnIH has been shown to decrease gonadotropin release, therefore down regulating gonadal and sexual development. While the existence and mechanism of GnIH release has been studied, its expression and range of effects across species remains largely unknown. In this study, the effect of age on the production of GnIH in the hypothalamus of Children\'s pythons is being investigated to determine how GnIH expression may be regulated through sexual maturation. Sectioned brains from Children\'s pythons aged one, two or three years old are being stained using immunohistochemistry with an antibody against GnIH. Following the completion of staining, ImageJ software will be used to both count the stained cell bodies and calculate an optical density measurement for the stained cells. It is hypothesized that, due to GnIH\'s function as a reproductive and sexual inhibitor, younger pythons will show higher GnIH expression than older pythons. Acquiring a greater understanding of the factors that regulate reproduction and maturation in pythons has potential to benefit both snake conservation and breeding programs in captivity. \n','[{\"name\":\"Coppolillo, Nina\",\"email\":\"ncoppoli@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Biological Sciences\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"yes\"},{\"name\":\"Strand, Christy\",\"email\":\"cstrand@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Biological Sciences\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Faculty\",\"frost\":\"no\"}]','10:30am-12:00pm,1:00pm-3:00pm','','2022-04-14 20:40:20',28,'1:00-2:45','1:15-1:30','180-266'),(58,'41f087fd471af4966d3d7ce5117bf273','2022','poster','Sleep and Physical Activity in College Students During COVID-19 Pandemic','During the Covid-19 pandemic, interest in how lifestyle changes affected both physical activity and sleep patterns in college aged students developed, but it is yet to be determined conclusively how the pandemic and restrictions have affected sedentary behavior, physical activity, sleep quantity, and sleep quality. The aim of this study is to objectively measure the physical activity levels and sleep of college students during the Covid-19 pandemic using accelerometer techniques. This cross-sectional observational study utilized triaxial Actigraph GT3x-BT (Actigraph LLC; Pensacola, FL) data collected from California Polytechnic State University (Cal Poly) students who wore the accelerometer on their wrist for 7 consecutive days to identify physical activity levels and sleep duration and quantity. Data collected shows an average of 47.45 minutes of continuous physical activity daily and relatively high continuous bouts of inactivity, approximately 5.2 hours per day. Low sleep duration and efficiency was also observed with an average of 6.65 hours, well below the recommended 8 hours per night. Further statistical analysis must be conducted to identify how the data collected compares to a referent population. A proportional analysis will be able to determine what proportion of the sample met national recommendations. These initial findings suggest that the restrictions placed during the Covid-19 pandemic did not lead to low physical activity in Cal Poly students yet may have negatively impacted their sleep. ','[{\"name\":\"Richardson, Alix\",\"email\":\"aricha32@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Kinesiology and Public Health\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"yes\"},{\"name\":\"Greever, Cory\",\"email\":\"greever@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Kinesiology and Public Health\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Faculty\",\"frost\":\"no\"}]','','We would like to attend a workshop but CANNOT attend on Tuesday April 19, 5:10-6pm','2022-04-14 21:46:39',36,NULL,NULL,NULL),(59,'f5e969ba974928a688465db862fb0b57','2022','poster','Predictive Modeling In Silico Modeling','A critical step in the formulation of many coatings is the determination of volatile organic compounds (VOC) amount. To enable faster formulation development and iteration a machine learning model workflow has been developed which predicts the VOC content of small molecule mixtures and exemplar formulations. Artificial neural networks are trained to predict response factor and retention time for individual components in a mixture or formulation. A simulated elution profile is produced, and a predicted VOC amount is calculated. The combination of neural networks and empirical gas chromatography are used to enhance such quantitative parameters of analytes. Given the increasing interest in predicting certain quantitative parameters of analytes, the tool may be added to other predictive workflows to further enable digital design of coating formulations outside of the traditional wet laboratory.','[{\"name\":\"Kim, Paul\",\"email\":\"pkim56@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Biological Sciences\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"yes\"},{\"name\":\"Smith,Philip\",\"email\":\"psmith31@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Chemistry and Biochemistry\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"yes\"},{\"name\":\"Sapper, Erik\",\"email\":\"esapper@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Chemistry and Biochemistry\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Faculty\",\"frost\":\"yes\"}]','','We know how to make one','2022-04-14 21:49:08',37,NULL,NULL,NULL),(60,'6a115012a732c288362fc66f09ce046f','2022','talk','Find your Flow: A menstrual health social media campaign ','In many cultures, menstruation is surrounded by silence and shame instead of being celebrated as a sign of health and vitality. Globally, challenges, including stigma surrounding menstruation, create barriers for menstruators (White, 2013; Crawford, 2014; Garg, 2015). It proves to be difficult for young menstruators to navigate menarche due to the taboos and socio-cultural restrictions surrounding menstruation (Sharma,2015). Encouraging women to have open conversations about their periods is necessary to combat these challenges. To understand how to address the stigmas around menstruation, the researchers first conducted a literature review, revealing that education messages via the Internet, posters, storytelling and peer group discussion effectively created awareness of menstruation (Hennegan, 2020). Therefore, a social media campaign was launched to address the gaps identified in the literature. The IRB-approved campaign is active on Facebook and Instagram, as identified in the literature, for easy user participation and opportunities for networking with other organizations (Bebla, 2018). Participants completed a Qualtrics survey recounting their first-period experiences and stories. Thus far, respondents from the U.S., Canada, India, Kenya, Ghana, and South Africa have shared their first menstrual experience. Preliminary themes include young menarche age, initial support from mothers or relatives, and education as a primary source of support for North American participants. Participants residing in the Global South experienced confusion, embarrassment, and fright more than their Global North counterparts. As evidenced in the literature, storytelling is a powerful tool to normalize conversations around menstruation. Many menstruators have vocalized their support for open communication of shared menstrual experiences through social media. The campaign aims to recognize and address the taboos, stigmas, and misconceptions surrounding menstruation in the next five years and assess the attitudinal changes resulting from menstruators engaging in more open, authentic dialogue about menstruation globally.  ','[{\"name\":\"Roberts, Joni\",\"email\":\"jrober81@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Kinesiology and Public Health\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Faculty\",\"frost\":\"yes\"},{\"name\":\"Hamp-Adams, Sarah\",\"email\":\"shampada@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Kinesiology and Public Health\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"yes\"},{\"name\":\"Petit, Kate\",\"email\":\"kepetit@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Kinesiology and Public Health\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"no\"},{\"name\":\"Manalili, Nicola\",\"email\":\"nmanalil@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Kinesiology and Public Health\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"no\"},{\"name\":\"Carolan, Sydney\",\"email\":\"scarolan@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Biological Sciences\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"no\",\"presenter\":\"yes\"}]','9:00am-10:30am',NULL,'2022-04-14 22:16:46',14,'9:00-10:45','9-9:15','180-270'),(61,'30d7cfaf285e61227c918292ff634bde','2022','talk','Discovery of a Silver Based Method to Synthesize Benzoxazole Inhibitors of CK2','Protein kinases are a type of enzyme which serve to catalyze the transfer of a phosphate group from an adenosine triphosphate (ATP) molecule to the kinase\'s target substrate protein. Kinase mutations can disrupt signaling pathways and regulation, which have been linked to inflammatory diseases and cancer. For this reason, kinase enzymes have been a prevalent drug target in medicinal chemistry research. The objective of the present work is to synthesize a compound that targets the kinase protein CK2 (Protein Kinase CK2). There is increasing evidence that there is a correlation between the over-expression of CK2 and different cancers, including breast, lung, ovarian, and prostate cancer. Furthermore, CK2 has become a desirable drug target and attempts have been made to develop an inhibitor for CK2. Our collaborators at North Carolina Chapel Hill screened potential inhibitors and identified a potent benzoxazole inhibitor (ERB041) as a promising drug candidate for CK2. Although ERB041 shows great promise for being highly potent against CK2, their results showed that there was low nanomolar activity at the two active kinase subunits CK2a and CK2a2 suggesting low selectivity for CK2. With this work, our desire is to modify the benzoxazole core such that we will increase selectivity for CK2 while maintaining the desired potency of the inhibitor.  ','[{\"name\":\"Wong, Chloe\",\"email\":\"cwong141@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Chemistry and Biochemistry\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"yes\"},{\"name\":\"Eagon, Scott\",\"email\":\"seagon@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Chemistry and Biochemistry\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Faculty\",\"frost\":\"yes\"}]','1:00pm-3:00pm','','2022-04-14 22:54:22',30,'1:00-2:45','1:45-2','180-266'),(62,'55cdfe9cb799a8b1eccfb6b3f9c44761','2022','poster','Repellency responses of human-biting California tick species to essential oils','Ticks are well-known vectors that cause disease in humans and animals. There are many plant-derived compounds that warrant further investigation as personal tick repellents. The goal of this project was to investigate the repellency properties of essential oils on two local tick species in San Luis Obispo that feed on a range of mammal hosts, including humans: Pacific Coast ticks ([[Dermacentor occidentalis]]) and Western Blacklegged ticks ([[Ixodes pacificus]]). [[Ixodes pacificus]] is the primary vector of [[Borrelia burgdorferi]] in the western U.S., which is the causative agent of Lyme disease, and is also capable of transmitting several other pathogens to humans and other animals. Assays to evaluate adult tick crawling behavior on suspended pieces of treated filter paper were administered to observe responses to a 3% dilution of several essential oils. The oils tested were cedarwood, cinnamon leaf, coriander, clove bud, eucalyptus, lavender, lemongrass, peppermint, and thyme. Responses were compared to three types of controls: untreated filter paper (tick crawling substrate negative control), coconut oil treated filter paper (essential oil diluent negative control), and DEET treated filter paper (positive control). Repellency was evaluated based on whether or not ticks ascended past the treated zone of the filter paper. The essential oil with the greatest repellency was determined to be clove bud oil, with most other oils showing some degree of repellency.  Results of this project provide data on the potential efficacy of essential oils, particularly clove bud oil, as alternative repellents against two tick species commonly found in California.','[{\"name\":\"Vredevoe, Larisa\",\"email\":\"lvredevo@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Biological Sciences\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Faculty\",\"frost\":\"yes\"},{\"name\":\"Barnes, Skylar\",\"email\":\"skbarnes@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Biological Sciences\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"yes\"},{\"name\":\"Figueroa, Samantha\",\"email\":\"sbfiguer@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Biological Sciences\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"yes\"}]','','We know how to make one','2022-04-15 00:41:51',38,NULL,NULL,NULL),(63,'e2a2f778bae3faad25cc8e649d22c285','2022','talk','Characterization of glutathione-sensitive vesicles prepared from supramolecular amphiphiles','In the development of drug delivery systems, nanocarriers capable of releasing encapsulated loads of therapeutics are shown to hold promise in future medical applications. Nanocarriers can be designed to exhibit controlled and sustained release of therapeutics, thus more effectively targeting diseases in the body, such as cancer. This innovative characteristic is achieved by designing nanomaterials capable of degrading under conditions local to an intended delivery site. However, the challenge in developing these materials is achieving the ideal rate of payload release. We will present the investigation of the characteristics and functionality of a vesicle nanocarrier composed of a novel, self-assembling supramolecular amphiphile, the aim of which is to create a material with kinetics that can be fine-tuned for a given application. Additionally, our study will present the results of these vesicles\' triggered degradation. The vesicle utilizes a glutathione (GSH) sensitive disulfide bond within its constituent amphiphile, which provides a mechanism for releasing an encapsulated payload under specific conditions. Here we will present the results of our triggered degradation studies as well as other data characterizing these vesicles. In future research, we aim to extend the properties of the nanocarrier to a hydrogel of crosslinked vesicles and from it, adapt a second drug dispersal mechanism. The GSH-triggered release mechanism of this vesicle, along with other essential characteristics observed in experimental data, has continued to demonstrate the viability of this nanocarrier for future use in drug delivery.','[{\"name\":\"Schroeder, James\",\"email\":\"Jschro04@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Chemistry and Biochemistry\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"no\",\"presenter\":\"yes\"},{\"name\":\"Yim, Matthew\",\"email\":\"mgyim@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Biological Sciences\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"yes\"},{\"name\":\"Ward, Sandra\",\"email\":\"sward07@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Chemistry and Biochemistry\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Faculty\",\"frost\":\"yes\"}]','9:00am-10:30am,10:30am-12:00pm',NULL,'2022-04-15 01:03:07',15,'9:00-10:45','9:15-9:30','180-270'),(64,'d15be452d130c82517a010cbe4347e7a','2022','talk','Insulated Solar Electric Cooking: Development of Technology and the Global Learning Community','Insulated Solar Electric Cooking (ISEC), where an electric heater directly connected to a solar panel in an insulated chamber cooks food safely and inexpensively, but users want to store energy for higher power and night-time use. Three storage strategies are battery, thermal storage using Phase Change Material (PCM) or Solid Thermal Storage (STS). A Global Learning Community was created to share knowledge and to support an international collaboration of small manufacturing/disseminating enterprises. Large amounts of solar panels and other rural electrification hardware are being imported to collaborators supporting a wide variety of needs besides cooking such as irrigation, lighting and charging devices.\n','[{\"name\":\"Brekalo, Katarina\",\"email\":\"kbrekalo@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Physics\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"yes\"},{\"name\":\"Shepherd, Andrew\",\"email\":\"asheph02@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Physics\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"yes\"},{\"name\":\"Schwartz, Pete\",\"email\":\"pschwart@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Physics\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Faculty\",\"frost\":\"yes\"}]','9:00am-10:30am,10:30am-12:00pm','','2022-04-15 01:37:20',10,'9:00-10:45','9:30-9:45','180-266'),(65,'7d8eec0daba98f15965e129cf83175fa','2022','poster','Augmenting Breast Cancer Subtype Predictors with Graph Knowledge','Deep learning neural networks have improved performance in many cancer informatics problems, including breast cancer subtype classification. However, the biological relevance and reproducibility are often second priority to algorithm speed and dataset size metrics.   Many networks experience underspecification - where several combinations of parameters achieve similar performance outputs.  Embedding prior knowledge from the literature may address this issue by boosting predictive models that provide crucial, in-depth information about a given disease. Breast cancer research provides a wealth of such knowledge, particularly in the form of subtype biomarkers and genetic signatures. We propose to continue with existing projects in our lab to utilize past research on breast cancer subtype biomarkers, label propagation, and neural graph machines to present a novel methodology for embedding knowledge into machine learning systems. We will embed prior knowledge such as biomarkers and patient metadata into the loss function in the form of inter-subject distances derived from a well-known published breast cancer signature. We have shown that this methodology reduces predictor variability on state-of-the-art deep learning architectures and increases predictor consistency leading to improved interpretation.  This novel method applies to a broad range of existing studies and predictive models. ','[{\"name\":\"Anderson, Paul \",\"email\":\"pander14@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Other...\",\"other_affiliation\":\"Computer Science\",\"role\":\"Faculty\",\"frost\":\"no\"},{\"name\":\"Tang, Jonathan \",\"email\":\"jtang46@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Other...\",\"other_affiliation\":\"Computer Science\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"no\"},{\"name\":\"Kressman, McClain \",\"email\":\"mkressma@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Biological Sciences\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"no\"},{\"name\":\"Kim, Paul \",\"email\":\"pkim56@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Biological Sciences\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"no\"},{\"name\":\"Gallivan, Andrew \",\"email\":\"agalliva@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Biological Sciences\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"no\"},{\"name\":\"Garabedian, Lauren \",\"email\":\"lgarabed@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Biological Sciences\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"no\"},{\"name\":\"Lakshmankumar, Harsha \",\"email\":\"hlakshma@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Biological Sciences\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"no\"},{\"name\":\"Sunkara, Yogi \",\"email\":\"ysunkara@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Other...\",\"other_affiliation\":\"Computer Science\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"no\"},{\"name\":\"Davidson, Jean\",\"email\":\"jdavid06@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Biological Sciences\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Faculty\",\"frost\":\"yes\"}]','','We know how to make one','2022-04-15 02:33:42',39,NULL,NULL,NULL),(66,'9635b0fd4d1f1a1ca1eb5d16f08a2e09','2022','poster','Effect of Coconut Oil Intake on the Gut-Liver-Brain Axis in a Juvenile Iberian Pig Model','Gut and liver problems such as non-alcoholic fatty liver disease (NAFLD), Crohn\'s disease, and irritable bowel syndrome (IBS) as well as neurodegenerative diseases, like dementia, have been shown to be associated with excessive dietary fat consumption. However, it is unclear which fats are more detrimental when consumed in excess. The objective of this study was to compare the metabolic effects of the Western Diet [high in fat and in fructose] with different fatty acid compositions on the gut-liver-brain axis in juvenile Iberian pigs. To explore this, we fed two hypercaloric diets enriched in medium-chain fatty acids (coconut oil) and long-chain fatty acids (lard) to twenty juvenile Iberian pigs for 10 weeks and assessed the liver, gut, and brain injury using histology, serum biochemistry, immunohistochemistry, and transcriptomics analysis. It was observed that diets supplemented with excessive medium-chain fatty acids lead to increased hepatic cell proliferation, indicative of liver damage, as well as an increase in intestinal epithelial cytoskeletal remodeling which potentially suggests early stages of gut damage. There were no significant differences in the level of brain injury between the two diets.\n\n','[{\"name\":\"Gehani, Tanvi\",\"email\":\"tgehani@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Other...\",\"other_affiliation\":\"Biomedical Engineering\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"no\"},{\"name\":\"Levy, Katie\",\"email\":\"millgirl00@gmail.com\",\"affiliation\":\"Biological Sciences\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"no\"},{\"name\":\"Smart, Hayden\",\"email\":\"hjsmart@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Biological Sciences\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"yes\"},{\"name\":\"Wheeler, Kevin\",\"email\":\"kevinallanwheeler@gmail.com\",\"affiliation\":\"Biological Sciences\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"no\"},{\"name\":\"Maj, Magdalena\",\"email\":\"mmaj@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Biological Sciences\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Faculty\",\"frost\":\"no\"}]','','We know how to make one,We can attend April 19, 5-6pm','2022-04-15 02:40:32',40,NULL,NULL,NULL),(67,'661051b5996a87209c686893d4cd4f73','2022','poster','Comparisons of Knowledge Graphs and Entity Extraction in Breast Cancer Subtyping Biomedical Text Analysis','With the accumulation of detailed biological research publications and databases, the use of open-source tools is critical for the discovery of novel relationships. To take advantage of this extensive biological data, we used a natural language processing Python-based package called ScispaCy, for biomedical and scientific text processing, which can assist in the extraction and classification of named entities in unstructured text. This package was implemented into a pipeline that can generate knowledge graphs to visually represent the comprehensive network of the named entities. Here, we compare the utility of knowledge graphs and named entity extraction for identifying biologically appropriate results from breast cancer subtyping publications. Breast cancer subtyping literature was used as our test set due to them being complex yet the mechanistic pathophysiology is well studied. Improving the components of named entity recognition and knowledge graphs for interpreting biological data can have significant clinical applications in patient care responses, such as the accurate identification of breast cancer subtypes for a curated therapeutic course of action. Our research suggests that limitations exist in current knowledge graph pipelines in biomedical data analysis, primarily related to named entity extraction issues.\n','[{\"name\":\"Davidson, Jean\",\"email\":\"jdavid06@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Biological Sciences\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Faculty\",\"frost\":\"yes\"},{\"name\":\"Hawblitzel, Grif \",\"email\":\"ghawblit@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Biological Sciences\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"no\"},{\"name\":\"Zarate, Nicholas\",\"email\":\"nezarate@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Biological Sciences\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"no\"},{\"name\":\"Kressman, McClain\",\"email\":\"mkressma@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Biological Sciences\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"no\"},{\"name\":\"Doud, Andrew\",\"email\":\"adoud@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Other...\",\"other_affiliation\":\"Computer Science\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"no\"},{\"name\":\"Jakusovszky, Ava\",\"email\":\"ajakusov@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Biological Sciences\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"no\"},{\"name\":\"Aduaka, Belle \",\"email\":\"baduaka@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Biological Sciences\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"no\"},{\"name\":\"Andrysek, Otakar \",\"email\":\"oandryse@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Other...\",\"other_affiliation\":\"Computer Science\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"no\"},{\"name\":\"Anderson, Paul\",\"email\":\"pander14@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Other...\",\"other_affiliation\":\"Computer Science\",\"role\":\"Faculty\",\"frost\":\"no\"}]','','We know how to make one','2022-04-15 02:45:24',41,NULL,NULL,NULL),(68,'d71d9335a9bc84de3004ab4ae09ce2a1','2022','talk','Save the Sea Otters: Using subspecies databases to identify biomarkers for hypertrophic cardiomyopathy','A subspecies can be defined as an aggregate of phenotypically similar populations of a species inhabiting a geographic subdivision of the range of that species and differing taxonomically from other populations of that species (Mayr and Ashlock 1991). Defining subspecies has been important for evolutionary theories and conservation efforts, but there is not a general standard for defining a subspecies. Historically, subspecies have been defined based on morphology, but with recent technological advancements, many are using genetics to define subspecies.  While defining a species may never have a straightforward answer, we hope to ask a question that may: Does using certain subspecies databases affect subsequent analyses? In other words, are the genomes of subspecies so different that using the same genome for analyzing both subspecies would produce erroneous results? These questions arose after a study aimed at identifying a biomarker for hypertrophic cardiomyopathy in southern sea otters (Enhydra lutris nereis) used the northern sea otter genome (Enhydra lutris kenyoni) for their analysis (Johnson et al., 2021). We compare the impact of the bioinformatic tools used to generate the proteomic and genomic databases to define the major differences between subspecies in identifying the biomarker Complement C8 in hypertrophic cardiomypathy.  \r\n','[{\"name\":\"Andrasz, Cassidy\",\"email\":\"candrasz@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Biological Sciences\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"no\",\"presenter\":\"yes\"},\r\n{\"name\":\"Johnson, Kieran\",\"email\":\"johnsonhr.2013@gmail.com\",\"affiliation\":\"Biological Sciences\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"no\",\"presenter\":\"yes\"},\r\n{\"name\":\"Vernola, Daniel\",\"email\":\"dvernola@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Biological Sciences\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"no\",\"presenter\":\"yes\"},\r\n{\"name\":\"Doebling, Augie\",\"email\":\"wdoeblin@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Other...\",\"other_affiliation\":\"Computer Sciences\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"no\",\"presenter\":\"no\"},\r\n{\"name\":\"Davidson, Jean\",\"email\":\"jdavid06@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Biological Sciences\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Faculty\",\"frost\":\"no\"},\r\n{\"name\":\"Anderson, Paul\",\"email\":\"pander14@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Biological Sciences\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Faculty\",\"frost\":\"no\"}]','9:00am-10:30am,10:30am-12:00pm',NULL,'2022-04-15 02:57:58',5,'9:00-10:45','10-10:15','180-261'),(69,'90fa26b30ec54c3a45a14663bfe7af40','2022','poster','[[De-novo]] genome assembly and comparative gene expression of [[Kelletia kelletii]], the Kellets Whelk','[[Kelletia kelletii]], commonly known as Kellets Whelk, is a marine gastropod mollusc that lives in kelp forests and on rocky reef habitat along the coast of Monterey, California to Baja, California. Due to its expanding biogeographical range and the distinct biotic and abiotic factors at each location, there is bound to be differential expression of genes within each subpopulation as the whelks acclimate to their current conditions. Our group is establishing a [[de-novo]] draft genome assembly with PacBio long read sequencing scaffolds and Illumina short read sequencing polishing.  We are using this genome to understand more about the phylogenomic relationships of the Kellets Whelk and its related species.  We are also using this genome to create a genome guided - reference transcriptome from RNA-seq data collected by colleagues and analyze the implications of differential expression on the overall molecular deviations between different populations of this marine gastropod. The Kellets Whelk lab recently collected egg capsules and conducted RNA sequencing on 70 samples which were collected from four geographical locations and gene expression data was collected.  We are now conducting differential expression analysis in order to understand what sets these geographically separated populations apart genetically. By discovering what genes are differentially expressed, we may be able to better understand how the whelks acclimate to varying conditions across the coast of California and how the populations differ on an epigenetic scale.\n','[{\"name\":\"Daniels, Ben\",\"email\":\"bndaniel@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Biological Sciences\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"yes\"},{\"name\":\"Andrasz, Cassidy\",\"email\":\"candrasz@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Biological Sciences\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"no\"},{\"name\":\"Zarate, Nicholas\",\"email\":\"nezarate@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Biological Sciences\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"no\"},{\"name\":\"Joshua, Isaac\",\"email\":\"ijoshua@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Other...\",\"other_affiliation\":\"Biomedical Engineering\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"no\"},{\"name\":\"De Smet, Chanel\",\"email\":\"cldesmet@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Biological Sciences\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"yes\"},{\"name\":\"White, Crow\",\"email\":\"cwhite31@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Biological Sciences\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Faculty\",\"frost\":\"no\"},{\"name\":\"Anderson, Paul\",\"email\":\"pander14@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Biological Sciences\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Faculty\",\"frost\":\"no\"},{\"name\":\"Davidson, Jean\",\"email\":\"jdavid06@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Biological Sciences\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Faculty\",\"frost\":\"yes\"}]','','We know how to make one','2022-04-15 03:17:25',42,NULL,NULL,NULL),(70,'2435085f87c9eb4c0febdc461851ae6f','2022','poster','Nuestra Ciencia: Teaching Microbiology in Spanish ','We describe the university-elementary bilingual partnership Nuestra Ciencia, which tackles two parallel sets of challenges, the first about recruitment and retention of Latinx people into STEM professions, and the second related to generalized microbiology misconceptions, such as how vaccines and antibiotics work. Nuestra Ciencia addresses both, as we develop engaging experiments for elementary school students that illustrate microbiology concepts, and visit bilingual classrooms to lead the experiments in Spanish. In addition to classroom activities, we provide bilingual instructional materials to take home and develop pre-activity questionnaires that involve families in science discussions.\nIn this poster, we outline the background, goals and components of the program, review activities developed, and share potential impact and lessons learned. Our research questions include what are elementary students\' microbiology preconceptions and relevant ideas from everyday life, what are students\' attitudes towards science and scientists, and whether participation in Nuestra Ciencia impacts those preconceptions and attitudes.\nOur ongoing work focuses on developing and piloting a set of activities related to the SARS-CoV-2 pandemic for grades 4-6, each focused on teaching one of the following concepts: basic epidemiology of respiratory virus transmission, mechanism of action of vaccines, and herd immunity.  We have developed and piloted a virtual lesson on vaccines, and we are currently working on a hands-on activity explaining the concept of herd immunity.','[{\"name\":\"Yep, Alejandra\",\"email\":\"yep@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Biological Sciences\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Faculty\",\"frost\":\"no\"},{\"name\":\"Nation, Jasmine\",\"email\":\"jmnation@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Liberal Studies\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Faculty\",\"frost\":\"no\"},{\"name\":\"Reyes, Hector\",\"email\":\"hfreyes@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Other...\",\"other_affiliation\":\"Psychology and Child Development\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"no\"},{\"name\":\"Ceja, Natali\",\"email\":\"naceja@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Other...\",\"other_affiliation\":\"Biomedical Engineering\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"no\"},{\"name\":\"De Smet, Chanel\",\"email\":\"cldesmet@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Biological Sciences\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"no\"},{\"name\":\"Landaverde-Ortega, Ariann\",\"email\":\"adlandav@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Other...\",\"other_affiliation\":\"Environmental Sciences\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"no\"}]','','We can attend April 19, 5-6pm','2022-04-15 03:22:41',43,NULL,NULL,NULL),(71,'01a3709a9c49169980592f471dca9262','2022','poster','[[De novo]] genome assembly of [[Botrylloides violaceus]] creates foundation for studying whole body regeneration','[[Botrylloides violaceus]] is a colonial tunicate able to undergo whole-body regeneration. This species is an invertebrate chordate and therefore more closely related to vertebrates than typical model organisms for regeneration. Due to this unique phylogenetic relationship, Cal Poly students recently sequenced and assembled its genome to study its regenerative capacity. The genome was drafted using a hybrid assembly technique combining both Illumina and Oxford Nanopore Technologies sequencing data. Annotation of the genome revealed elements including genes of the Wnt gene family, which encodes signaling molecules involved in regenerative processes. Comparative genomics of the Wnt gene family suggests candidate family members that may be involved in this high regenerative capacity; experimental data regarding gene expression are needed to explore functional roles for Wnt proteins and other signaling path components. Current efforts are in developing RNA isolation protocols and designing primers, utilizing the newly annotated genome, to target the Wnt family genes. Ultimately, a deeper understanding of the regenerative capacity of these organisms will be illuminated through bioinformatic analysis of genomic and transcriptomic data.','[{\"name\":\"Andrasz, Cassidy\",\"email\":\"candrasz@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Biological Sciences\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"yes\"},{\"name\":\"Wax, Sarah\",\"email\":\"smwax@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Biological Sciences\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"no\"},{\"name\":\"Fernandes, Keona\",\"email\":\"kferna22@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Biological Sciences\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"no\"},{\"name\":\"Sumner, Jack\",\"email\":\"jacksumner22@gmail.com\",\"affiliation\":\"Biological Sciences\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"yes\"},{\"name\":\"Johnson, Christine\",\"email\":\"christineejohnson12@gmail.com\",\"affiliation\":\"Biological Sciences\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"no\"},{\"name\":\"Anderson, Paul\",\"email\":\"pander14@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Other...\",\"other_affiliation\":\"Department of Computer Science and Software Engineering\",\"role\":\"Faculty\",\"frost\":\"no\"},{\"name\":\"Davidson, Jean\",\"email\":\"jdavid06@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Biological Sciences\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Faculty\",\"frost\":\"no\"},{\"name\":\"Keeling, Elena\",\"email\":\"ekeeling@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Biological Sciences\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Faculty\",\"frost\":\"no\"}]','','We would like to attend a workshop but CANNOT attend on Tuesday April 19, 5:10-6pm','2022-04-15 03:44:43',44,NULL,NULL,NULL),(72,'5373454e913124f636dc89df37b81101','2022','poster','Use of small-scale classroom experiments to inform simulation-based statistical inference (SBI) pedagogy in tertiary classrooms','In order to help students understand statistical inference, we have been using different simulation strategies and representations of those strategies, e.g., PowerPoint animations, tactile/physical simulations, and computer-based simulations. We have also been investigating the effectiveness of each of these strategies on student understanding of key concepts. The general framework is the same for each strategy: carrying out repeated re-randomizations and building a \"null\" distribution. This research involves examining the impact of different levels of student involvement in creating this distribution (e.g., reading about creating the distribution vs. actively participating in creating the distribution). Students are randomly assigned to slightly different pre-lab assignments. For example, students may be asked to shuffle index cards and record results, or be asked to view a PowerPoint animation of the process, or be asked to perform a few trials in a free online applet. All students will then answer the same set of multiple-choice questions about the underlying statistical principles. Our prior suspicion is that direct student involvement may be preferable to instructor demonstration, but that is only based on opinion.','[{\"name\":\"Chung, Sophia\",\"email\":\"spchung@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Statistics\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"yes\"},{\"name\":\"Chance, Beth\",\"email\":\"bchance@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Statistics\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Faculty\",\"frost\":\"yes\"}]','','We can attend April 19, 5-6pm','2022-04-15 05:01:53',45,NULL,NULL,NULL),(73,'9998ba383695e1d149621cbbc939220d','2022','talk','Part I: [[In vitro]] Analysis of the Interaction Between Phosphomimetic Mutants of Human YB-1 protein and the HIV Gag protein','Human immunodeficiency virus (HIV) affects millions of people worldwide and current issues like the Covid-19 pandemic and climate change are predicted to increase the spread of this virus. YB-1, a human RNA binding protein, is involved in RNA loading of extracellular vesicles and has been implicated in successful assembly of retroviral progeny. In human tissue culture, post-translational phosphorylation of YB-1 has been implicated as a requirement for the protein\'s activity in a variety of published assays, but the effect of these modifications on HIV assembly is unknown. To examine if phosphorylation affects interactions between YB-1 and the HIV capsid protein Gag, phosphomimetic forms of YB-1, where phosphorylated serine residues (S) are mimicked by replacing them with aspartate (D) residues, were constructed. Previous work in the lab has generated eight expression constructs with the following versions of the YBX1 gene (encoding YB-1 protein): wild type, S102D, S165D, S176D, S102D+S165D, S102D+S176D, S165D+S176D, and S102D+S165D+S176D. Each of these YB-1 versions and the HIV Gag coding region were cloned into bacterial expression vectors for expression and purification of the proteins. To evaluate the interaction between YB-1 and Gag, co-immunoprecipitation was performed [[in vitro]] in the presence or absence of HIV genomic RNA. Results will be provided that show only certain phosphomimetic versions of YB-1 interact with HIV Gag, suggesting that particular residues in YB-1 may require post-translational modification for the protein to participate in HIV assembly.','[{\"name\":\"Peter-Contesse, Sierra\",\"email\":\"speterco@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Biological Sciences\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"no\"},{\"name\":\"Geitner, David\",\"email\":\"dgeitner@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Biological Sciences\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"no\"},{\"name\":\"Gopan, Vinay\",\"email\":\"vgopan@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Biological Sciences\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"no\"},{\"name\":\"Black, Michael \",\"email\":\"mblack@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Biological Sciences\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Faculty\",\"frost\":\"no\"}]','10:30am-12:00pm',NULL,'2022-04-15 05:28:03',38,'1:00-2:45','2:15-2:30','180-270'),(74,'bb12ad6bf080032280f37b120c3bb7c3','2022','poster','Measuring Thermal Conductivity of Insulating Materials ','In our quest to build low-cost, insulated cooking for the global poor, we are making carbon foam by pyrolyzing bread, shown to be an effective and low-cost thermal insulator. Even though bread-derived foam is cheaper to produce than polymer-derived foams, expensive vacuum chambers, inert gases, and temperature-controlled furnaces are used. We produce carbon foam of similar thermal conductivity using inexpensive equipment. Our other goal is to test the impact of different leavening agents on the thermal conductivity of the carbon foam.  Standard instruments for measuring very low thermal conductivity cost upwards of 30,000 dollars. The total cost of making our instrument (now available as a Cal Poly user facility) is less than 1,500 dollars. ','[{\"name\":\"Schwartz, Peter\",\"email\":\"pschwart@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Physics\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Faculty\",\"frost\":\"no\"},{\"name\":\"Dalsin, Michael\",\"email\":\"mdalsin@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Physics\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"yes\"},{\"name\":\"Lazzara, Hudson\",\"email\":\"hlazzara@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Physics\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"no\"},{\"name\":\"Cobb, Isabelle\",\"email\":\"icobb@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Physics\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"no\"}]','','We would like to attend a workshop but CANNOT attend on Tuesday April 19, 5:10-6pm','2022-04-15 05:45:58',46,NULL,NULL,NULL),(75,'381251827c6d3bead64ef17c15540005','2022','talk','Correlation Between Social Media Use and Eating Disorder Symptoms: A Senior Project Literature Review','Social media has become a pervasive influence in modern society presenting many potential public health implications. The long-term impacts of chronic social media use are not thoroughly understood in current research. The purpose of this literature review is to explore the correlation between social media use and eating disorders in current primary research. Peer-reviewed articles published within the last five years were gathered from Google Scholar and the OneSearch databases using the combination of search terms \"social media\" and \"eating disorder\" (January-February, 2022). The resulting articles included four cross-sectional studies and two social media content analyses. Each of the cross-sectional studies found a significant correlation between increased social media use and increased rates and severity of eating disorder symptoms. Thematic analysis of two social media platforms revealed trends in eating disorder content on social media including body inspiration, gamified content, and overlap of eating disorders with other mental illnesses. The strong correlation found across multiple studies indicates that social media use could be a risk factor in the development and severity of eating disorders in various populations. This risk appears to increase with exposure to specific types of social media content that relate to eating disorders. The proposed mechanism of this correlation is the act of body comparison that social media encourages. Social media habits should be considered in the prevention and treatment of eating disorders. Future research should explore this correlation further in attempt to find a causal relationship as well as study new social media platforms.  \n','[{\"name\":\"Burger, Makenna R.\",\"email\":\"mrburger@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Kinesiology and Public Health\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"no\"},{\"name\":\"Thomas, Jafra D.\",\"email\":\"jthoma84@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Kinesiology and Public Health\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Faculty\",\"frost\":\"no\"}]','9:00am-10:30am,10:30am-12:00pm,1:00pm-3:00pm','','2022-04-15 07:01:04',21,'1:00-2:45','1-1:15','180-261'),(76,'028bcbeea02117a2e5d0bd2d57b1e9ec','2022','talk','Nanohybrid Reinforced PVA Coating of Packaging Paper','Most paper packaging is coated in a petroleum based polymer to protect from moisture, oxidization, bacteria, etc. Unfortunately, such petroleum based polymer coating cannot be easily degraded or recycled, resulting in significant plastic pollution to the environment. Biodegradable alternatives such as poly(vinyl alcohol) (PVA) are highly desirable in the packaging industry although PVA does not have comparable properties to the petroleum based polymers. An effective method of producing high performance sustainable coatings is adding nanoparticles to the PVA coating. In this work, we report nanohybrid reinforced PVA coating of packaging paper. Nanohybrids consist of  1D cellulose nanofibrils (CNF) and 2D graphene oxide (GO). The coating formulation is prepared and the physical properties are investigated by means of various techniques. \r\n','[{\"name\":\"Lambert, Isabel\",\"email\":\"islamber@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Chemistry and Biochemistry\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"no\",\"presenter\":\"yes\"},{\"name\":\"Schleinitz, Madeleine\",\"email\":\"mschlein@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Chemistry and Biochemistry\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"no\"},{\"name\":\"Gamez, Isabel\",\"email\":\"igamez@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Chemistry and Biochemistry\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"no\"},{\"name\":\"Zhang, Shanju\",\"email\":\"szhang05@calpoly.edu \",\"affiliation\":\"Chemistry and Biochemistry\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Faculty\",\"frost\":\"no\"}]','9:00am-10:30am,10:30am-12:00pm,1:00pm-3:00pm',NULL,'2022-04-15 15:19:29',16,'9:00-10:45','9:30-9:45','180-270'),(77,'ff9d79bfb53e9d3ee0b3594f843cb462','2022','poster','Antimicrobial Activity of Oregano Oil Against a Bacterial Entomopathogen ','With the rise and growing prevalence of antibiotic resistance, there is an increased urgency to discover and develop new treatments for bacterial infections. Essential oils and other plant-based extracts have been utilized in alternative medicinal practices for thousands of years. Essential oils and plant-based derivatives show great potential for treating bacterial infections because of their varied modes of action. Our laboratory has developed a flexible invertebrate animal model to explore the therapeutic effects of antibacterial compounds against a bacterial pathogen that is commonly lethal for the host. For this study, we sought to evaluate the effectiveness of the essential oils, oregano and clove, to treat the entomopathogen, Serratia marcescens in Nauphoeta cinerea (lobster cockroach). In vitro experiments, including Minimal Inhibitory Concentration Plates, were first used. The antibacterial properties of oregano oil were established, however clove was not found to be as effective. Next, in vivo, roaches were injected with S. marcescens, treated with oregano oil, and survival rates were recorded as compared to positive and negative controls. Initial results of our experiment establish that oregano oil has antibacterial properties in vitro, however, the concentration of this oil tested was also lethal to the cockroach negative controls. Future studies will explore lower concentrations of oregano oil for in vivo testing, and additional types of essential oils will be explored using this protocol.','[{\"name\":\"Walsh, Ellie\",\"email\":\"egwalsh@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Biological Sciences\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"no\"},{\"name\":\"Wong, Nick\",\"email\":\"nwong48@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Biological Sciences\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"no\"},{\"name\":\"Vredevoe, Larisa\",\"email\":\"lvredevo@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Biological Sciences\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Faculty\",\"frost\":\"no\"}]','','We can attend April 19, 5-6pm','2022-04-15 16:07:48',47,NULL,NULL,NULL),(78,'e4c4d93cd561cec8acfae7d6e50318ab','2022','poster','Baby fur on baby seals: Morphology and thermal function of the pelts of Weddell seal pups ','The Weddell seal (Leptonychotes weddellii) is the southernmost breeding mammal on Earth. These Antarctic seals are born in extreme conditions with lanugo fur (neonatal fur) and no blubber layer, and yet need to maintain a body temperature similar to ours. Unlike many phocid (true seal) pups, Weddell seals begin swimming and diving in polar waters around two weeks of age, before they have molted their lanugo fur or developed a substantial blubber layer. Because seawater is 25x more conductive than air, this is especially thermally challenging to young pups. This study compares the morphological characteristics (hair length, circularity, and density) and thermal function (thermal resistance) of Weddell seal lanugo pelts (n=6) and adult pelts (n=5) in air and in water. As expected, both pelt types had reduced thermal resistance in water compared to air. However, neonate pelts had higher thermal resistance than adult pelts in both conditions, largely because lanugo hairs are longer. Next, we will relate additional aspects of pelt morphology (hair circularity and density) to how the pelts function as insulators in air and water. These results highlight the importance of the blubber layer for thermoregulation in adult Weddell seals, and have implications for how climatic changes such as increased temperature and melting of fast ice (their breeding habitat) will impact the species\' long-term survival.','[{\"name\":\"Liwanag, Heather\",\"email\":\"hliwanag@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Biological Sciences\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Faculty\",\"frost\":\"yes\"},{\"name\":\"Twisk, Dana \",\"email\":\"dtwisk@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Biological Sciences\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"yes\"},{\"name\":\"Taylor, Allyson \",\"email\":\"ataylo64@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Biological Sciences\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"yes\"}]','','We would like to attend a workshop but CANNOT attend on Tuesday April 19, 5:10-6pm','2022-04-15 16:49:39',48,NULL,NULL,NULL),(79,'e412179f5d9f1205017f152c00fa6fc6','2022','poster','Antimicrobial properties of Ganjang Gejang Marinade on Foodborne Pathogens','Marinades utilize the purportedly natural antimicrobial properties of its ingredients to prevent foodborne illnesses. Ganjang Gejang is a seafood dish utilizing a soy sauce marinade to preserve crabs before they are eaten raw. Even though the raw crabs can result in food poisoning, it remains a popular meal. Previous studies showed that soy sauce marination was effective at inactivating Vibrio parahaemolyticus in Ganjang Gejang, but the marinade was ineffective at inactivating gram positive bacteria.  Further antimicrobial measures were suggested to ensure consumer safety (Cho, et. al, 2016). This study investigates a modified Ganjang Gejang marinade containing lime, cinnamon, pomegranate peel, and thyme to increase antibacterial effectiveness. The antimicrobial properties of the marinade were determined based on the survival of Salmonella enterica and Listeria monocytogenes in the marinade over time. In phase one of the study, microbes were inoculated in an unmodified marinade at 27 C, and cell count was recorded every two hours. There was a significant negative relationship between S. enterica log(cfu/mL) and time (R2=0.87, df=2, p=0.046) whereas L. monocytogenes had no significant relationship between log(cfu/mL) and time (R2=-0.37, df=2, p=0.71).   The antimicrobial effect of modified marinade will be tested. In phase two, the same microbes will be inoculated onto canned crab meat using the most effective modified marinades recipes based on the results from phase 1. The crab meat will be stomached, stored at 4 C, and cell count will be recorded for over 6 days.  Our findings will show that food preparation plays a factor in food safety, and the modified Ganjang Gejang marinade will likely have increased antimicrobial properties.','[{\"name\":\"Lee, Suzie \",\"email\":\"slee363@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Biological Sciences\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"yes\"},{\"name\":\"Yeung, Marie\",\"email\":\"pmyeung@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Biological Sciences\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Faculty\",\"frost\":\"yes\"}]','','We would like to attend a workshop but CANNOT attend on Tuesday April 19, 5:10-6pm','2022-04-15 17:12:56',49,NULL,NULL,NULL),(80,'54b514f3acce2b5d3a22d8652cdb296e','2022','poster','Student-Athlete Professional Identity and Transition','Student-athletes often struggle with the transition from undergraduate to graduate programs due to the lack of information and resources offered. There is a lack of research and focus on student-athletes due to the fact that they are considered a vulnerable population. Additionally, the impact of the COVID-19 pandemic gave student-athletes an extra year of eligibility which gives them the opportunity of attending a graduate program. This study consists of a qualitative analysis of student-athlete populations to enhance their experience at Cal Poly. The purpose of this research project is to analyze the level of preparedness of student-athletes as they go through the transition from college athletics to post-undergraduate life. Engaging with student-athletes through the use of surveys and interviews provided insight into their experiences as well as the difficulties and challenges they face. We hope to make more resources accessible to student-athletes to allow them to take advantage of their eligibility.','[{\"name\":\"Vardanyan, Gary\",\"email\":\"kvardany@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Kinesiology and Public Health\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"no\"},{\"name\":\"Wang, Vanessa\",\"email\":\"vwang13@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Other...\",\"other_affiliation\":\"CAFES- EIM\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"no\"},{\"name\":\"Maurice, Stefanee\",\"email\":\"somauric@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Kinesiology and Public Health\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Faculty\",\"frost\":\"no\"},{\"name\":\"Greenwood, Brian\",\"email\":\"pgreenwo@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Other...\",\"other_affiliation\":\"CAFES- EIM\",\"role\":\"Faculty\",\"frost\":\"no\"},{\"name\":\"Torgerson, Louise\",\"email\":\"ltorgers@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Kinesiology and Public Health\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Faculty\",\"frost\":\"no\"},{\"name\":\"Avrit, Darren\",\"email\":\"davrit@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Kinesiology and Public Health\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Faculty\",\"frost\":\"no\"}]',NULL,NULL,'2022-04-15 17:24:46',50,NULL,NULL,NULL),(81,'bcaa6bcb2e4424ef928f165553309b95','2022','poster','A Look Into Patterns of Heterolocalism Among Chinese Immigrants in Philadelphia','Neighborhood contextual and social factors are an important aspect of the social determinants of health. Previous literature has shown associations between living in immigrant enclave neighborhoods and risk for various health conditions. However, these studies have not looked at factors outside of immigrant enclave neighborhoods such as where people travel for daily activities. Heterolocalism is a concept that explores how immigrants connect to new settings without clustering amongst co-ethnics.  This approach allows researchers to examine how immigrants maintain ties to their ethnic community despite immediate or rapid spatial dispersion and to look more deeply into what neighborhood factors affect health. The study collected location-based data for employment, grocery stores, religious services, healthcare services, and leisure activities. ArcGIS was utilized to conduct a spatial analysis to examine the distance traveled to each of these activities and categorized participants into whether they live in an enclave, emerging enclave, or not an enclave. In preliminary analyses, we found that Chinese immigrants in enclave neighborhoods were most likely to stay in their enclave for groceries and least likely to stay near their enclave for healthcare services. A further analysis of the time spent in the activity zones and frequency of visits will establish a better understanding of heterolocalism in this population. ','[{\"name\":\"Batterson, Ella\",\"email\":\"erbatter@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Kinesiology and Public Health\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"yes\"},{\"name\":\"Tseng, Marilyn\",\"email\":\"mtseng@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Kinesiology and Public Health\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Faculty\",\"frost\":\"no\"},{\"name\":\"Ngov, Anthony\",\"email\":\"angov@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Kinesiology and Public Health\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"no\"},{\"name\":\"Fong, Natalie\",\"email\":\"nfong01@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Kinesiology and Public Health\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"no\"}]','','We would like to attend a workshop but CANNOT attend on Tuesday April 19, 5:10-6pm','2022-04-15 17:32:47',51,NULL,NULL,NULL),(82,'2f831315b6fc77c23e8dfd2eade334ce','2022','poster','The Importance of Health Literacy: A Student-Led Workshop on Lay Communication','The purpose of this experiential senior project was to advance the knowledge and practice of health communication by (a) exploring the relationship between health literacy and effective communication and (b) delivering an educational workshop to Cal Poly undergraduate students. Through the completion of a rapid review of the literature, workshop materials were designed to elicit a foundational understanding of elements for effective communication of health information as well as the history and evolution of health literacy as a concept. With the stated goal to provide undergraduate students with practical skills for effectively communicating health information to a lay adult audience and an awareness of health literacy and the role of plain language in promoting health literacy, the workshop content was adapted from materials first developed by Dr. Jafra Thomas (2020). After the workshop\'s conclusion, student participants were successfully able to define health literacy and identify tips for effective communication of health information. This submission presents the student\'s reflection on their experiential project, the review of literature, identified key elements for an educationally effective workshop on the topic, evaluation and analysis of participant pre-and post-workshop surveys, and finally, suggestions for improvements to the workshop including the addition of personal anecdotes and case studies.','[{\"name\":\"Kamp, Sarah J\",\"email\":\"skamp@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Kinesiology and Public Health\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"no\"},{\"name\":\"Thomas, Jafra D\",\"email\":\"jthoma84@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Kinesiology and Public Health\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Faculty\",\"frost\":\"no\"}]','','We would like to attend a workshop but CANNOT attend on Tuesday April 19, 5:10-6pm','2022-04-15 17:52:27',52,NULL,NULL,NULL),(83,'3da7cafaf5be4e875767fdab926d1f86','2022','talk','Extracting and Correcting Neutron Kinetic Energy from Neutron Time-of-Flight in the NIFFTE Experiment and Energy Analysis using SRIM','The Neutron Induced Fission Fragment Tracking Experiment (NIFFTE) investigates nuclear fission using pulsed beams provided by the Los Alamos Neutron Science Center (LANSCE). One of the goals of this analysis was to accurately determine the neutron energy from neutron time-of-flight (nToF) and correcting for wraparound, which happens when faster neutrons arrive simultaneously with slower neutrons that were emitted earlier. Another goal of this analysis was to investigate energy loss of alpha particles using data obtained with simulations from the Stopping Ranges of Ions in Matter (SRIM) software. Energy loss can be characterized with a Bragg curve from which comparisons between curve profiles and total energy loss can be made. Analysis details and current results will be presented.','[{\"name\":\"Aguilar, Vanessa\",\"email\":\"vaguil02@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Physics\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"no\"},{\"name\":\"Klay, Jennifer\",\"email\":\"jklay@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Physics\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Faculty\",\"frost\":\"no\"}]','10:30am-12:00pm,1:00pm-3:00pm','','2022-04-15 18:30:54',11,'9:00-10:45','9:45-10','180-266'),(84,'9ac5e33d258dd7a90e99207a887af877','2022','poster','qPCR Analysis of Relative Telomere Length in Bluebird Nestlings','Telomeres are repetitive nucleotide sequences at the ends of chromosomes that protect them from degradation and can be lengthened to counteract chromosome shortening when cells divide. In various species, including humans and birds, telomeres shorten with age and in response to various environmental and physiological stressors. We are developing protocols to use quantitative real-time PCR assays (qPCR) to measure relative telomere length in blood samples from Western bluebird nestlings exposed to varying levels of noise. Relative telomere length is the ratio of telomere repeat copy number (T) to single gene copy number (S). We hypothesize that because noise induces a physiological stress response in bluebirds, bluebirds exposed to noise will have shorter relative telomere lengths than bluebirds not exposed. Our primary goal is to determine whether these expected differences in relative telomere length are detectable in bluebird nestlings.','[{\"name\":\"Upp, Sarah\",\"email\":\"supp@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Biological Sciences\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"no\"},{\"name\":\"Sachi Watanabe, Ren\",\"email\":\"rswatana@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Biological Sciences\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"no\"},{\"name\":\"Gonur, Kavana\",\"email\":\"kgonur@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Biological Sciences\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"no\"},{\"name\":\"Keeling, Elena\",\"email\":\"ekeeling@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Biological Sciences\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Faculty\",\"frost\":\"no\"}]','','We would like to attend a workshop but CANNOT attend on Tuesday April 19, 5:10-6pm','2022-04-15 18:51:43',53,NULL,NULL,NULL),(85,'4618d883f8ba0dfd62798d21a42d66f1','2022','talk','Testing and linkage to care for HCV at SSP: Expanding access and lowering barriers for treatment','People who inject drugs (PWID) are at high risk for acquiring blood borne pathogens such as Hepatitis C Virus (HCV) and HIV. Syringe services programs (SSP) are thus necessary for preventing the spread of communicable diseases and serve as ideal locations for screening and linkage to care. SLO Bangers SSP has implemented a multimodal approach to treating HCV by providing incentivized testing and treatment coupled with on-site collaborative tele-health and linkage to local care. Due to advancements in treatment, we will also explore how direct acting antivirals treat HCV and the ways in which this medication has impacted barriers to treatment for PWID. SSPs are mindful of the contextual and environmental supports and barriers that people injecting drugs are affected by and have built trust with their participants. On site testing and linkage to care will help streamline progress towards curing HCV in a safe and familiar environment.','[{\"name\":\"Lavorando, Maya\",\"email\":\"mlavoran@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Biological Sciences\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"no\"},{\"name\":\"Winstead, Candace\",\"email\":\"cwinstea@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Biological Sciences\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Faculty\",\"frost\":\"no\"}]','9:00am-10:30am,10:30am-12:00pm','','2022-04-15 19:30:16',6,'9:00-10:45','10:15-10:30','180-261'),(86,'91f900d8157c215f3cd2f4b7dad5d143','2022','talk','Network Analysis of COVID 19 in the United States','Using methods from network theory and time-series analysis we will investigate the spread of COVID 19 cases in the United States. Through network theory we will be able to see how the pandemic started and continues to be endemic in the US. Using correlations between COVID 19 cases in US states and territories we will establish a network structure and analyze its characteristics. We will review previous research done in this area. With an eye on what community detection and network statistics have to tell us about how the pandemic spreads from state to state.','[{\"name\":\"McGuire, Joseph\",\"email\":\"jmcgui05@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Mathematics\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"no\"},{\"name\":\"Dimitrova, Elena\",\"email\":\"edimitro@calpoly.esu\",\"affiliation\":\"Mathematics\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Faculty\",\"frost\":\"no\"}]','1:00pm-3:00pm','','2022-04-15 19:45:57',35,'1:00-2:45','1:30-1:45','180-270'),(87,'18036109b3d150492c5fbade2cb35c10','2022','poster','Flat Portions on Numerical Ranges of Nilpotent Matrices','In their 2008 paper, Gau and Wu conjectured a maximum number of flat portions on the boundary of the numerical range of a general nilpotent n x n matrix (n - 2 for n <= 5 and 2(n - 4) for n >= 6). Using the associated Kippenhahn curve and its algebraic geometry, we explore key observations about the behavior of these Kippenahahn curves and their effects on the flat portions on the boundary of a numerical range. Illustrative examples of conjectured maximal cases are included.','[{\"name\":\"Lowrey, Kelsey\",\"email\":\"klowrey@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Mathematics\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"yes\"},{\"name\":\"Royston, Tim\",\"email\":\"ttroysto@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Mathematics\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"yes\"},{\"name\":\"Zieber, Karl\",\"email\":\"krzieber@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Mathematics\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"yes\"},{\"name\":\"Patton, Linda\",\"email\":\"lpatton@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Mathematics\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Faculty\",\"frost\":\"yes\"}]','','We have one already','2022-04-15 19:52:19',54,NULL,NULL,NULL),(88,'6c1149c7f940b1aca756f35740c43d3a','2022','poster','Acute changes in cutaneous evaporative water loss of lizards as a function of temperature','Cutaneous evaporative water loss (CEWL) is one of the primary ways reptiles lose water to their environment. As an adaptive and plastic trait, CEWL is an important area of study as climate change presents new challenges to reptiles\' ability to osmoregulate. Lipids are one of the primary barriers to CEWL in snakes and lizards. Given that lipid membrane permeability to water is directly related to temperature, we studied CEWL plasticity in response to acute change in temperature in Western Fence Lizards (Sceloporus occidentalis). To test this, we either cooled or heated lizards to certain body temperatures, and then we warmed up the cold lizards and cooled down the hot lizards while continuously recording CEWL for 15 minutes using a handheld evaporimeter. We found that CEWL was positively related to temperature and is capable of instantaneous change on a second to minute basis. This suggests that the permeability of dermal lipids to water increased or decreased immediately, as a direct effect of the change in temperature. However, at the same body temperature, CEWL for cooling lizards was approximately half CEWL for heating lizards, which indicates that the biophysical properties of lipid membranes are not the only internal physiological mechanisms that may affect acute change in CEWL. These results demonstrate that CEWL is a plastic trait capable of immediate change in response to temperature, which could either help or harm organisms as global temperatures continue to rise.','[{\"name\":\"Davis, Calvin\",\"email\":\"cgdavis@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Biological Sciences\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"no\"},{\"name\":\"Weaver, Savannah\",\"email\":\" saweaver@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Biological Sciences\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"no\"},{\"name\":\"Taylor, Emily\",\"email\":\"etaylor@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Biological Sciences\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Faculty\",\"frost\":\"no\"}]','','We can attend April 19, 5-6pm','2022-04-15 20:12:29',55,NULL,NULL,NULL),(89,'24bd178ab4e92f49bb4bf2d11ce2bfab','2022','poster','An Investigation of Re-injury Anxiety in Club Sport Athletes','The purpose of this research was to examine the role re-injury anxiety and fear played in club sport athletes as they recovered from injury. Athletes grouped into collision, contact, or non-contact sport categories completed demographic questionnaires in addition to the Re-Injury Anxiety Inventory (Walker, Thatcher, & Lavallee, 2010). While recent data is still being processed, preliminary research has suggested that there is a correlation between the type of sport one plays and the influence of anxiety or fear on their recovery and return to sport. Further, trait anxiety may play a role in the level of anxiety an individual experiences during their recovery. Older data from a previous investigation will be paired with the current findings to form a more complete understanding of the topic. The results of this study will help foster a deeper understanding of the relationship between injury and re-injury anxiety that club sport athletes experience while undergoing rehabilitation for their injury.  \n','[{\"name\":\"Price, Lauren S.\",\"email\":\"lprice02@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Kinesiology and Public Health\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"no\"},{\"name\":\"Entenman, Connor S. \",\"email\":\"centenma@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Kinesiology and Public Health\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"no\"},{\"name\":\"Maurice, Stephanie \",\"email\":\"somauric@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Kinesiology and Public Health\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Faculty\",\"frost\":\"no\"}]','','We know how to make one','2022-04-15 20:12:54',56,NULL,NULL,NULL),(90,'bc0919dbf3506665e1922249830987d1','2022','poster','Ricci Curvature on Paley Graphs','We attempt to find the coarse Ricci curvature on Paley graphs. By exploring relations between primes, quadratic residues, and finite fields, we are able to derive a formula for the Ricci curvature of Paley graphs which have order equal to the even power of a prime.','[{\"name\":\"Semmens, Caroline\",\"email\":\"csemmens@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Mathematics\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"yes\"},{\"name\":\"Bonini, Vincent\",\"email\":\"vbonini@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Mathematics\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Faculty\",\"frost\":\"yes\"},{\"name\":\"Liu, Shiaohan\",\"email\":\"sliu21@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Mathematics\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"yes\"}]','','We know how to make one','2022-04-15 20:17:59',57,NULL,NULL,NULL),(91,'2f1d350ec535f8692a20ff1cf48fe811','2022','poster','Characterization of Norcardia farcinica N-Acetyl Glutamate Synthase','N-acetyl glutamate synthase (NAGS) is the enzyme that catalyzes the first step in prokaryotic arginine biosynthesis. The enzyme uses acetylCoA and glutamate to form N-acetyl glutamate and CoA. This study focuses on short NAGS (S-NAGS) enzymes which consist of a single domain and are relatively poorly characterized in contrast to the two domain, classical NAGS enzymes. A 22 kDa S-NAGS enzyme from [[Nocardia farcinica]] has been analyzed. Initial kinetic studies revealed that the enzyme utilizes both glutamate and glutamine as substrates, with kinetic parameters k$_{cat}$ = 39.2 s-1, K$_m$ = 250 mM, and k$_{cat}$  = 11.4 s-1, K$_m$= 200 mM, respectively. Inhibition studies showed strong regulation by L-arginine, with inhibition value IC$_{50}$=74$\\mu$M. More detailed kinetic studies suggested that the bisubstrate enzyme follows a sequential mechanism.  Comparison to classical and other S-NAGS enzymes will be discussed.','[{\"name\":\"Le, Hannah\",\"email\":\"hle35@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Chemistry and Biochemistry\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"yes\"},{\"name\":\"Bentley, Kristi\",\"email\":\"khbentle@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Chemistry and Biochemistry\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"no\"},{\"name\":\"Sheng, Yuting\",\"email\":\"yusheng@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Chemistry and Biochemistry\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"no\"},{\"name\":\"Bueno, Maria\",\"email\":\"mabueno@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Chemistry and Biochemistry\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Other\",\"frost\":\"no\"},{\"name\":\"Newton, Kass\",\"email\":\"knewto02@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Chemistry and Biochemistry\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Other\",\"frost\":\"no\"},{\"name\":\"Fogle, Emily\",\"email\":\"efogle@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Chemistry and Biochemistry\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Faculty\",\"frost\":\"no\"}]','','We know how to make one','2022-04-15 20:18:08',58,NULL,NULL,NULL),(92,'c00940d2165a09e05b4a972a075fca99','2022','talk','Creating a Cultural Relevant R-Shiny Using Census Data','The breakdown of race demographics in the US has changed dramatically since the last census in 2010. With many individuals moving to states on the West Coast, especially California, it has become one of the most diverse states in the country. But, how about the other states? How did they change throughout the decade? The goal of this research project was to create an interactive visualization to showcase the racial demographics within large cities in the United States. At first, we were set on using an API to access the entire country, but due to many trials and errors, we were unable to. The US cities included (i.e., San Francisco, Los Angeles, and New York). The data was extracted using a Census API to gather from the Census to visualize the racial demographics of the selected cities. An R Shiny was then created so that a user can select different cities and visualize the racial breakdown of the city. This work serves as a potential conduit to an activity for instructors to introduce culturally relevant data in the data science and statistics classrooms. The dataset and R Shiny app can be used to discuss the issues surrounding the lack of diversity in certain areas around the US. ','[{\"name\":\"Thai, Kevin\",\"email\":\"kthai03@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Statistics\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"yes\"},{\"name\":\"Williams, Immanuel\",\"email\":\"imwillia@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Statistics\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Faculty\",\"frost\":\"yes\"}]','','','2022-04-15 20:27:05',12,'9:00-10:45','10-10:15','180-266'),(93,'b7551d1a7d4f226ffa087a7c348a4c23','2022','poster','A Hammett Study on Ylidinenorbornadiene Dicarboxylate Fragmentations','Ylidinenorbornadiene dicarboxylate (YND) substrates were prepared by  [4 + 2] cycloaddition reactions between fulvenes and dimethylacetylenedicarboxylate. The YNDs react with beta-mercaptoethanol to yield YND-BMEs which undergo a retro [4 + 2] cycloaddition fragmentation. A Hammett study was performed on para-substituted phenylic YND-BMEs in order to determine the effect these substituents had on the kinetics of the retro [4 + 2] cycloaddition fragmentation. The results of this study indicate that resonance effects of electron donating groups provides the most stabilization of the asynchronous transition state for the fragmentation.   ','[{\"name\":\"McDonough, Elizabeth\",\"email\":\"eamcdono@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Chemistry and Biochemistry\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"yes\"},{\"name\":\"Bercovici, Dan\",\"email\":\"dbercovi@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Chemistry and Biochemistry\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Faculty\",\"frost\":\"yes\"}]','','We know how to make one','2022-04-15 21:23:28',59,NULL,NULL,NULL),(94,'57bbdc92a143be65f18cfbcc40e94762','2022','poster','Microplastic Presence in the Morro Bay Estuary','Plastic pollution is an emerging threat in marine ecosystems. Microplastics (MPs), fragments or fibers of plastic that are smaller than 5mm, are pervasive throughout marine ecosystems and are found in the gills and guts of the smallest marine organisms causing deleterious effects. Many surveys of microplastics have been completed along many stretches of coastline around the world. However, little research has been performed on plastic presence and their effects in estuarine environments, especially on California\'s Central Coast. The Morro Bay Estuary is a marine protected area heavily influenced by ecotourism and agricultural runoff and is susceptible to MP pollution. We started a long-term MP monitoring program to establish a baseline for MP presence, quantity, and type at three locations in the estuary. We sampled once monthly for MPs, processed and analyzed samples via 10% KOH digestion and density separation, vacuum filtered and fixed solutions onto glass fiber filters, and viewed filters with fluorescence microscopy with Nile Red and Calcofluor White stains. We found that all locations were present with MPs with the most abundant type being MP fibers. There were no significant differences in the abundance of MPs among sample sites each month or among the types of MPs found each month. Thus far, our findings indicate that MPs are present in the estuary, but only in low amounts. This study will serve as a baseline for long term monitoring and comparison among other locations. ','[{\"name\":\"Adams, Ashley\",\"email\":\"aadams53@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Biological Sciences\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"yes\"},{\"name\":\"Adams, Nikki\",\"email\":\"nadams@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Biological Sciences\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Faculty\",\"frost\":\"yes\"}]','','We can attend April 19, 5-6pm','2022-04-15 21:32:00',60,NULL,NULL,NULL),(95,'893aa322a7173c050dd794e9cc364880','2022','poster','The effect of intramolecular hydrogen bonding on ylidenenorbornadienedicarboxylate retro-[4+2] fragmentation.','Ylidenenorbornadienedicarboxylates (YNDs) have been shown to undergo a retro-[4+2] fragmentation after a conjugate addition of a thiol nucleophile. Previously, beta-mercaptoethanol (BME) has been used as a nucleophile. Mercaptopropane (MP) has now been utilized to synthesize YND-MPs as a steric homologue to YND-BMEs for determining the importance of the intramolecular hydrogen bond in YND-BME retro-[4+2] fragmentation kinetics. Kinetic trials at 80$^o$C utilizing $^1$H NMR spectroscopy were used to determine the rate of fragmentation of YND-BME and YND-MP in deuterodimethylsulfoxide (DMSO-d6) and deuterochloroform (CDCl$_3$).  Evidence suggests the hydroxyl has hydrogen bonding coordination with one carbonyl of the dicarboxylate, stabilizing the negative charge build-up in the transition state, causing a faster rate of fragmentation. ','[{\"name\":\"L\'Heureux, Scott\",\"email\":\"slheureu@clpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Chemistry and Biochemistry\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"yes\"},{\"name\":\"Bercovici, Daniel\",\"email\":\"dbercovi@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Chemistry and Biochemistry\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Faculty\",\"frost\":\"yes\"}]','','We would like to attend a workshop but CANNOT attend on Tuesday April 19, 5:10-6pm','2022-04-15 21:45:27',61,NULL,NULL,NULL),(96,'8cf448e1c5ea3c9b91ed0962d1c5f0d6','2022','talk','Saving a species from extinction on Anacapa Island','The northern island mallow, Malva assurgentiflora subsp. assurgentiflora, is a rare shrub endemic to Anacapa and San Miguel Islands,  two of the California Channel Islands located off the coast of southern California. Decades of grazing by introduced herbivores led to the extirpation of Malva on Anacapa Island. Fortunately, prior to extirpation, seeds were collected from the last remaining plants and used to create a new population on East Anacapa Island, where 1,000 individuals were planted by the National Park Service. In the years following restoration, however, the new population has failed to produce recruits despite the high reproductive output of each plant. This alarming lack of recruitment puts Malva at risk of future declines. To better understand where the greatest limitation to recruitment occurs during Malva life history, we tracked the fate of propagules during several early life-history stages. Experiments also measured propagule loss by the Anacapa deer mouse, a known seed predator of Malva. \n\nIn 2020, we began to track the fate of propagules under exposed and deer mouse excluded conditions for the following life history stages: (1) fruits prior to dispersal, (2) fruits after dispersal, (3) sewed seeds, and (4) seedlings. The greatest number of Malva propagules was lost during the pre-dispersal stage, where deer mice removed 70% of fruits from plants before maturation to viable fruits. Fruit maturation was 100% for treatments that excluded deer mice. Similarly, deer mice removed 50 to 100% of exposed dispersed fruit, with the greatest removal rates occurring during peak deer mouse density (Fall). Germination only occurred in treatments where deer mice were completely excluded from sewed seeds. However, 95% of seedlings died due to lack of water, regardless of exposure, showing that water availability may be more important for seedling survival than deer mouse predation. \n','[{\"name\":\"Calloway, Stephanie\",\"email\":\"smcallow@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Biological Sciences\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"no\"},{\"name\":\"Ritter, Matt\",\"email\":\"mritter@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Biological Sciences\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Faculty\",\"frost\":\"no\"},{\"name\":\"Yost, Jenn\",\"email\":\"jyost@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Biological Sciences\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Faculty\",\"frost\":\"no\"}]','9:00am-10:30am,10:30am-12:00pm','','2022-04-15 21:48:04',7,'9:00-10:45','10:30-10:45','180-261'),(97,'c968b74850f7b7f4485a5299e55ba5b8','2022','talk','Factors influencing reusable menstrual product choice: A review','Factors influencing contraceptives choice and reusable menstrual products are often studied as separate entities (Bekinska et al., 2015, Bitzer et al., 2013, Blackstone et al., 2017, Claringbold et al., 2019, vanEijk et al., 2021). This study reviewed global studies on factors influencing reusable menstrual product use among menstruators to observe any similarities to factors influencing hormonal contraception choice. A literature review was conducted, with 225 articles collected through multiple global databases. The articles were imported to Covidence for initial screening. From this, 77 duplicates were removed. The remaining were screened for relevance based on title and abstract. Any articles about reusable menstrual products and choices were sent to the following screening stage. From this stage, 65 articles were deemed irrelevant. Finally, the remaining articles were screened by full text. Only articles that investigated factors driving reusable menstrual product choice or use were included in this study. Common patterns emerged from the 40 articles eligible for review. Barriers to reusable menstrual product uptake include initial financial costs, discomfort, social norms, and issues with use. Some factors that encourage uptake include long-term financial benefits, environmental benefits, and support from acquaintances. Social norms and support from loved ones influence contraceptive choice and reusable menstrual product use. This conclusion stresses the importance of supportive relationships for individuals menstruating or considering contraception and the need for accurate reproductive health information to enable an informed choice.  \n\n ','[{\"name\":\"To, Arie\",\"email\":\"apto@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Kinesiology and Public Health\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"no\"},{\"name\":\"Roberts, Joni\",\"email\":\"jrober81@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Kinesiology and Public Health\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Faculty\",\"frost\":\"no\"}]','10:30am-12:00pm,1:00pm-3:00pm','','2022-04-15 21:56:03',25,'1:00-2:45','2-2:15','180-261'),(98,'7a231fdfc36f3cb6cbb1988ad0fb8acd','2022','talk','Studies of the UV-Visible Spectrum and Excited Electronic States of Dithiocarboxylate Derivatives through Photochemical and Thermal Reaction Pathways ','Derivatives of Dithiocarboxylates have been used in several photochemical transformations, but the electronic structure of the salt itself has only recently been reported. While stable under ambient conditions, dithiocarboxylates decompose upon long-term exposure to high-intensity UV light. Both the mechanism and products of this decomposition were unknown, but directly involved the chromophore as the signals in the Visible region of the absorption spectrum disappeared over time. Through investigation of the products of the photochemical probes, it was found that there are also thermal degradation pathways that can further functionalize the dithiocarboxylate functionality.  Under elevated temperatures, the dithiocarboxylate reacts with the ammonium counterion, directly resulting in the corresponding dithioesters. With two reactive pathways, photochemical and thermal, dithiocarboxylates can serve as interesting functional handles for building complex molecules.  Further development will focus on the scope of the reactivity in regard to the functionalization of the dithiocarboxylate as well as variations in the counterion.','[{\"name\":\"Bhat, Naveen\",\"email\":\"npbhat@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Chemistry and Biochemistry\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"yes\",\"presenter\":\"yes\"},{\"name\":\"Blechen, Kelsey\",\"email\":\"kblechen@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Chemistry and Biochemistry\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"yes\"},{\"name\":\"Zigler, David\",\"email\":\"dzigler@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Chemistry and Biochemistry\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Faculty\",\"frost\":\"yes\"},{\"name\":\"Haynes, M.Taylor\",\"email\":\"mthaynes@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Chemistry and Biochemistry\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Faculty\",\"frost\":\"yes\"}]','9:00am-10:30am,10:30am-12:00pm',NULL,'2022-04-15 22:03:04',17,'9:00-10:45','9:45-10','180-270'),(99,'b9bad593a9964ff330136378ad50e53c','2022','poster','Television Viewing and Mortality','Background: Several large observational studies have observed a strong, dose-response relationship between TV viewing and adverse health outcomes, including increased mortality risk from cardiovascular disease (CVD), and several of the leading causes of death. However, it remains controversial whether the associations are causal or due to confounding. The purpose of this analysis was to examine if the relationship between TV viewing and cause-specific mortality is explained by confounding by employing a negative control outcome in a large nationally representative survey. Methods: Our study uses annual data from the National Health and Nutrition Examination Survey (NHANES) from 1999 to 2011. Participants (N=17,030) were followed prospectively for mortality and ICD-9/10 codes were used to categorize cause-specific mortality as cardiovascular (CVD) disease and accidental deaths, which served as the negative control outcome. We examined the distribution of potential covariates and unadjusted mortality rates by TV viewing category. Preliminary Results: Over an average 8.82 years of follow-up, there were 1939 deaths from any causes, 358 from cardiovascular disease and 54 accidental deaths. In total, 2,501 reported no television viewing, 7,090 watched 1-2 hrs/day, 4,709 watched 3-4 hrs/day, and 2,730 watched > 5hrs/day. Increasing amounts of television viewing were associated with older age, higher BMI, higher proportion of current smokers, lower educational attainment, higher proportion of self-reported heart attacks and high blood pressure, and lower proportion of married individuals. Conclusion: Watching more television is associated with a higher unadjusted mortality rate and a number of confounding variables. The next step in this analysis will be to use proportional hazards models to estimate adjusted HRs and 95% CIs with careful consideration for the confounding variables we have identified. We will examine mortality associations with time spent in TV viewing category for all-cause, CVD and accidental death, which will serve as the negative control outcome.  ','[{\"name\":\"Freid, Lena\",\"email\":\"lfreid@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Kinesiology and Public Health\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"no\"},{\"name\":\"Weiss, Skylar\",\"email\":\"skweiss@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Kinesiology and Public Health\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"no\"},{\"name\":\"Keadle, Sarah\",\"email\":\"skeadle@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Biological Sciences\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Faculty\",\"frost\":\"yes\"}]','','We know how to make one,We can attend April 19, 5-6pm','2022-04-15 22:34:20',62,NULL,NULL,NULL),(100,'eeb56e1e90a89e70444c9d1fc528e6d8','2022','talk','Cloning and Expression of Amino Acid Ligases for TLN-05220 Biosynthesis','TLN-05220 is secondary metabolite natural product of Micromonospora echinospora, a gram-positive bacterium. TLN-05220 exhibits antibiotic activity against resistant pathogens in the same therapeutic range as the last resort antibiotic, vancomycin. While the biosynthesis of the hexacyclic aromatic polyketide backbone is generally understood, the synthesis of a unique nitrogen-containing ring remains under investigation. This piperazinone moiety consists of glycine, alanine, and serine, which are hypothesized to be ligated to the polyketide scaffold, and one another, by two amino acid ligase enzymes. It is postulated that the two amino acid ligases are modeled after asparagine synthetases. A reaction in the N-terminal domain of asparagine synthetase produces ammonia, which yields asparagine. However, due to a mutation in the putative asparagine synthetase, we propose an amino acid is used as the nitrogen source instead. In order to further understand the role of these ligases in the biosynthesis of TLN-05220, both asparagine synthetases were cloned into the pET28b vector using Gibson Assembly, transformation into Escherichia coli BL21, and selection with kanamycin resistance. One protein was successfully overexpressed with a C-terminal 6X histidine affinity tag, and FPLC purified with a Nickel-NTA column. After purification, the protein yield was found to be 6.89 mg/L. In the future, the purified proteins will be tested for ligase activity in vitro between various polyketide and amino acid substrates. ','[{\"name\":\"Watts, Katharine\",\"email\":\"krwatts@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Chemistry and Biochemistry\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Faculty\",\"frost\":\"yes\"},{\"name\":\"Goduco, Maria Ylleana Caryle\",\"email\":\"mgoduco@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Chemistry and Biochemistry\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"yes\"}]','1:00pm-3:00pm','','2022-04-15 22:47:32',31,'1:00-2:45','2-2:15','180-266'),(101,'a13d13d5d890f0a3a8f672c3416c33b4','2022','poster','Designing a Simple and Robust Enzymatic Assay for Ribonuclease A','The polarizability of the enzyme ribonuclease A allows for the structure to fold according to its specific packing of information. The short time it takes for RNase A to fold suggests that it is not a random process. We seek to analyze the activity of RNase A as a model system, and to address the question of folding by exploring pathways towards peptide self-assembly and function. The enzymatic activity of Ribonuclease A can be analyzed through changes in fluorescence intensity of ethidium bromide on binding with yeast RNA, or the change of absorbance at 300 nm, using the Kunitz method (Tripath et.al, 1946). In this study, we use a scale-downed approach for measuring enzymatic activity using a 96-well plate. Data analysis will be conducted based on measurements made on a UV-Vis spectrophotometer (pathlength = 1cm). Methods for evaluation of enzymatic activity will be integrated into CHEM 371 curriculum, and conducted under various redox conditions; these procedures will further yield an understanding of disulfide bonds in the protein folding dynamics of RNase A. Results from this study will inspire long-term goals concerning probability in abiotic peptide self-assembly. \n','[{\"name\":\"Campbell, Tammy\",\"email\":\"tcampb06@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Chemistry and Biochemistry\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Faculty\",\"frost\":\"yes\"},{\"name\":\"Cosmos-Jackson, Hal\",\"email\":\"hcosmosj@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Chemistry and Biochemistry\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"yes\"}]','','We would like to attend a workshop but CANNOT attend on Tuesday April 19, 5:10-6pm','2022-04-15 22:52:01',63,NULL,NULL,NULL),(102,'07f56801ddab2681ff5693da76379196','2022','talk','Investigating Simulation-Based Curriculum in Introductory Statistics Courses','With the advent of better and faster computer technology, simulation-based pedagogy is becoming more relevant, challenging the more traditional mathematical approaches in introductory statistics courses. In this study, we investigate whether simulation-based pedagogy (SBI) is more effective at helping students grasp key concepts in introductory statistics courses than the traditional methods (non-SBI). The study compares SBI-focused and non-SBI curricula at roughly 126 institutions across the United States. Data were collected across three academic years (2014-2017) and used various pre/post measures of conceptual understanding to gauge student learning. We find that the strongest predictors of students\' learning are pre-course student characteristics (e.g. prior knowledge), but that curriculum choice still has a meaningful impact on student understanding of key statistical concepts. In fact, textbook choice is the most important \"modifiable\" factor in predicting student success, with SBI being the most effective curriculum. More work needs to be done to uncover which particular introductory statistics topics (such as p-values, confidence intervals, the investigative process as a whole, etc.) are impacted most by curriculum choice.','[{\"name\":\"Leader, Sean\",\"email\":\"spleader@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Statistics\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"yes\"},{\"name\":\"Chan, Katherine\",\"email\":\"kchan78@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Statistics\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"yes\"},{\"name\":\"Chance, Beth\",\"email\":\"bchance@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Statistics\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Faculty\",\"frost\":\"yes\"},{\"name\":\"Roy, Soma\",\"email\":\"soroy@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Statistics\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Faculty\",\"frost\":\"yes\"}]','10:30am-12:00pm','','2022-04-15 23:00:30',36,'1:00-2:45','1:45-2','180-270'),(103,'56836c8cdc689361e64bbec820557ca4','2022','poster','Designing a Simple and Robust Enzymatic Assay for Ribonuclease A','The polarizability of the enzyme ribonuclease A allows for the structure to fold according to its specific packing of information. The short time it takes for RNase A to fold suggests that it is not a random process. We seek to analyze the activity of RNase A as a model system and to address the question of folding by exploring pathways towards peptide self-assembly and function. The enzymatic activity of Ribonuclease A can be analyzed through changes in fluorescence intensity of ethidium bromide on binding with yeast RNA, or the change of absorbance at 300 nm, using the Kunitz method (Tripath et.al, 1946). In this study, we use a scale-downed approach for measuring enzymatic activity using a 96-well plate. Data analysis will be conducted based on measurements made on a UV-Vis spectrophotometer (pathlength = 1cm). Methods for evaluation of enzymatic activity will be integrated into CHEM 371 curriculum, and conducted under various redox conditions; these procedures will further yield an understanding of disulfide bonds in the protein folding dynamics of RNase A. Results from this study will inspire long-term goals concerning probability in abiotic peptide self-assembly. ','[{\"name\":\"Cosmos-Jackson, Hal\",\"email\":\"Hcosmosj@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Chemistry and Biochemistry\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"yes\"},{\"name\":\"Campbell, Tammy\",\"email\":\"Tcampb06@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Chemistry and Biochemistry\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Faculty\",\"frost\":\"yes\"},{\"name\":\"Dhungana, Sami\",\"email\":\"SDhungan@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Chemistry and Biochemistry\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"yes\"}]','','We would like to attend a workshop but CANNOT attend on Tuesday April 19, 5:10-6pm','2022-04-15 23:11:39',64,NULL,NULL,NULL),(104,'97f8773e773fabf065a61564af8c7e9a','2022','poster','Electrical, thermal, and thermomagnetic transport properties of the chalcopyrite compound CdSnAs$_2$','In the ongoing effort to identify new semiconducting materials with improved thermoelectric performance, compounds having the chalcopyrite structure with general formula II-IV-V$_2$ are recently receiving significant attention. In the present work, we report the results of a study of the galvanomagnetic, thermomagnetic, and thermal transport properties of CdSnAs$_2$ with the chalcopyrite structure. Temperature dependent transport measurements on nominally undoped polycrystalline CdSnAs$_2$ indicate n-type semiconducting behavior with a relatively high thermoelectric power factor. This is correlated with a very high Hall mobility greater than 1700 cm$^2$ V$^{-1}$ s$^{-1}$ at 300 K that increases with temperature, in contrast to the behavior for typical semiconductors. The electrical resistivity, Seebeck coefficient, Hall coefficient, and Nernst coefficient are measured on a single sample. By comparing the experimental data to semiconductor theory, as well as creating qualitative models, we examine the underlying mechanisms for the observed behavior of the Hall mobility and its relationship to the effective mass. From this we also glean insight into the dominant charge carrier scattering mechanism in this material. This work contributes to the fundamental understanding of chalcopyrite-based materials, providing guidance for investigations into altering/improving their properties for thermoelectric applications.','[{\"name\":\"Laney, Eva\",\"email\":\"elaney@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Physics\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"yes\"},{\"name\":\"Dutra, Chad\",\"email\":\"cadutra@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Physics\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"yes\"},{\"name\":\"Beekman, Matt\",\"email\":\"mbeekman@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Physics\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Faculty\",\"frost\":\"yes\"}]','','We have one already','2022-04-15 23:15:39',65,NULL,NULL,NULL),(105,'6bcaa0c29bbc5dcc2be3ccaeba5e1383','2022','poster','Seasonal and Hourly Variability in Chemical and Biological Parameters in San Luis Bay Coastal Waters','The coastal ocean is a unique region that allows for the study of the chemical and biological environment distinct from the open ocean and influenced by both local and larger-scale processes. In this study, we characterize seawater carbonate chemistry, and use additional physical and biological measurements to observe and understand both the seasonal and daily variability in the coastal waters of San Luis Obispo Bay, CA. Monthly seawater samples were collected from the end of the California Polytechnic State University Pier in San Luis Obispo Bay using a sampling rosette. The data spans Jan 2018 - Dec 2021, with a six-month gap in 2020 due to COVID-19. These samples demonstrate monthly variability largely driven by large-scale ocean mixing and seasonal wind-driven coastal upwelling. To investigate shorter term variability, additional samples were collected for 8 to 12 consecutive hours on a single day in the spring, summer, and fall of 2021. This higher-frequency sampling provides insight into local drivers of variability in the nearshore waters such as tides and biological modification including photosynthesis, respiration, and plankton bloom events.','[{\"name\":\"Herbst, Amanda\",\"email\":\"herbst@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Chemistry and Biochemistry\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"yes\"},{\"name\":\"Keller, Landon\",\"email\":\"lwkeller@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Chemistry and Biochemistry\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"no\"},{\"name\":\"Bockmon, Emily\",\"email\":\"ebockmon@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Chemistry and Biochemistry\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Faculty\",\"frost\":\"no\"},{\"name\":\"Pasulka, Alexis\",\"email\":\"apasulka@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Biological Sciences\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Faculty\",\"frost\":\"no\"}]','','We know how to make one','2022-04-15 23:23:30',66,NULL,NULL,NULL),(106,'d1735e625f76e471a1113a4fd8958fbe','2022','poster','Movement of weaned northern elephant seal (Mirounga angustirostris) pups during their first at-sea foraging migration','The Northern Elephant Seal (NES) is a well-studied marine mammal that is known for engaging in long foraging migrations at sea. Adult male NES follow pathways along the coast towards Alaska and adult female NES follow pathways out into open ocean. However, there is little to no information about weaned NES pup foraging behavior. This lack of knowledge is significant because NES have a mortality rate of ~50% in the first year. This project aims to better understand the migratory pathways of NES during this critical life stage. We will deploy satellite tags (Wildlife Computers SPOT-287) on seals born at the Vandenberg Space Force Base breeding site (VSFB) and the Piedras Blancas breeding site (PB). We hypothesize that the weaned NES pups will [1] prioritize near-site foraging areas and in turn migrate shorter distances compared to adults, [2] exhibit no sexual divergence in their migratory pathways, and [3] have migratory pathways that differ between the two breeding sites. By determining the migratory pathways of weaned pups from two different breeding sites (VSFB and PB), we can gain insights into foraging grounds, differences between breeding sites, and potentially the navigational mechanisms of this species, which will improve conservation and management of this ecologically important marine mammal.  ','[{\"name\":\"Saenger, Katie\",\"email\":\"esaenger@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Biological Sciences\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"no\"},{\"name\":\"Liwanag, Heather\",\"email\":\"hliwanag@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Biological Sciences\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Faculty\",\"frost\":\"no\"},{\"name\":\"Bean, Tim\",\"email\":\"wtbean@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Biological Sciences\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Faculty\",\"frost\":\"no\"},{\"name\":\"Kolluru, Gita\",\"email\":\"gkolluru@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Biological Sciences\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Faculty\",\"frost\":\"no\"}]','','We can attend April 19, 5-6pm','2022-04-15 23:28:48',67,NULL,NULL,NULL),(107,'7b264255dbaab494d2093e712bbf5e83','2022','talk','Constructing and Cloning a Plasmid with a Gene Expressing an Epoxomicin Non-Ribosomal Peptide Synthase Modular Protein','Epoxomicin is a potent and selective proteasome inhibitor naturally synthesized by the bacterial Actinomycete strain classified as Goodfellowiella coeruleoviolacea. Chemical modifications of the tetrapeptide backbone of epoxomicin has yielded synthetic derivatives YU101 and Carfilzomib which display increased proteasome inhibition, selectivity, and solubility in water. Carfilzomib is FDA-approved and marketed as KrypolisTM for treatment of multiple myeloma. The high cost of KrypolisTM is attributed to the laborious process of its chemical synthesis. We believe that harnessing the biosynthetic pathway that produces epoxomicin will lower the cost to patients. The assembly of epoxomicin is catalyzed by a non-ribosomal peptide synthetase (NRPS) and polyketide synthetase (PKS) mega-enzyme. Modifying the amino acid specificity of the epoxomicin NRPS modular protein may instead allow assembly of the YU101 derivative. We hypothesize that modification of the mega-enzyme can be achieved by dissecting the synthase into individual modules and installing communication mediating domains that allow protein-protein interactions between consecutive modules. Previous work done to heterologously express the first dissected NRPS module displayed low yield and significant fragmentation. Thus, the gene was cloned into the pBAD33 vector with an arabinose inducible promoter, resulting in improved yield and purity of the holo- and apoprotein. These proteins are currently being assessed for amino acid substrate specificity using a coupled enzyme assay. ','[{\"name\":\"Yeung, Wilson\",\"email\":\"wlyeung@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Biological Sciences\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"yes\"},{\"name\":\"Watts, Katharine\",\"email\":\"krwatts@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Chemistry and Biochemistry\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Faculty\",\"frost\":\"yes\"}]','10:30am-12:00pm','','2022-04-15 23:32:23',29,'1:00-2:45','1:30-1:45','180-266'),(108,'8b8f58891c109e01cbf7773a8f2beb90','2022','poster','Ylidenenorbornadiene carboxylates: Bridge Substituents & Ring Strain','Ylidenenorbornadienes (YNDs), synthesized by [4 + 2] cyclo-additions between fulvenes and acetylene dicarboxylates, react with beta-mercaptoethanol (BME) creating mixtures of four YND-BME diastereomers. Fragmentation kinetics of these YND-BMEs through spontaneous retro-[4+2] cycloadditions were investigated.  An investigation of 10 YND systems was performed to understand the structural modifications on the bridging ylidene that influence the rate of fragmentation. Among the array of bridging ylidene substituents tested was a set of carbocycle structures to test the effect of ring strain on the rate of YND-BME fragmentation. Overall, across the 10 systems studied the range for half-lives observed was very broad (22.6-605min) at 80 oC. This wide range in the rate of degradation of the library of substrates highlights the potential utility of YND systems when used as a modular cleavable linker across many applications.  \n\n','[{\"name\":\"Fleischer, Cameron\",\"email\":\"Cjfleisc@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Chemistry and Biochemistry\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"yes\"},{\"name\":\"Bercovici, Daniel\",\"email\":\"Dbercovi@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Chemistry and Biochemistry\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Faculty\",\"frost\":\"no\"}]','','We know how to make one,We would like to attend a workshop but CANNOT attend on Tuesday April 19, 5:10-6pm','2022-04-15 23:44:19',68,NULL,NULL,NULL),(109,'13416ec740cd310174c01b7e537cd936','2022','talk','COVID-19: The Impact of Social Isolation on Wellbeing ','This cross-sectional study looks to evaluate the relationship between social isolation post-COVID-19 and wellbeing among college students. Pandemic restrictions have disrupted social networks, leaving lasting impacts on students around the world. Recent studies show that these restrictions have adverse effects on students\' psychological wellbeing, especially for females (Sundarasen et al., 2020). This study looks to apply a more holistic model to examine health and wellness beyond the absence of disease or injury. Social isolation was assessed using the Social Isolation Questionnaire developed for this study, the Short Warwick-Edinburgh Mental Wellbeing Scale, and the Seity Health daily check-in. It is hypothesized that higher levels of perceived social isolation will be correlated with lower wellbeing scores. Based on previous research, we also predict that females will report lower wellbeing than males among socially isolated students (Sundarasen et al., 2020). Finally, it is predicted that a student\'s major will be related to their social isolation, impacting their wellbeing. At this time, verifying the validity of the sample is underway. With responses collected from Cal State University, Stanislaus and MTurk, the data reflects the inability of attention checks to ensure the quality of a sample. Instead, asking participants to provide the nickname given to students at the university has served as a more reliable quality filter. After validating the sample and collecting responses from Cal Poly, a reliability analysis on the Social Isolation Questionnaire will occur and social isolation will be correlated to wellbeing using Cronbach\'s alpha. From the analyses, we look to share this information with universities about the impact of social isolation on overall wellbeing. Through this, universities can be informed on their students\' needs. With mental health being a large problem on university campuses, greater insight into the wellbeing of students is crucial. ','[{\"name\":\"Romeo, Izzy\",\"email\":\"romeo@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Kinesiology and Public Health\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"no\"},{\"name\":\"Roberts, Joni\",\"email\":\"jrober81@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Kinesiology and Public Health\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Faculty\",\"frost\":\"no\"}]','9:00am-10:30am,1:00pm-3:00pm','','2022-04-15 23:53:02',23,'1:00-2:45','1:30-1:45','180-261'),(110,'eb422280fd086c58c04cb2c504ee0a82','2022','talk','Ylidenenorbornadiene carboxylates - Experimental and Extrapolated Kinetic Analysis of a Nucleophile-Induced retro-[4+2] Fragmentation','Ylidenenorbornadiene carboxylate (YND) substrates were prepared by [4+2] cycloaddition reactions between fulvenes and acetylene mono- or dicarboxylates.  YNDs, like their previously reported oxa- and azanorbornadienedicarboxylate (OND and ZND) analogs, have proven to be reactive electrophiles with thiols. This reaction then triggers their retro-[4+2] fragmentation. An investigation of 19 YND systems was performed to understand the structural and electronic effects that influence the rate of degradation. Of these 19 YND systems, the ester and ring strain subset have four observed diastereomers, which arise due to the mechanism of the conjugate addition of the thiol nucleophile. Through extrapolation utilizing a genetic algorithm and the simplex method, the kinetic rate of three out of the four diastereomers was uncovered. Each diastereomer undergoes the retro-[4+2] cycloaddition at substantially different rates. Therefore, the population of slow vs. fast diastereomers in each YND system greatly influences the observed kinetic rate of the substrate. Across the 4 ester and 5 ring strain systems studied, the range of half-lives observed was very broad (22.6-14,600 min) at 80^{\\circ}C. Through the use of this kinetic extrapolation method, individual rate constants can be determined from complex mixtures of diastereomers, allowing for a better understanding of structural and electronic effects on the fragmentation reaction.','[{\"name\":\"Henry, Ava\",\"email\":\"avhenry@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Chemistry and Biochemistry\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"no\"},{\"name\":\"Bercovici, Daniel\",\"email\":\"dbercovi@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Chemistry and Biochemistry\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Faculty\",\"frost\":\"no\"}]','1:00pm-3:00pm','','2022-04-15 23:54:22',32,'1:00-2:45','2:15-2:30','180-266'),(111,'a396bbd89fa9c60093bf7d7c8085e255','2022','poster','Organic Contributions to Total Alkalinity in Morro Bay','The ocean\'s chemistry is controlled in part by its ability to withstand changes in pH, essentially determined by its buffering capacity, as indicated by total alkalinity. Total alkalinity is one of the measurable parameters (including pH, dissolved inorganic carbon, and dissolved partial pressure of CO2) that define the inorganic carbonate system and are all connected by a mathematical model. In this system at least two measured parameters are required to constrain the system and thus, given two parameters, any other can be calculated, (i.e. measured values of pH and dissolved inorganic carbon can be used to calculate total alkalinity), and produce a theoretical value. This work evaluates measured Morro Bay total alkalinity data against theoretical values, investigating observed discrepancies. These discrepancies are likely due to undefined organic acids that are contributing to the total alkalinity measurement, but that are not included in the mathematical model and thus the theoretical value. Previous work has observed this phenomenon and suggested possible sources of organic alkalinity but have not specially investigated a small low-inflow estuary such as Morro Bay. This study links observed total alkalinity discrepancies using nutrient concentrations, seasonal variations, tide direction, and sample locations, to correlate spatial and chemical variations, while additionally finding connections between the organic and inorganic marine carbonate system. ','[{\"name\":\"Kassem, Siobhan\",\"email\":\"skassemc@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Chemistry and Biochemistry\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"no\"},{\"name\":\"Bockmon, Emily\",\"email\":\"ebockmon@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Chemistry and Biochemistry\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Faculty\",\"frost\":\"no\"}]','','We know how to make one','2022-04-16 00:06:33',69,NULL,NULL,NULL),(112,'d46fe9621ea1a1418bb46d8d0a835445','2022','poster','Water Purification with Covalent Organic Frameworks','Water contamination with pollutants such as dye molecules used in the textile industry present a major challenge for the global community. To combat this challenge, porous adsorbents such as covalent organic frameworks (COFs) have been investigated due to their high intrinsic surface areas. However, to date, most studies investigate the effect of changing the building blocks used to synthesize COFs as opposed to more fundamental studies looking at the effect of particle size, shape, and morphology. This is largely due to difficulty accessing high quality samples with different morphologies. In this study, we investigate the effects of catalyst acidity and reaction temperature to access COF samples with different particle morphologies characterized by scanning electron microscopy (SEM). These samples are tested for their ability to perform water purification using UV-visible spectroscopy. We hope to leverage these findings towards optimizing the performance of this class of materials in water purification.','[{\"name\":\"Chew, Alyssa\",\"email\":\"achew05@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Chemistry and Biochemistry\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"yes\"},{\"name\":\"Chew, Alison\",\"email\":\"acchew@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Other...\",\"other_affiliation\":\"Department of Materials Engineering\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"no\"},{\"name\":\"Ngo, Brandon\",\"email\":\"bngo13@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Chemistry and Biochemistry\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"no\"},{\"name\":\"Tran, Donna\",\"email\":\"dtran111@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Chemistry and Biochemistry\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"no\"},{\"name\":\"Hamachi, Leslie\",\"email\":\"hamachi@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Chemistry and Biochemistry\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Faculty\",\"frost\":\"no\"}]','','We know how to make one','2022-04-16 00:13:54',70,NULL,NULL,NULL),(113,'40f05d916dfcbb5a2b3c53b596d9cbaa','2022','poster','Kinetic Parameters for Continuous Fermentation','Fermentation is a chemical process used to make many popular beverages including beer, wine, and kombucha. The fermentation method used by the producers of these beverages is done in a single container, or a batch reactor, instead of flowing continuously through several containers and emerging as a finished product. Our fermentation experiments aim to find the kinetic parameters and rate constants for continuous production of beer. The beer is frequently sampled throughout the fermentation process to track the fluctuation of several compounds, such as sugar, yeast, and ethanol, which indicate the progress of fermentation. By varying the reaction of temperature or the initial levels of sugar of yeast, and observing their effects on the parameters, we can determine how each compound influences the rate. These effects are captures in the kinetic model which has eleven rate constants which constrain six rate laws, each modeling a different reaction. The rate constants we have generated for individual runs fit our experimental data with relative accuracy, but they differ too greatly between sets of runs to suggest the model parameters are universal. This indicates that modification of these established rate laws, or even additional factors, needs to be undertaken in order to better represent wide ranges of fermentation data. A better understanding of the parameters which control the fermentation process could help to optimize beer manufacturing. ','[{\"name\":\"Bentley, Kristi\",\"email\":\"khbentle@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Chemistry and Biochemistry\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"yes\"},{\"name\":\"Heying, Michael\",\"email\":\"mdheying@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Chemistry and Biochemistry\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Faculty\",\"frost\":\"yes\"},{\"name\":\"Thibault, Kelsey\",\"email\":\"kthibaul@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Chemistry and Biochemistry\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"yes\"},{\"name\":\"Cramer, Kristen\",\"email\":\"klcramer@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Chemistry and Biochemistry\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"no\"}]','','We would like to attend a workshop but CANNOT attend on Tuesday April 19, 5:10-6pm','2022-04-16 00:31:36',71,NULL,NULL,NULL),(114,'7a286b097b13171c4b6e29526fbc2fa2','2022','poster','Non-Equilibrium Fluctuations and Diffusion in 2D Fluids','The dominant mechanism for molecular transport in biological systems is diffusion. The continuum mechanics of Fick\'s Laws have been applied to model non-equilibrium diffusion for over one hundred years, since concentration fluctuations typically exist only at molecular scales. However, recent research has measured fluctuations 10,000 times molecular scales along the concentration gradient in a liquid due to the coupling of diffusive mechanisms and fluid flow, which may make Fick\'s Law inadequate. These so-called \'Giant Fluctuations\' have been observed through shadowgraphs in three-dimensional fluids, and it has been theorized that the fluctuations are significantly larger in two dimensions. Here we describe several experiments that aim to discover the extent to which giant fluctuations are present in two-dimensional liquids, including freely-suspended liquid crystal films and Langmuir monolayers, using fluorescence recovery after photobleaching (FRAP) and phase separation of dye, to induce a concentration gradient and to observe non-equilibrium diffusion. We analyze fluorescence images using spatial 2D Fourier transforms, and correlation functions to observe and quantify the properties of the theorized \'Giant Fluctuations.\' ','[{\"name\":\"Sullivan, Patrick\",\"email\":\"psulli13@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Physics\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"no\"},{\"name\":\"Dunning, Nicolas\",\"email\":\"ndunning@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Physics\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"no\"},{\"name\":\"Maxwell, Hannah\",\"email\":\"hcmaxwel@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Physics\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"no\"},{\"name\":\"Micklin, Elsa\",\"email\":\"emicklin@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Physics\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"no\"},{\"name\":\"Miller, Claudia\",\"email\":\"cmill127@gmail.com\",\"affiliation\":\"Other...\",\"other_affiliation\":\"Biomedical Engineering\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"no\"},{\"name\":\"Fernsler, Jonathan\",\"email\":\"jfernsle@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Physics\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Faculty\",\"frost\":\"no\"}]','','We have one already','2022-04-16 00:54:37',72,NULL,NULL,NULL),(115,'b2c3591024f25f7ed0b3d07c9a1c2dff','2022','talk','Clean Status, Condoms, and The Campus Community','Sexual wellbeing is a large aspect of college students\' health that continues to be minimally addressed on university campuses. Considering the topic of STIs specifically, it is estimated that people ages 15-24 accounted for almost half of the 26 million new sexually transmitted infections that occurred in the United States in 2018 (CDC, 2018). However, only 42.1% of Cal Poly students reported using a barrier method most of the time during vaginal sex (ACHA-NCHA III Survey, 2021). Furthermore, a mere 11% of students reported being tested for HIV within the last year (ACHA-NCHA III Survey, 2021). A preliminary study by Cal Poly\'s Sexual and Reproductive Health Lab conducted during the 2020-21 school year (n=580) indicated that while 69% of students are engaging in sexual activity, sex-based differences are apparent in terms of desire to use condoms. Further, participation in conversations surrounding STI clean status is limited. Therefore, a follow-up study exploring the clean status phenomena was initiated. Multiple clean status trends continue to emerge in the current interview process (n=22). In both survey data and qualitative interviews, trust appears to be an influential factor: an overwhelming majority of participants indicate that although they may ask their partners if they have been tested, they do not require proof of results. Preliminary findings suggest emerging trends that Cal Poly students have a general awareness of STIs and the importance of using condoms, yet external circumstances, such as avoiding awkwardness, blindly trusting partners, or being caught up in the moment, hold greater weight in their decision to use condoms during sexual activity.   \n\n  \n','[{\"name\":\"Roberts, Joni\",\"email\":\"jrober81@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Kinesiology and Public Health\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Faculty\",\"frost\":\"no\"},{\"name\":\"Snow, Gabriella\",\"email\":\"gksnow@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Kinesiology and Public Health\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"no\"},{\"name\":\"Sampath, Anusha \",\"email\":\"asampath@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Kinesiology and Public Health\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"no\"},{\"name\":\"Asson, Alexa\",\"email\":\"alexa.asson@gmail.com\",\"affiliation\":\"Kinesiology and Public Health\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"no\"},{\"name\":\"Higashi, Kate\",\"email\":\"k8higashi11@gmail.com\",\"affiliation\":\"Kinesiology and Public Health\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"no\"}]','10:30am-12:00pm','','2022-04-16 00:57:04',26,'1:00-2:45','2:15-2:30','180-261'),(116,'52c35568182adcc3b42427b667c7854d','2022','poster','Polyols as Phase Change Materials in Solar Electric Cooking','We are developing Insulated Solar Electric Cooking (ISEC) as an answer to the environmental and humanitarian crises caused by traditional wood-fire cooking. To enable solar cooking when there is no sun, abundant polyols such as erythritol and xylitol are utilized for their high latent heats to store energy in the ISECs. In sunny atmospheric conditions, solar panels attached to the ISEC heat the given polyol, effectively storing the latent fusion energy in the endothermic melting process. In less desirable conditions for solar cooking, such as cloudy atmospheric conditions or nightfall, the polyol is allowed to exothermically solidify, heating the food pot. Because of this process, these materials are dubbed phase change materials, or PCMs.\n \nHowever, erythritol is known to degrade and become less efficient at energy storage after cycling for an extended time, and xylitol\'s melting temperature is two Celsius degrees below the boiling point of water. In addition, PCM data gathered on the differential scanning calorimeter suggests that the drastic supercooling exhibited by polyols may affect the temperature at which the stored latent energy can be accessed. This project explores the viability of erythritol and xylitol as PCMs in our developed solar cooking model.','[{\"name\":\"Gamoji, Sudheendra\",\"email\":\"sgamoji@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Physics\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"no\"},{\"name\":\"Micklin, Elsa\",\"email\":\"emicklin@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Chemistry and Biochemistry\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"no\"},{\"name\":\"Nagy, Daniel\",\"email\":\"dnagy@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Chemistry and Biochemistry\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"no\"},{\"name\":\"Schwartz, Peter\",\"email\":\"pschwart@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Physics\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Faculty\",\"frost\":\"no\"}]','','We would like to attend a workshop but CANNOT attend on Tuesday April 19, 5:10-6pm','2022-04-16 01:08:56',73,NULL,NULL,NULL),(117,'83f4e197bcf2db72730c97805c7074a0','2022','poster','Drought Impacts on Net Primary Productivity In California Rangelands','The State of California plans to sequester 15 million metric tons of atmospheric carbon in natural lands by the year 2030 to mitigate greenhouse gas emissions, as outlined in the Global Warming Solutions Act of 2006. Vegetation on natural lands removes CO2 from the atmosphere through photosynthesis, leading to carbon storage in the form of stable plant material and soil organic matter. Rangelands, including grasslands, shrublands, and woodlands, make up over half of California\'s natural lands and represent a large potential for carbon storage. Recognizing this potential, the state has already invested over $600 million in conservation, restoration, and management of these lands. However, we lack a comprehensive understanding of how carbon storage potential varies across the state and how a drying climate will impact these carbon stores. Thus, the state is limited in its ability to make strategic investments based on where conservation will yield the most carbon storage. Net Primary Productivity is a measure of carbon absorbed by plants during photosynthesis minus carbon lost during respiration and is widely used to quantify the potential for ecosystem carbon storage (Keeling, 2007; Dangal, 2020). Previous work has linked warmer and wetter conditions with higher NPP at a coarse scale (Knapp and Smith, 2001), but the fine scale effects of climate, topography, vegetation biodiversity, and soil properties on regional and local NPP are poorly understood. California\'s drying climate and the onset of more frequent precipitation anomalies (Diffenbaugh et al 2015) adds further uncertainty to the dynamics of NPP at fine scales. In this study, we combine a high resolution remote sensed product of ecosystem carbon storage potential with a fine scale hydrologic model of California to generate, for the first time, spatially explicit models of (1) rangeland carbon storage potential and (2) carbon storage response to precipitation anomalies in California.  ','[{\"name\":\"McCafferty, Mary\",\"email\":\"mkmccaff@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Mathematics\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"no\"},{\"name\":\"Alexander, Jack\",\"email\":\"jalexa15@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Biological Sciences\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"no\"},{\"name\":\"James, Jeremy\",\"email\":\"jjames20@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Other...\",\"other_affiliation\":\"Natural Resources\",\"role\":\"Faculty\",\"frost\":\"no\"},{\"name\":\"Fricker, Andrew\",\"email\":\"africker@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Other...\",\"other_affiliation\":\"Geography\",\"role\":\"Faculty\",\"frost\":\"no\"}]','','We have one already','2022-04-16 01:19:49',74,NULL,NULL,NULL),(118,'3c672b9213c1ef7f4eb0fcc8389a6c08','2022','poster','Influence of voltage offsets on measurement of the Seebeck coefficient ','Thermoelectric materials enable conversion of heat to electrical energy with no moving parts. The Seebeck coefficient, defined as the ratio of the thermoelectric voltage generated to the applied temperature difference, S = - dV/dT, is an important material property commonly measured in the characterization of new thermoelectric materials, and directly influences energy conversion efficiency. As such, accurate measurement of S is critical to the design and development of new thermoelectric materials. In this work, we have used simulations to evaluate the influence of voltage offsets on the accuracy of Seebeck measurements performed using common protocols. We discuss how the polarity and magnitude of possible voltage offsets can impact the accuracy of the resulting Seebeck values, including the maximum offsets that can be tolerated under various conditions. The results will be of use to the thermoelectric materials research community, particularly for those wishing to characterize and improve experimental measurement of the Seebeck coefficient. ','[{\"name\":\"Mohakar, Nakul\",\"email\":\"nmohakar@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Other...\",\"other_affiliation\":\"Electrical Engineering\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"no\"},{\"name\":\"Posadas, Christian\",\"email\":\"cposadas@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Physics\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"yes\"},{\"name\":\"Clark, Ben\",\"email\":\"bclark33@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Other...\",\"other_affiliation\":\"Electrical Engineering\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"yes\"},{\"name\":\"Beekman, Matt\",\"email\":\"mbeekman@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Physics\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Faculty\",\"frost\":\"yes\"}]','','We have one already','2022-04-16 01:28:51',75,NULL,NULL,NULL),(119,'b1ab5b61a25a085ae9b52f1533c0b3a3','2022','poster','Analyzing Hubble Space Telescope Images of Active Galaxies to Create a Baseline of Supermassive Black Hole - Host-Galaxy Scaling Relations','This NSF-funded research project focuses on scaling relations between active galactic nuclei (AGNs) and their host-galaxy properties. We use the software GALFIT to analyze Hubble Space Telescope images of 14 AGNs with securely measured black hole masses via reverberation mapping. In addition to the AGN luminosity (fitted as a point-source function, PSF, in the center), host-galaxy properties are derived, including sizes and luminosities of bulge, disk, and bar (if present). When converted from measured units into physical quantities, scaling relations between the mass of the supermassive black holes and their host-galaxy properties are established. These local baselines form the foundation of black hole - host-galaxy co-evolution studies.','[{\"name\":\"Bennert, Vardha\",\"email\":\"vbennert@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Physics\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Faculty\",\"frost\":\"no\"},{\"name\":\"Soderberg, Steve\",\"email\":\"ssoderbe@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Physics\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Faculty\",\"frost\":\"no\"},{\"name\":\"De Souza, Nathalia\",\"email\":\"ndesouza@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Physics\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"no\"},{\"name\":\"Capili, Jewel\",\"email\":\"jcapili@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Physics\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"no\"},{\"name\":\"Howell, Jess\",\"email\":\"jfhowell@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Physics\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"no\"},{\"name\":\"Hood, Jonathan\",\"email\":\"jfhood@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Physics\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"no\"}]','','We can attend April 19, 5-6pm','2022-04-16 01:40:23',76,NULL,NULL,NULL),(120,'f2726364545485868fa66c2f77f7ac7c','2022','poster','Imaging and Spectroscopy at the Cal Poly Observatory','Cal Poly Observatory consists of multiple small telescopes, some of which are used for public viewing of bright night-sky objects. The biggest telescope is a XXX Meade telescope equipped with a CCD (charged-coupled device) camera. After learning the operation of the telescope and camera, our team obtained images of stars, nebulae and galaxies. We are currently in the process of increasing the versatility of Cal Poly Observatory by adding a spectrograph to the system. Spectroscopy of planetary, stellar and extra-galactic objects sheds light onto chemical composition, velocity and nature of the sources studied and thus is a great addition to imaging. We learn and document operation, data acquisition and data reduction, with the goal of implementing spectroscopy in upper-division astronomy courses offered at Cal Poly (in particular the observational astronomy class ASTR 444, offered next in Fall 2022). We plan on taking spectra of a range of objects for comparison, including active galaxies for the sake of estimating their black hole masses.','[{\"name\":\"Bennert, Vardha\",\"email\":\"vbennert@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Physics\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Faculty\",\"frost\":\"no\"},{\"name\":\"Soderberg, Steve\",\"email\":\"ssoderbe@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Physics\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Faculty\",\"frost\":\"no\"},{\"name\":\"Capili, Jewel\",\"email\":\"jcapili@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Physics\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"no\"},{\"name\":\"De Souza, Nathalia\",\"email\":\"ndesouza@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Physics\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"no\"},{\"name\":\"Howell, Jess\",\"email\":\"jfhowell@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Physics\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"no\"},{\"name\":\"Hood, Jonathan \",\"email\":\"jfhood@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Physics\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"no\"}]','','We can attend April 19, 5-6pm','2022-04-16 01:45:14',77,NULL,NULL,NULL),(121,'ead36644207e7c49a469a4a0e340bb8b','2022','poster','Infant-Mother Communications During Bottle Feeding','Rapid weight gain during infancy is an often underappreciated precursor for obesity in life. One of the most important recommendations to curb infant overfeeding is to promote a responsive feeding style, adjusting the length and pace of the feeding to subtle cues that the infant uses to communicate its needs. By examining detailed time series of over 600 feedings, we have been able to find insights into the potency and meaning of many of these clues, as well as shedding light on the great degree of variability we can expect between infants. Far from revealing a simple meaning and way to respond to each infant cue, we\'ve found that even cues normally associated with fullness such as the infant leaning away or spitting up were only about twice as likely near the end of the feeding as at the start. We also found great differences in what cues meant for infants across different ages, such as 2-8 week old babies closing their mouths as an indication of satiation, while older infants rarely did so. As this is a descriptive, explorative study, the results are designed to answer a wide variety of questions about infant-mother communication, in the hopes of revealing surprising truths that can help prevent rapid infant weight gain.','[{\"name\":\"Medwid, William\",\"email\":\"wmedwid@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Statistics\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"yes\"},{\"name\":\"Ross, Kevin\",\"email\":\"kjross@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Statistics\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Faculty\",\"frost\":\"yes\"},{\"name\":\"Ventura, Allison\",\"email\":\"akventur@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Kinesiology and Public Health\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Faculty\",\"frost\":\"yes\"}]','','We can attend April 19, 5-6pm','2022-04-16 02:11:34',78,NULL,NULL,NULL),(122,'70ef615c807c32d2d44df134eee89a0b','2022','poster','Understanding Seawater pH Fluctuations at Local Oyster Farm','Compared to traditional fishing methods, aquaculture can be an environmentally and economically sustainable practice for providing food and commercial products with minimal impact on marine ecology. Careful attention to water quality conditions at aquaculture farms can support and improve their practices. We deployed an autonomous pH and temperature sensor next to an off-bottom oyster bed at the Grassy Bar Oyster Company lease, in Morro Bay. Seawater conditions, including pH are critical for heathy development and shell calcification of oysters. Additional data (salinity, dissolved oxygen and seawater pressure) from a nearby autonomous coastal observing station maintained by Central and Northern California Ocean Observing Systems (CeNCOOS) were used to examine the drivers of pH variability in the bay. The data show a strong relationship between pH and tide, coupled with the day-night cycle. During high tide oceanic seawater is swept into the bay refreshing the water quality. When the tide recedes, modified seawater from the shallow back bay sweeps over the oyster bed. Exceptionally high (>8.5) seawater pH was observed when low tide happened during the daytime, likely indicative of active photosynthesis in the bay. Low seawater pH (<7.5), potentially problematic for calcifying organisms, was observed during nighttime as tidal height increased. Understanding seawater pH dynamics provides oysters growers with data to inform their management practices to maximize oyster survival and growth across variable calcification conditions.','[{\"name\":\"Negi,Shreeya\",\"email\":\"snegi@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Chemistry and Biochemistry\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"no\"},{\"name\":\"Bockmon,Emily\",\"email\":\"ebockmon@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Chemistry and Biochemistry\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Faculty\",\"frost\":\"no\"},{\"name\":\"Johnson,Kevin\",\"email\":\"kjohn263@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Biological Sciences\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Faculty\",\"frost\":\"no\"}]','','We know how to make one','2022-04-16 02:35:08',79,NULL,NULL,NULL),(123,'69fe682d16ce12f06e0dc9bf981421ff','2022','talk','Mom, is that you? A northern elephant seal pup\'s ability to vocally recognize its mother in a densely populated rookery.','Mutual parent-young recognition is fundamental in species characterized by high densities at breeding sites, including pinnipeds (seals, sea lions, walruses). Northern elephant seal (NES) mothers stay hauled out with their pup throughout the 28-day nursing period, in dense rookeries with as many as 100 females and dependents per harem. Pups can become separated from their mothers during female-female aggression, inclement weather, and/or a male infiltrating the harem. The likelihood of a pup dying is greatly increased once separated from its mother, making recognition critical to pup survival, but little is known about NES mother-pup vocal recognition. One recent study demonstrated that females can vocally recognize their pup days after birth, but it is unknown if this recognition is mutual, and we hypothesized it is. This past breeding season, we tested this by collecting focal recordings of adult female attraction calls (ACs) for playback experiments at the Piedras Blancas NES rookery. The playbacks included ACs of the pup\'s own mother and ACs of an unrelated female, and were performed four times throughout the nursing period. We recorded the pup\'s behavioral responses to each playback, including vocalizations, phonotaxis, and head turns toward the speaker. Given that a pup separated from its mother has a lower chance of survival, we predicted NES pups will respond more to calls from their own mother than calls of another female. We found that pups do not appear to recognize the ACs of their mother, as their behavioral responses to the playbacks were relatively similar for both treatments. Age and sex also do not seem to predict behavioral response to playbacks, and responsiveness to playbacks does not influence weaning weight and weaning age. These results suggest that pups rely on their mothers for maintaining contact throughout the nursing period.  ','[{\"name\":\"Murphy, Molly\",\"email\":\"mmurph72@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Biological Sciences\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"no\"},{\"name\":\"Liwanag, Heather\",\"email\":\"hliwanag@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Biological Sciences\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Faculty\",\"frost\":\"no\"},{\"name\":\"Casey, Caroline\",\"email\":\"cbcasey@ucsc.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Other...\",\"other_affiliation\":\"UCSC\",\"role\":\"Faculty\",\"frost\":\"no\"},{\"name\":\"Kolluru, Gita\",\"email\":\"gkolluru@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Biological Sciences\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Faculty\",\"frost\":\"no\"},{\"name\":\"Schroth-Glanz, Maddie\",\"email\":\"mschroth@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Statistics\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Faculty\",\"frost\":\"no\"}]','9:00am-10:30am,10:30am-12:00pm,1:00pm-3:00pm','','2022-04-16 03:27:34',27,'1:00-2:45','1-1:15','180-266'),(124,'845afbf12ce1b93d014397ce1d0263c5','2022','talk','Keytanglement: Quantum Key Distribution Simulation Using Bell States','To communicate information securely, the sender and recipient of the information need to have a shared, secret key. Quantum key distribution (QKD) is a proposed method for this, taking advantage of the laws of quantum mechanics. The users, Alice and Bob, exchange quantum information in the form of entangled qubits over a quantum channel as well as exchanging measurement information over a classical channel. A successful QKD algorithm will ensure that when an eavesdropper has access to both the quantum and classical information channels, they cannot deduce the key, and they will be detected by the key generators. This presentation will introduce quantum key distribution and explain the implemented simulation of a proposed QKD algorithm using entangled Bell states via an online secure chat interface. A user can visit the Keytanglement website to generate keys via the Bell state QKD and have an encrypted chat with another user. The project won second place in the QuTech division of the MIT quantum hackathon called iQuHack which took place in January 2022.','[{\"name\":\"Tiwari, Nayana\",\"email\":\"natiwari@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Other...\",\"other_affiliation\":\"Department of Physics and Computer Engineering\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"no\",\"presenter\":\"yes\"},{\"name\":\"Knapen, Alexander\",\"email\":\"aknapen@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Other...\",\"other_affiliation\":\"Department of Computer Engineering\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"no\"},{\"name\":\"Rice, Julian\",\"email\":\"jrice15@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Other...\",\"other_affiliation\":\"Department of Computer Science\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"no\"},{\"name\":\"Gillen, Dr. Katharina\",\"email\":\"kgillen@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Physics\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Faculty\",\"frost\":\"no\"}]','10:30am-12:00pm,1:00pm-3:00pm',NULL,'2022-04-16 03:42:16',33,'1:00-2:45','1-1:15','180-270'),(125,'d9df8eb395b56c81ce931fba17ccf773','2022','poster','Groundwater Exploration through Subsurface Imaging','Groundwater management in California is imperative to sustainably using the state\'s natural resources. Current groundwater supplies are stressed due to factors such as an increasing population and heightened demand for agriculture. Bartleson Ranch, managed by Cal Poly, has struggled with finding an adequate amount of water to sustain their crops. Through subsurface imaging, the identification and assessment of known geologic features can help us deduce possible locations for groundwater supply. Mapping subsurface geologic structure via the electrical properties of rock, have provided subsurface images that reveal a fault intersecting the property. This fault is thought to have changed the geologic structure of the subsurface over short distances across the ranch, allowing us to identify promising sites for potential ground water wells.','[{\"name\":\"Hillis, Charlie\",\"email\":\"cmhillis@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Other...\",\"other_affiliation\":\"Department of Natural Resources\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"no\"},{\"name\":\"Seibly, Caroline\",\"email\":\"cseibly@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Physics\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"no\"},{\"name\":\"Jasbinsek, John\",\"email\":\"jjasbins@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Physics\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Faculty\",\"frost\":\"no\"}]','','We know how to make one,We can attend April 19, 5-6pm','2022-04-16 03:56:32',80,NULL,NULL,NULL),(126,'a130fbb18d67e315f070be4e5cfe053c','2022','poster','Training Novices to Evaluate Physical Activity Promotion Material Quality: Results of a Pilot Study','Few studies have evaluated the quality of lay physical activity promotion material (PAPM) over time. The purpose of this presentation is to present the results of a training project done to prepare novice coders to reliably evaluate lay material over time, using established methods to critically appraise lay material quality. Three Cal Poly undergraduates were trained in how to use an adapted version of the Suitability Assessment of Materials (SAM) method (Feb.-Aug. 2020), with ENT pre-assigned to evaluate material for the longitudinal study. Using established interpretive cut-points, rater agreement was measured with the intraclass correlation statistic. Between-rater agreement was checked using scores from JDT. Following the training phase with material excluded from the study (written in English), ENT tested his skills further with 16 random PAPM web articles from the longitudinal study (Jul.-Aug. 2020). We observed between-coder agreement was, overall, Excellent (M = .76, LL = .68, UL = .86). Within-coder agreement was Excellent across all SAM categories (M = .96, LL = .92, UL = .99, 3-day grace period). This pilot study demonstrates that a novice coder can learn to code material with a high degree of fidelity. We will discuss our results and practical lessons from the experience. ','[{\"name\":\"Tse, Ethan\",\"email\":\"entse@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Kinesiology and Public Health\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"yes\"},{\"name\":\"Longoria, Savannah\",\"email\":\"salongor@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Kinesiology and Public Health\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"yes\"},{\"name\":\"Christopher, Cameron \",\"email\":\"camic@bu.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Kinesiology and Public Health\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"yes\"},{\"name\":\"Thomas, Jafr\\u0101\",\"email\":\"jthoma84@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Kinesiology and Public Health\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Faculty\",\"frost\":\"yes\"}]','','We can attend April 19, 5-6pm','2022-04-16 04:14:09',81,NULL,NULL,NULL),(127,'693cc7609e5e7030a5e7b784030d0e14','2022','poster','Identification and Characterization of Soil Bacteria with Antimicrobial Activities','Bacterial infections are very common and are becoming increasingly difficult to treat due to widespread antibiotic resistance. Microbial populations from many different types of soil habitats continue to reveal a rich source of novel or poorly understood antimicrobial compounds with therapeutic implications. Nineteen bacterial isolates recovered by students during MCRO 225 in Spring of 2021 from various soil types in San Luis Obispo were evaluated for their spectrum of antimicrobial activities against a panel of 15 potentially susceptible lab strains of bacteria. We performed cross-streak and punch plug antibiotic sensitivity assays to visualize the extent of antimicrobial activities for each of the isolates. Five of these isolates exhibited growth inhibition against susceptible lab strains. Isolates S213, S2113, and S2114 inhibited the growth of Escherichia coli and Pseudomonas fluorescens. S2115 and S2118 produced antimicrobial activity against Citrobacter freundii and Escherichia coli. These isolates will be tentatively identified to species by GEN III Microplate Biolog testing and verified by 16S rRNA gene sequencing, which may provide further insight as to the categories of antimicrobials produced by the isolates. Developing a deeper understanding of the functional activities of compounds produced by soil dwelling bacteria will assist in the discovery of valuable bioactive molecules that can contribute to the solution against our current public health crisis. ','[{\"name\":\"Vredevoe, Larisa\",\"email\":\"lvredevoe@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Biological Sciences\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Faculty\",\"frost\":\"yes\"},{\"name\":\"Fannin, Hailey\",\"email\":\"hfannin@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Biological Sciences\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"yes\"},{\"name\":\"Bantle, Melanie\",\"email\":\"mlbantle@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Biological Sciences\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"yes\"}]','','We can attend April 19, 5-6pm','2022-04-16 05:37:30',82,NULL,NULL,NULL),(128,'48e41d37c164ce4f9befada5697ae182','2022','poster','Mi Gente, Nuestra Salud: A People\'s Movement for Health','\nBackground: Mi Gente, Nuestra Salud is a community based participatory research project. It is based on gathering health asset data within the two cities of Santa Maria and Guadalupe, both socioeconomically and medically underserved in comparison to other California cities.\nPurpose: This study aims to facilitate an understanding of the Santa Maria communitys unique needs and resources with the goal of informing strategies to reduce community health disparities.\nMethods: A survey was used to collect data about Santa Maria residents satisfaction with 40 conditions and services within their community, the questionnaire was subsequently shortened to 15 items to reduce respondent burden. We utilized JMP statistical software to describe the samples demographics and analyze satisfaction scores by income level and gender.  \nFindings: According to preliminary results from the analyses, the items that both short and long form survey respondents were least satisfied with included availability of safe and affordable housing, job availability, as well as the availability and affordability of recreational activity opportunities for residents.\nResults: Findings will inform pathways for policy and community organizing, help build resources to address items that people are the least satisfied with in their community, and to reduce health disparities in Santa Maria and Guadalupe.\n','[{\"name\":\"Gonzalez, Elisa\",\"email\":\"egonz141@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Kinesiology and Public Health\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"no\"},{\"name\":\"Tseng, Marilyn\",\"email\":\"mtseng@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Kinesiology and Public Health\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Faculty\",\"frost\":\"no\"},{\"name\":\"Phelan, Suzanne\",\"email\":\"sphelan@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Kinesiology and Public Health\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Faculty\",\"frost\":\"yes\"},{\"name\":\"Perez, Maritza\",\"email\":\"mpere148@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Kinesiology and Public Health\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"yes\"}]','','We know how to make one','2022-04-16 05:46:43',83,NULL,NULL,NULL),(129,'89d19098a1b508623edea143c0e2458f','2022','poster','Kinetics of Acid-Promoted Rearrangement of 1-Arylbicyclo[3.1.0]hexanes','A series of substituted 1-arylbicyclo[3.1.0]hexanes was subjected to acid-promoted rearrangement. Reaction progress was followed by GC-MS and first-order kinetics were observed for the cyclopropane substrate. Paired competition was used to develop a linear free-energy relationship (LFER) among the derivatives. The main product for each derivative was determined to be the 1-aryl-2-methylcyclopent-1-ene isomer, with small amounts of ring expansion product also observed. The alkene product is also capable of isomerizing and this equilibrium was studied independently by mixing authentic samples under identical conditions.','[{\"name\":\"Blackwell, Thea\",\"email\":\"theablackwell@gmail.com\",\"affiliation\":\"Biological Sciences\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"yes\"},{\"name\":\"Berrios, Meekaela\",\"email\":\"mberri01@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Chemistry and Biochemistry\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"yes\"},{\"name\":\"Russ, Zoe\",\"email\":\"zruss@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Biological Sciences\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"yes\"},{\"name\":\"Smith, Zach\",\"email\":\"\",\"affiliation\":\"Biological Sciences\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"yes\"},{\"name\":\"Wagenblast, Hannah\",\"email\":\"\",\"affiliation\":\"Chemistry and Biochemistry\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"yes\"},{\"name\":\"Zordilla, Madi\",\"email\":\"\",\"affiliation\":\"Biological Sciences\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"yes\"},{\"name\":\"Wax, Sarah\",\"email\":\"\",\"affiliation\":\"Chemistry and Biochemistry\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"yes\"},{\"name\":\"Kantorowski, Eric J.\",\"email\":\"ekantoro@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Biological Sciences\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Faculty\",\"frost\":\"yes\"}]','','We can attend April 19, 5-6pm','2022-04-16 05:58:12',84,NULL,NULL,NULL),(130,'4d6ffcd2e8d05fac98644f589fdd8257','2022','poster','Mi Gente Nuestra Salud People\'s Movement for Health Ownership: Qualitative assessment of community health needs','The Mi Gente, Nuestra Salud (MGNS) initiative aims to mobilize a social movement for community health ownership in the cities of Santa Maria and Guadalupe in Northern Santa Barbara County, CA. Santa Maria and Guadalupe are among Californias poorest and medically underserved regions. Compared with its more affluent neighbors, Santa Maria and Guadalupe suffer disproportionately from nearly every chronic disease, including obesity, diabetes, cancer, stroke, and heart, respiratory, and rheumatoid diseases. \n\nThe purpose of this substudy is to collect qualitative data to understand the health needs and resources in Santa Maria and Guadalupe. Recruitment was conducted at various locations throughout the area, such as Food Banks, public parks, and frequented grocery stores such as Walmart/Vallarta Supermarkets. We sought diverse populations through this strategy, such as farm laborers, those with low health literacy, and pregnant women. Focus groups were conducted outside and in-depth interviews over the phone due to COVID-19 precautions. 10 participants from Santa Maria and Guadalupe participated in focus groups (n=10) and in-depth interviews (n=17). Data collected from these interviews are being transcribed utilizing AWS transcription service. Transcripts are then reviewed by research assistants to ensure accuracy. Data in English will translate into Spanish and analyzed with NVIVO to identify themes that pertain to the perceived health needs and assets of the community. This data will be analyzed in conjunction with survey data. This information will inform the community of potential pathways to address health needs and bolster resources.','[{\"name\":\"Perez, maritza\",\"email\":\"Mpere148@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Kinesiology and Public Health\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"no\"},{\"name\":\"Phelan, Suzanne \",\"email\":\"Sphelan@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Kinesiology and Public Health\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Faculty\",\"frost\":\"no\"}]','','We can attend April 19, 5-6pm','2022-04-16 14:52:11',85,NULL,NULL,NULL),(132,'898511bb7656f5e71b3fdf2487c77226','2022','talk','Sea Otters: May the Buoyant Force be with Them','Buoyancy in marine mammals is crucial for survival in the aquatic environment and can vary across species. In sea otters, the air layer trapped in the dense pelage is important for both thermoregulation and buoyancy, allowing the animals to float effortlessly at the surface. Past studies have investigated the buoyancy of adult otters, but none have examined buoyancy changes throughout development. In this study, we investigated possible changes in buoyancy as otters age, as well as the effects of crude oil on the buoyancy of otter pelts. We hypothesized that lanugo (neonatal) otter pelts would be more buoyant, as it is known that pups cannot dive for their first months of life. Using an underwater scale, we measured buoyancy for sea otter pelts (n=38) across 6 age classes. We calculated the buoyant force of pelts under normal conditions, after applying crude oil, and after washing with Dawn(C). We found no difference in pelt buoyant force across age classes (p=0.0825). However, buoyant forces were significantly higher in control pelts compared to oiled and washed pelts for all ages (p<0.0001). A possible explanation for this is that crude oil disturbs the air layer and reduces the insulative and buoyant properties of the fur. Additionally, Dawn(C) may remove natural oils from the fur that aid in buoyancy. This suggests the buoyancy of the fur is not what prohibits pups from diving, but there are other variables at play. This study represents the first step towards understanding buoyancy during ontogeny for otters and provides insight into how contaminants affect pelage functionality.','[{\"name\":\"Dean, Annika\",\"email\":\"edean@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Biological Sciences\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"yes\",\"presenter\":\"yes\"},{\"name\":\"Riordan, Kate\",\"email\":\"kriord01@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Biological Sciences\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"yes\"},{\"name\":\"Levin, Emily\",\"email\":\"elevin02@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Biological Sciences\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"yes\"},{\"name\":\"Thompson, Alex\",\"email\":\"athomp52@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Biological Sciences\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"yes\"},{\"name\":\"Liwanag, Heather\",\"email\":\"hliwanag@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Biological Sciences\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Faculty\",\"frost\":\"yes\"}]','1:00pm-3:00pm',NULL,'2022-04-19 05:13:39',37,'1:00-2:45','2-2:15','180-270'),(133,'53bc90146696f447ebee4c4016e8b28e','2022','talk','Part II: [[In vitro]] Analysis of the Interaction Between Phosphomimetic Mutants of Human YB-1 protein and the HIV Gag protein','Human immunodeficiency virus (HIV) affects millions of people worldwide and current issues like the Covid-19 pandemic and climate change are predicted to increase the spread of this virus. YB-1, a human RNA binding protein, is involved in RNA loading of extracellular vesicles and has been implicated in successful assembly of retroviral progeny. In human tissue culture, post-translational phosphorylation of YB-1 has been implicated as a requirement for the protein\'s activity in a variety of published assays, but the effect of these modifications on HIV assembly is unknown. To examine if phosphorylation affects interactions between YB-1 and the HIV capsid protein Gag, phosphomimetic forms of YB-1, where phosphorylated serine residues (S) are mimicked by replacing them with aspartate (D) residues, were constructed. Previous work in the lab has generated eight expression constructs with the following versions of the YBX1 gene (encoding YB-1 protein): wild type, S102D, S165D, S176D, S102D+S165D, S102D+S176D, S165D+S176D, and S102D+S165D+S176D. Each of these YB-1 versions and the HIV Gag coding region were cloned into bacterial expression vectors for expression and purification of the proteins. To evaluate the interaction between YB-1 and Gag, co-immunoprecipitation was performed [[in vitro]] in the presence or absence of HIV genomic RNA. Results will be provided that show only certain phosphomimetic versions of YB-1 interact with HIV Gag, suggesting that particular residues in YB-1 may require post-translational modification for the protein to participate in HIV assembly.','[{\"name\":\"Peter-Contesse, Sierra\",\"email\":\"speterco@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Biological Sciences\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"no\"},{\"name\":\"Geitner, David\",\"email\":\"dgeitner@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Biological Sciences\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"no\"},{\"name\":\"Gopan, Vinay\",\"email\":\"vgopan@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Biological Sciences\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Student\",\"frost\":\"no\"},{\"name\":\"Black, Michael \",\"email\":\"mblack@calpoly.edu\",\"affiliation\":\"Biological Sciences\",\"other_affiliation\":\"\",\"role\":\"Faculty\",\"frost\":\"no\"}]','1:00pm-3:00pm',NULL,'2022-04-19 16:11:16',39,'1:00-2:45','2:30-2:45','180-270');
